<FIRST>r i PM-Romania-Destruction     02-27 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Romania-Destruction,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalist Smuggles Out Film Of Village Eradication</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British journalist says she and a colleague were
arrested four times for clandestinely filming rural areas of Romania
wrecked by President Nicolae Ceausescu's agricultural modernization
scheme.
   Sue Lloyd-Roberts said she managed to save her videocassettes
from confiscation by hiding them in her underwear whenever she was
arrested and handing authorities footage of home movies the two had
brought along.
   She and colleague Vivian Roberts overcame stringent restrictions
on foreign news coverage by entering the East bloc country posing as
tourists, she said.
   Her footage, broadcast on Independent Television News, showed
empty, brick-strewn fields where three villages had stood until last
fall, and a signpost with its place name replaced.
   These villages appeared on older maps which were already
unobtainable in Romania, Ms. Lloyd-Roberts said.
   An unidentified peasant woman was shown describing what had
happened: ``We worked all our lives. They destroyed everyone's home.
My house was knocked to the ground. They've made us live in new
blocks. Everything is wretched and miserable. What can be done?''
   The report said people spoke of villagers being killed resisting
militiamen who evicted them from their homes on 24 hours notice.
   The demolitions are part of Ceausescu's plan to raze up to 7,000
of Romania's 13,000 villages and resettle the population in
so-called agro-industrial centers.
   ``Ceausescu wants to create his `Communist Man,' and he has to
destroy the Romanian village because that's where the opposition to
communism is total,'' Ion Rativ, a Romanian emigre leader in London,
told ITN.
   In Bucharest, the capital, Ms. Lloyd-Roberts also filmed areas
demolished to make way for a vast palace Ceausescu is building for
himself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
