<FIRST>r w PM-AP-BureauChief     02-27 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP-Bureau Chief,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>AP Names Bureau Chief In Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jonathan P. Wolman, assistant bureau chief of
The Associated Press' Washington bureau for the past five years, has
been promoted to bureau chief, AP President Louis D. Boccardi has
announced.
   Wolman will direct the AP's news operations in the capital. He
succeeds Charles J. Lewis, who is joining Hearst Newspapers as
Washington bureau chief.
   Boccardi made the announcement Monday.
   Wolman, 38, joined the AP in Detroit in 1973. He became news
editor for Michigan in 1975, then moved to Washington in 1976 as a
member of a team specializing in coverage of urban problems.
   In 1981, he became a Washington news editor. He was promoted to
assistant bureau chief in September 1984.
   He is a graduate of the University of Wisconsin and a native of
Madison.
</TEXT>
