<FIRST>r a AM-ArtTheftProbe     02-27 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Art Theft Probe,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Police Chief's Son Charged in Art Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of a former city police chief has been
charged in a federal investigation of an alleged $3 million
art-theft ring centered in Cincinnati, federal authorities said
Monday.
   Jacob W. Schott Jr., 48, of the Cincinnati suburb of Wyoming was
arraigned Monday before U.S. Magistrate Robert Steinberg on a charge
of interstate transportation of stolen property.
   Schott, the third person to be charged in the case, filed notice
he would plead guilty to the charge in a plea bargain with federal
prosecutors.
   Schott agreed to cooperate with federal authorities and testify
against Teddy R. Rudder, an alleged member of the art-theft ring
already charged in the case, said Assistant U.S. Attorney John
DiPuccio.
   In exchange, federal authorities agreed not to file additional
charges against Schott, who was released on his own recognizance,
DiPuccio said.
   Schott is the son of the late Jacob W. Schott, who was Cincinnati
police chief from 1967 to 1970.
   He is accused of transporting an $80,000 painting stolen from a
Cincinnati house in February 1988 to Indianapolis, where is it was
sold to an art dealer, FBI agent Edward Boldt said.
   The oil painting by Edward Potthast, ``Women on Beach-Women in
Water,'' was later sold to a Santa Fe, N.M., art dealer. The Santa
Fe dealer saw the work listed in a bulletin on stolen art, and
reported it to the FBI, Boldt said.
   The charge against Schott carries a maximum sentence of 10 years
in prisona and $250,00 fine on conviction.
   The ring is accused of stealing items with an estimated worth of
$3 million from Cincinnati area homes, DiPuccio said.
   The FBI estimates it has recovered more than $500,000 worth of
items, most of them art objects.
   Rudder, 42, of Columbus, was arrested Feb. 7 and is jailed
without bond while his case is pending before a federal grand jury,
DiPuccio said.
   Rudder is charged with conspiracy to transport stolen property
interstate, and is charged with interstate travel to commit an arson
in an unrelated case, DiPuccio said.
   Federal authorities also have arrested Jerry Mulholland of
Cincinnati in the art-theft case.
   Mulholland, who is out on bond, is charged with an unrelated
count of possession with intent to distribute cocaine, DiPuccio said.
   Federal authorities said they anticipate more arrests.
</TEXT>
