<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--ChineseOut     02-27 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Chinese Out,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Businessmen Ordered To Leave South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Ministry has refused to
extend the visas of eight Chinese businessmen who have been trying
to gain a foothold for their operations in South Korea, press
reports say.
   The eight include Hong Cheong Tak, vice chairman of China
Liaoning Ltd., a Hong Kong-based trade arm of China's Liaoning
province, the South Korean news agency Yonhap reported Sunday.
   The agency said the ministry ordered the businessmen, who arrived
in December seeking to open company branches in Seoul, to leave by
March 2.
   Yonhap said the move indicates South Korea does not want Chinese
companies to open branches in the country on a long-term basis,
given that Seoul and Beijing have no formal diplomatic relations.
   South Korean businessmen are not allowed to stay in Beijing more
than three months, and China prevents South Korean firms from
opening branches there.
   China has promoted economic exchanges with South Korea in recent
years but has been reluctant to upgrade such relations, apparently
due to its ties with communist North Korea.
</TEXT>
