<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 0051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Sikhs     02-27 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Sikhs,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Gunmen Kill Family of Three, Two Policemen Slain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant Sikh separatists shot and killed
a Sikh farmer and his two sons and two policemen in separate attacks
in Punjab state, police and news reports said today.
   Five gunmen raided the home of Banta Singh in Gagubhua village in
Amritsar district late Sunday and fatally shot Singh and his sons at
point-blank range after separating them from the women in the
family, said area police chief Sanjeev Gupta.
   Sikhs militants who are campaigning for an independent homeland
in India's north often pick moderate Sikhs as their targets.
   Moderate Sikhs want greater political autonomny for their rich
farming state but refuse to endorse the radicals' demand for
secession.
   United News of India said two policemen were shot and killed late
Sunday night by Sikh militants in the village of Deffarwal in
Hoshiarpur district.
   The latest slayings brought the total number of deaths blamed on
Sikh militants in Punjab to at least 325 this year.
   Last year, at least 2,440 deaths were blamed on the extremists.
   Sikhs, who make up about two percent of India's 880 million
people, say they are discriminated by Hindus, the country's
religious majority accounting for about 82 percent of its people.
   Sikhs comprise a slight majority in Punjab state.
</TEXT>
