<DOCNO> AP890227-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 0023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-RailroadExplosion 2ndLd-Writethru a0810 02-27 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Railroad Explosion, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0810,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Cars Explode; Thousands Evacuated</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with quotes from fire chief, CSX spokesman,
more specific numbers of cars involved and later information on their contents;
DELETES outdated material; ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHUCK MELVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train derailment caused an explosion and
fire involving four tanker cars, forcing the evacuation of thousands
of people from a residential and industrial area near downtown
Sunday night, authorities said.
   No injuries were immediately reported.
   The burning cars were among 17 that derailed from a CSX
Transportation train at the B.F. Goodrich Chemical plant, said Akron
Fire Chief George Romanoski.
   Nine of the cars carried highly flammable butane, CSX spokesman
Lloyd Lewis said by telephone from Jacksonville, Fla. The eight
other cars carried non-hazardous materials including vegetable oil,
clay and sand, he said.
   Allan Franks, a spokesman for the Ohio Environmental Protection
Agency said one of the cars contained butadiene, which may produce
hazardous smoke when burned, but Lewis said the petroleum derivative
was not in any of the derailed cars.
   Romanoski said fires in three of the cars and been put out and
one car was still burning late Sunday night. Firefighters had
planned to allow the fourth car to burn itself out. The accident
occurred about 7:30 p.m., authorities said.
   Firefighters ran hoses up to the train to spread water on
adjoining cars to cool them and diminish the possibility they would
explode, he said.
   ``The area was evacuated because of the danger of explosion in
the surrounding tank cars,'' Romanoski said.
   At least 1,500 homes in an area within one-half mile of the plant
were evacuated, but the number of evacuees was not immediately
available, Mayor Don Plusquilic said.
   The evacuees were taken by bus to a high school and to the
University of Akron's Memorial Hall, said Scott Swearengin, the
county emergency management coordinator.
   Romanoski said people would not be allowed to return to their
homes until the fire was extinguished. He said he did not know when
that would be, ``but just as a yardstick, we're saying `plan on
being there overnight at least,''' he said.
   The train was not making a stop at the Goodrich plant, but was
using its tracks to pass through the area, said Mike Fletcher, plant
manager.
   The train, which had a total of 45 cars, was en route from
Willard, Ohio, to Akron and back to Willard, Lewis said. He did not
know where the train's next stop was scheduled. He said the train
carried a crew of three or four, and that no crew members were
injured.
   Lewis said investigators from CSX would arrive in Akron early
Monday morning. No cause for the accident had been determined Sunday
night, he said.
   Witnesses said flames from the burning tankers could be seen for
miles.
   Akron-area hospitals reported no injuries four hours after the
explosion, but some area residents reported feeling nauseated.
</TEXT>
