<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 3rdLd-Writethru a0402 02-27 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0402,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Duarte Makes Counterproposal To Rebel Peace Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with eight grafs to CLARIFY that Duarte saying that
referendum proposed if talks with rebels prove inconculsive. Picks up 7th
pvs, `Duarte said ...' ^BY ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
on Sunday called for a cease-fire and peace talks with leftist
rebels, who have offered to take part in national elections set for
March if the vote is postponed.
   Duarte said on nationwide television and radio that if the talks
prove inconclusive on the postponement issue, he favors resolving it
with a referendum.
   The president proposed that the U.S.-backed government and the
rebel Farabundo Marti Liberation Front ``unilaterally cease
hostilities between Feb. 28 and June 1'' and begin peace talks
Tuesday in Guatemala.
   The rebels offered on Jan. 24 to take part in elections _ and
recognize the results _ if the vote were postponed from March 19
until September, and if their security is guaranteed and electoral
changes are made to ensure a fair vote.
   In an unprecedented meeting in Mexico last week, they told
Salvadoran political leaders that they would lay down their arms if
the election were postponed at least four months, the armed forces
sharply reduced and the police reorganized. They also proposed
direct talks with Duarte.
   There was no immediate rebel reaction to Duarte's comments Sunday.
   In his speech, Duarte suggested that the guerrillas be
incorporated into Salvadoran society and politics and that the
Salvadorn armed forces be recognized as the only army in the country.
   He did not refer directly to the guerrilla proposal, but he said
he would propose that the presidential balloting be postponed until
April 30. He did not specify when a plebiscite might take place.
   Duarte said the delegation to peace talks would include
representatives from the legislature, which is dominated by the
right-wing National Republican Alliance, and the 13 political
parties.
   He did not say whether he would participate in the talks or name
a representative.
   He also did not explain why he suddenly changed his position of
strongly opposing any delay in the elections.
   Proposing the referendum, Duarte said sovereignty rests with the
Salvadoran people and for this reason a ``solution is possible
through consulting the people.''
   He said another way to postpone elections legally would be for
the executive, legislative and judicial branches of the government
to all agree on a legal mechanism to bring about a postponement.
   He implied the presidential polling could not be postponed beyond
April 30.
   Duarte and the armed forces have been saying that a delay in the
vote would be unconstitutional and military leaders have suggested
publicly they may take over if the vote did not go on as scheduled.
   El Salvador's constitution specifies that a new president is to
take office on June 1.
   Duarte initially said he would let the political parties decide
on the matter. Last Monday and Tuesday, a delegation of Salvadoran
political leaders met in Mexico with rebel leaders.
   The meetings were cordial but ended without any agreement.
   The guerrillas contend that the politicial parties are hiding
behind the constitution to avoid substantive talks.
   More than 70,000 people, most of them civilians, have died in
9-year-old war between the government and the leftist rebels.
   The guerrillas have steadfastly rejected the five national
elections this decade as part of a U.S.-backed counterinsurgency
campaign.
   Duarte said in his speech Sunday it was necessary to initiate ``a
new search to put an end to the armed conflict that is covering our
country with blood.''
   He also said he had no personal ambitions in the matter: ``I beg
of God that he lets our people find peace.''
</TEXT>
