<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   02-27 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0807,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares, Dollar Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with closing Nikkei, dollar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After rising during the morning session, share
prices fell back in afternoon trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
Monday, while the dollar finished lower against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 126.00 yen, down 0.29 yen from its
126.29-yen finish on Thursday. After opening at 125.90 yen, the U.S.
currency ranged between 125.75 and 126.02 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which hit a new
high by gaining 56.70 points in the morning session, ended the day
down 166.72 points, or 0.51 percent, at 32,285.77. The index had
gained 140.56 points for a record 32,452.49-point closing on
Thursday.
   Japanese financial markets were closed Friday because of the
state funeral of Emperor Hirohito.
   Dealers said the Nikkei index fell because of profit taking.
   In currency dealings, the dollar's low opening followed its
weakness in Friday's New York trading, despite the Federal Reserve
action to raise its discount rate, dealers said.
   The Fed's rate hike dissappointed New York financial markets
because American market players had hoped it would go further than a
half-percentage-point hike, said foreign exchange traders. The move
was also seen as coming too late.
   Tokyo foreign exchange dealers were unimpressed as well. Traders
said that a rate hike had been expected, and was fully discounted.
   Higher U.S. interest rates tend to make the dollar more
attractive to foreign investors, but Friday's U.S. interest rate
hike did not lead Japanese market players to the dollar-buying, said
one dealer with a commercial bank in Tokyo.
   Meanwhile, Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama indicated
Monday that there is no need for Japan to follow the U.S. discount
rate hike with a rate hike of its own, Kyodo News Service reported.
</TEXT>
