<FIRST>r i PM-China-JobSeekers     02-27 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Job Seekers,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Province Awash in Job Seekers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A governor says forcible repatriation may be
necessary to stem a tide of job-seekers who have been left stranded
and homeless by the thousands in his southern China province, an
official report said today.
   Governor Ye Xuanping of Guangdong province described the
situation as a ``labor wave washing in from surrounding provinces,''
the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   He has told all cities and counties in the province to form teams
to try to persuade new arrivals to go home, the report said.
   China's migrant workers, estimated as high as 20 million, are a
by-product of the nation's easing of travel restrictions and its
market-oriented reforms, which have encouraged labor mobility.
   Guangdong, located next to Hong Kong and one of China's most
prosperous provinces, is the main Chinese mecca for urban
job-seekers.
   However, Shanghai also is reported to have a ``floating
population'' of 2 million, and more than 1 million non-residents are
temporarily staying in Beijing.
   Today's report said more than 2.5 million people have poured into
Guangdong looking for work since the Lunar New Year holiday ended
two weeks ago.
   Governor Ye was quoted as saying forced repatriation might be
necessary. He ordered all government and private enterprises to
immediately stop hiring new arrivals from other provinces.
   The agency said thousands of people are sleeping at railway
stations, wharves or on the street, mainly in the provincial capital
of Canton.
   Hundreds of thousands more are arriving every day or waiting at
train stations in other provinces for passage to Guangdong, the
report said.
   Transport and hygiene have been strained to the limit, crime is
up, and begging is expected to rise, the report said.
   Some of the jobless new arrivals are trying to make a living by
picking up trash in the streets, the agency said.
</TEXT>
