<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan-Blast     02-27 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Blast,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Blast Kills Guard, Police Officer Sees Link to Rushdie Furor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blast killed a guard outside a
British cultural center, and a police officer linked the attack to
Moslem protests over British author Salman Rushdie's novel ``The
Satanic Verses.''
   The two-pound bomb exploded Sunday night while the city's
British-run library was closed, police said on condition of
anonymity.
   It killed 65-year-old guard Mohammad Shafi, demolished the
building's guard room and damaged the outside wall.
   Police had earlier said the building housed the British
Consulate, but British diplomats said those offices are elsewhere.
   Asked whether the blast was connected to the furor over Rushdie's
novel, one officer said, ``It appears that way.''
   Many Moslems are outraged by Rushdie's novel, which they say
blasphemes their religion, and Moslem countries including Pakistan
have banned it.
   Six people died and scores more were injured when a mob attacked
an American cultural center Feb. 12 in the capital, Islamabad, to
demand that the United States ban the book.
   Two days later, Iran's fundamentalist leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini called on Moslems to seek out and kill Rushdie and his
publishers. Iranian clerics have posted a bounty of $5.2 million for
Rushdie's head.
   The author, who was born to a Moslem family in India, is in
hiding.
