<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneEmergency-Survivor     02-27 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Emergency-Survivor,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Survived By Switching Seats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Plane Emergency, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HU8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines Flight 811 passenger says he
cheated death by switching seats in the jumbo jet shortly before a
huge chunk of the fuselage tore off in flight, sweeping nine people
to their deaths.
   ``That really saved my life. I think I ended up with the safest
seat on the whole plane,'' said William Van Rij, 70, of
Christchurch, New Zealand.
   Van Rij, a dairy industry consultant, said he usually travels
business class, and likes to sit in the upper deck.
   He said he could not get an upper deck seat on the United
Airlines flight from Los Angeles, but was told to check in early at
Honolulu International Airport before Friday's flight to New Zealand
to switch from the main deck.
   Van Rij said he was given a window seat on the left side of the
upper deck of the Boeing 747-400.
   About 45 minutes into the flight, he said, ``we heard this loud
bang and then it was like a huge storm. The noise was really
tremendous. ...
   ``Pieces of the cabin were flying around. It's very hard to
describe. I'm sure I wold have died in that other seat.''
   Van Rij said he didn't realize until the plane returned safely to
Honolulu about 15 minutes later that a huge hole had been ripped in
the right side, and that the nine people sucked out of the plane had
been sitting in business class on the main deck.
   As the plane descended toward Honolulu, Van Rij said he thought
of the hundreds who died aboard the Titanic, then prayed and
remembered the words to the hymn ``Nearer My God To Thee.''
   ``We all thought that was the finish. You don't handle those
things yourself. You rely on God,'' he said.
   Twenty-seven others were hospitalized, although all but Van Rij
and two others, were released by Sunday.
   Van Rij, who said he underwent heart bypass surgery several years
ago, was hospitalized at the Queen's Medical Center for observation
after suffering chest pain.
   Van Rij's wife, Adrian, 69, flew to Honolulu on Saturday. He said
their six children have been checking on him by telephone.
   Although he marveled at his luck, another man who tried to get a
seat on the upper deck was not so lucky, Van Rij said.
   Two people claimed to have a boarding pass for the same seat, and
after an argument, one went downstairs to the main deck, Van Rij
said.
   Without knowing the passenger's name, United Airlines said it
could not confirm his fate.
   Van Rij said he is not afraid to fly again, even though this is
his second near miss.
   In 1948, he was supposed to fly to Atlantic City, N.J., for a
dairy products exhibition but became ill and could not travel.
   The flight he had booked crashed, killing everyone aboard, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890227-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 0508EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0799 02-27 1162</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0799,1180</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Brilliant Cavalcade of Broadway Dances in `Jerome Robbins' Broadway'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs with other New York reviews. No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-five years ago when dancing rather than
complicated, computerized scenery was the stuff that made musicals
move, Jerome Robbins was the king of Broadway.
   Now the king has come back to reclaim his throne with ``Jerome
Robbins' Broadway,'' a dazzling retrospective of dances and other
numbers from the musicals he helped bring to life from 1944 to 1964.
That list includes such classics as ``West Side Story,'' ``Gypsy,''
``Fiddler on the Roof,'' ``The King and I,'' ``Peter Pan'' and ``On
the Town.''
   The production, which opened Sunday at Broadway's Imperial
Theater, is not a revival. It's a brilliant distillation of the
past, reconstructed and rethought with the utmost precision and care
by Robbins and a team of assistants that includes such veteran
Broadway dancers as Grover Dale, Cynthia Onrubia and Jerry Mitchell.
   Robbins and his cast of 62 dancers demonstrate why the musical,
particularly the American musical, was, and still can be,
exhilarating. There's nothing else quite like it _ Peter Pan soaring
over the rooftops of London, the swagger and shock of the Sharks and
Jets crossing switchblades, Tevye expounding on the importance of
``Tradition'' or a dizzy Charleston that has flappers falling to the
floor and still continuing to dance.
   All are part of ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' but the evening
opens sentimentally with a trio of numbers from ``On the Town,''
Robbins' first show.
   ``On the Town'' tells the story of three sailors out on a 24-hour
spree in World War II New York. But it's a story told not only
through dialogue and song but through dance, too. It combines
elements of ballet with the brash, brassy and confident style of
popular dance.
   It's a technique that Robbins perfected more than a decade later
in ``West Side Story.'' For ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,'' he has put
together a 30-minute suite of dances from this Leonard
Bernstein-Stephen Sondheim musical, and it is the emotional and
physical heart of the show.
   Comprised of sections from ``The Prologue,'' ``The Rumble,''
``Cool,'' ``America,'' ``The Dance Hall'' and ``Somewhere,'' the
suite compresses the entire modern-day story of Romeo and Juliet
into quite simply the best choreography now on Broadway. And the
dancers attack it with a ferocity that is astounding. There is an
unnerving, on-the-edge menace to their work. When the rival Sharks
and Jets square off, the feeling is electric. The audience gasps
when Bernardo knifes Riff, and the hero Tony inevitably gets drawn
into the tragedy.
   The ``West Side Story'' suite features ensemble dancing at its
very best, but special praise must go to Scott Wise as the cocky
Riff, Nicholas Garr who is a murderous Bernardo and Robert La Fosse
as a poignant, even poetic Tony.
   Another side to Robbins also is revealed in this show. The man
can be funny, not above using a pratfall, a bawdy joke or just plain
corn to get a laugh. All of those elements come together in ``Comedy
Tonight,'' the opening number of the 1962 musical ``A Funny Thing
Happened on the Way to the Forum.''
   Robbins devised it when ``Forum'' was in trouble out of town. The
song's humor set the tone for the entire musical and helped make it
a hit in New York. The number gets just as many laughs now with
Jason Alexander playing the Zero Mostel role.
   Alexander, a pudgy-faced performer, serves as narrator for
``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' as well as an occasional participant in
the proceedings. Whether soft-shoeing his way through ``I Still Get
Jealous,'' a beguiling Jule Styne melody from ``High Button Shoes,''
or playing Tevye in ``Fiddler on the Roof,'' Alexander has all the
right moves.
   Robbins has constructed the show so it starts slowly, building to
the powerful ``West Side Story'' segment at the end of the first
act. But the pace doesn't let up in Act 2.
   Robbins begins the second act with ``The Small House of Uncle
Thomas,'' the charming ballet retelling of ``Uncle Tom's Cabin''
from ``The King and I.'' East meets West, and Robbins is the
interpreter, blending Oriental dance technique with Broadway
razzle-dazzle. The original setting, designed by Jo Mielziner, and
the striking and colorful Siamese costumes by Irene Sharaff, turn it
into the most visually stunning of the production numbers.
   What makes Robbins so special is the scope of his inventiveness.
He can go from the king of Siam to the queen of burlesque without
missing a beat. He follows ``Uncle Thomas'' with ``You Gotta Have a
Gimmick,'' the hilarious advice given by three strippers to Baby
Louise, the young performer who eventually peels down to become
Gypsy Rose Lee.
   Then he stops everything with ``On a Sunday by the Sea'' from
``High Button Shoes.'' It's a dizzy, raucous ballet involving a bag
of stolen money, a chorus line of bathing beauties, Keystone Kops,
two sets of identical twins and even a gorilla. The action never
stops and neither does the laughter.
   There's a double edge to the joy of ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway.''
If the musical celebrates the past, it also shows up the paucity of
the present.
   Choreography has disappeared on Broadway today. Can anybody
remember the dancing in ``The Phantom of the Opera,'' ``Les
Miserables,'' ``The Mystery of Edwin Drood'' and ``Big River,'' the
last four Tony award-winning musicals?
   With the deaths of Michael Bennett, Bob Fosse and Gower Champion,
Robbins is the last of the great Broadway choreographers. The best
news about his latest show is that the man may be working on a new
theatrical work. Judging from the riches to be found in ``Jerome
Robbins' Broadway,'' let's hope the rumor is true.
   In other New York reviews: Frank Rich writes in The New York
Times: ``While `Jerome Robbins's Broadway' may celebrate a vanished
musical theater, it does so with such youthful exuberance that
nostalgia finally gives way to a giddy, perhaps not even foolish,
dream that a new generation of Broadway babies may yet be born.''
   Howard Kissel writes in the Daily News: ``The evening pays
tribute to an ego that is apparently as huge as the talent behind it
... From the tone of the show you would never know musical theater
was about collaboration.'' But, he adds, ``Robbins' Broadway is
inseparable from the Broadway, the New York I imagined growing up in
Milwaukee. I want this show to run and run and run to remind me that
the greatness I imagined back then was indeed a reality.''
   Clive Barnes in the New York Post also notes that ``those same
musicals were among Broadway's finest, not solely on the basis of
the Robbins choreography and direction.'' But, he says, the show
``is magnificent _ a musical of musicals that is all dancing, all
music, and all feeling, revealing Robbins again as Broadway's once
and future king.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
