<FIRST>r a PM-AbandonedMarine     02-27 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abandoned Marine,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Process Begins For Officer Charged In Abandoned Marine Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An officer charged in the death of a
Marine corporal who was abandoned in the desert has been convicted
of disobeying an order, sentenced to four months in the brig and
dismissed from the Corps.
   First Lt. Allen Lawson, 25, was sentenced Saturday in the death
last year of Lance Cpl. Jason Rother, 19, of Minneapolis, who was
left in the Mojave desert when maneuvers ended. Rother was not
reported missing for nearly two days.
   Search teams found only his equipment and an arrow made of stones
at his post, and his remains were discovered Dec. 4.
   A military jury of eight officers found Lawson disobeyed an order
to post road guides in pairs and to submit a list of the guides to
the officer charged with picking up the Marines.
   He was found innocent of the more serious charge of willfully
disobeying the order.
   Several officers in Rother's battalion were reassigned after a
Marine investigation of the incident, and two sergeants who were
Rother's immediate superiors were convicted by a court-martial and
reduced in rank.
   No further charges were expected.
   The conviction will be reviewed by Major Gen. O.K. Steele, the
commanding general of the 2nd Marine Division who convened the
court-martial.
</TEXT>
