<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Eldridge     02-27 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Eldridge,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jazz Great Roy Eldridge Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Eldridge, one of the great innovators of the
jazz trumpet who gained prominence with Gene Krupa's band and later
toured with Benny Goodman, has died at age 78.
   Eldridge died Sunday at Franklin General Hospital in Valley
Stream. No cause of death was given. His wife, Viola, died three
weeks ago. They had been married 53 years.
   Fellow jazz trumpeter Jon Faddis said Eldridge was ``one of the
most exciting'' jazz trumpeters.
   ``One mistake that experts make is to say that he was the `link'
between Louis Armstrong and Dizzy Gillespie, but he was much more.
He was a giant in his own right,'' Faddis said.
   A native of Pittsburgh, Eldridge came to New York City in 1930
and played in Cecil Scott's band and later with Teddy Hill and
Connie's Hot Chocolates.
   He gained national attention when he was the featured trumpeter
and singer with Krupa's band from 1941 to 1943, becoming one of the
first black jazz musicians to be a permanent member of the brass
section of a white band.
   After leaving Krupa's band, he joined Norman Granz's Jazz at the
New York Philharmonic.
   When he left the Artie Shaw band in 1945, Eldridge complained
angrily about the many racial incidents he endured while playing
with the band. He vowed he would never play with a white band again,
although he did later.
   He gained star status in Europe, especially France, when in 1950
he toured with Goodman's sextet.
   He returned to the United States in 1951 and often appeared with
groups that featured such luminaries as Ella Fitzgerald, Johnny
Hodges and Coleman Hawkins.
   Eldridge is survived by a daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890227-0049 </DOCNO>
