<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-27 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Scattered In Central And Eastern United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell from Kansas and eastern Nebraska across Missouri into
western Kentucky early today, and rain fell to the south over
Arkansas and the Tennessee Valley.
   Southeast Missouri had between 3 and 6 inches of snow Sunday
night and a few other areas had higher accumulations, including 9
inches in Rolla. In Nebraska, 4 inches fell at Sidney and Kimbell, 3
inches at McCook and Scottsbluff and 1 inch at North Platte.
   Snow was fell across eastern Ohio and the central Appalachians.
The heaviest snow, between 6 and 9 inches, was expected in western
Maryland's mountains. Snow was forecast for the mountains of western
North Carolina.
   Low pressure off New England brought snow from northern New
Jersey to New Hampshire.
   Cold air moving across the warmer waters of the Great Lakes
produced lake-effect snow over the Lake Michigan shorelines in lower
Michigan and the Lake Superior shore areas of Upper Michigan and
northwest Wisconsin. Iron County, Wis., had 9 inches.
   Northern Montana and western North Dakota were receiving light
snow. A winter storm watch was posted for mountains and passes of
northwest Montana.
   Today's forecast called for snow in New England, across New York
state to the central Appalachians, and in the upper Mississippi
Valley to the northern Plains into the northern Rockies. Rain was
expected in the lower Mississippi Valley, the central Gulf Coast
region, the Tennessee Valley and the southern Atlantic Coast states.
Strong winds were forecast from Idaho to Wyoming and in southern
Texas.
   Predicted high temperatures: teens and 20s from eastern Montana
across North Dakota, eastern South Dakota, the upper Mississippi
Valley, the Great Lakes and the northern Appalachians to northern
New England; 30s and 40s from southern New England and the middle
Atlantic Coast across the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley,
Missouri and Arkansas, the central Plains, Oklahoma, western South
Dakota, northern and central Rockies and to the Washington coast;
50s and 60s from South Carolina and Georgia across central
Mississippi, northern Louisiana, southern Arkansas, northern Texas
across the southern Rockies to the Pacific Coast; 70s from Florida
across the Gulf Coast region; 70s and 80s from the southern Texas
across the southern Plateau to southern California.
   The temperature dropped to 47 degrees at Key West, Fla., early
today, breaking the low temperature record for the date of 51
degrees set in 1986.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from minus 21
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 73 degrees at Imperial, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 53 rain; Boston 26 snow; Buffalo 22 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 51 fair; Cincinnati 26 cloudy; Cleveland 27 snow;
Detroit 23 cloudy; Miami 52 fair; New York 34 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 32 fair; Pittsburgh 25 snow; Portland, Maine 20 snow;
Washington 37 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 10 snow; Chicago 19 snow; Denver 29 freezing
drizzle; Des Moines 15 fair; Indianapolis 22 snow; Kansas City 19
partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 04 fair; Nashville 33 snow; New
Orleans 52 fair; St. Louis 28 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 52 partly cloudy; Anchorage 22 partly cloudy;
Las Vegas 63 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 56 partly cloudy; Phoenix 65
fair; Salt Lake City 33 fair; San Diego 57 fair; San Francisco 48
fair; Seattle 37 foggy.
   _Canada: Montreal 07 partly cloudy; Toronto 21 snow.
</TEXT>
