<SECOND>PM-Verses-Bomb,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Killed By Bomb During Rushdie Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today at a demonstration
in a northern city protesting ``The Satanic Verses,'' killing one
person and injuring seven, a news report said.
   The demonstrators in Srinagar, Jammu-Kashmir state, were trying
to enforce a general strike to protest Friday's police gunfire
during rioting over the novel, which many Moslems consider
blasphemous, according to the Press Trust of India news agency.
   Nine people were shot and killed Friday.
   The Srinagar bomb was intended for police officers trying stop
demonstrators from closing Srinagar shops, Press Trust said, but
killed a Moslem civilian instead.
   One police officer and two news photographers were among the
injured, the agency added.
   There have been several protests against Salman Rushdie's novel
in India, especially in Jammu-Kashmir, the only state with a Moslem
majority.
   One person was killed there by police during a demonstration on
Feb. 13, a day after police in neighboring Pakistan shot and killed
six people during similar protests.
   Rushdie, who was born into a Moslem family in Bombay, India, is
now a British citizen.
</TEXT>
