<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--Jails-Health     02-27 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Jails-Health,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Three City Jails Cited For Health-Code Violations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inmates at three city jails may have been served
unsanitary food, the city Health Department said after finding more
than 100 health-code violations including signs of mice, roaches and
flies, according to a report published today.
   Inspections last month found unsanitary conditions in a jail on
Rikers Island and two facilities in Brooklyn, the Daily News said,
citing Health Department reports. The three jails house more than
4,500 inmates.
   Of the violations, 24 were deemed hazardous. Health Department
spokesman Barry Adkins said the most serious involved serving food
at the wrong temperature, which could lead to salmonella poisoning.
   The reports cited evidence of mice, flies and roaches in
food-storage areas and in one case, what may have been human
excrement, the News said. They also cited inoperative toilets and
dishwashers, and possible asbestos-containing material.
   The Correction Department has been working with the Health
Department to remedy problems, said Julian Prager, an assistant
correction commissioner, adding that conditions were not that bad.
   ``They could write up anybody's house worse than this,'' he said.
</TEXT>
