<SECOND>PM-Iran, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0490,0701</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Vows Stronger Soviet Ties With Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with new Shevardnadze quotes, Khamenei
asking Moscow to press Iraq. Picks up 5th pvs, ``On Sunday ...'' Trims
thereafter to tighten.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze said today his visit to Tehran signals expanded ties
with Iran, whose revolutionary leader says he wants Moscow to help
combat the ``devilish'' West.
   ``In our opinion, Iran enjoys high international prestige,''
Iran's official news agency quoted Shevardnadze as saying. ``We have
come to the conclusion that it is a must to acknowledge others'
beliefs and respect them.''
   Shevardnadze made his remarks at a meeting with President Ali
Khamenei. On Sunday, he met with Iran's revolutionary leader,
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, for 90 minutes.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency said Shevardnadze was quoted as
saying his visit held the promise of closer ties between Iran and
the Soviets despite ``ideological differences.'' IRNA did not quote
Shevardnadze as enumerating the differences, but Iran _ an Islamic
republic _ previously has criticized the Soviet Union's official
atheism.
   Shevardnadze was quoted as saying the two sides agreed that
military confrontations must be reduced and chemical weapons
annihilated worldwide, according to IRNA. He also said Moscow would
push for progress in the Iran-Iraq peace talks, stalled since the
Aug. 20 cease-fire in the Persian Gulf war.
   Khamenei told Shevardnadze, ``Iraq must be pressured, and we
think your government can exert this pressure more than anyone
else,'' IRNA said. The Soviet Union was Iraq's major weapons
supplier during the war and is believed to be one of its biggest
creditors.
   IRNA said Shevardnadze repeated his call for the withdrawal of
foreign forces from the gulf, saying ``We have explicitly announced
to the American president that we condemn the U.S. military presence
in the Persian Gulf, and will continue this policy until the
Americans withdraw their troops from the region.''
   The United States has 23 warships in and around the gulf, the
biggest fleet in the strategic waterway where the Soviet Union keeps
seven to nine ships. The Soviet envoy has said Moscow is willing to
withdraw its ships.
   On Sunday, parliamentiary deputies moved to put severing ties
with Britain to a floor vote on Tuesday.
   Last week, Britain recalled its diplomats from Tehran to protest
Khomeini's death decree for British author Salman Rushdie. IRNA said
editorials in Tehran newspapers today supported breaking ties.
   It said Shevardnadze did not ask Khomeini to withdraw his order
for Moslem zealots to assassinate Rushdie, whose novel ``The Satanic
Verses'' is considered blasphemous by many Moslems.
   Britain reportedly had asked Shevardnadze to press Khomeini to
reprieve Rushdie, but IRNA said, `There was no mention of the
(Rushdie) affair in Shevardnadze's speech.''
   Shevardnadze, the highest ranking Soviet official to visit Iran
since the 1979 Islamic revolution, met Khomeini two days after the
Iranian spiritual leader declared Iran does not need relations with
the West.
   Khomeini has been widely condemned in the West for issuing the
death decree.
   At their meeting, Khomeini stressed to Shevardnadze the
importance of ``the expansion of strong ties in various dimensions
in confronting the devilish acts of the West,'' Tehran Radio
reported.
   Tehran Radio, monitored in Nicosia, broadcast a recording of
excerpts from the dialogue and Tehran Television showed Khomeini,
wearing a skullcap and robes with a blanket over his knees, talking
to Shevardnadze.
   Afterward, Shevardnadze met Prime Minister Hussein Musavi and
delivered an invitation for him to visit Moscow, according to IRNA.
Tehran Radio said the two agreed to set up mechanisms for
``regulating political contacts'' between Moscow and Tehran.
   Rushdie, who was born into a Moslem family in India, has been in
hiding since Khomeini issued his execution order Feb. 14. Iranian
clerics have put a bounty of $5.2 million on his head.
   All 12 European Common Market countries as well as Norway, Sweden
and Canada have recalled their top diplomats from Iran to protest
the death decree.
   Shevardnadze was to return to Moscow today after his 10-day
Middle East trip.
</TEXT>
