<FIRST>r p PM-Giuliani     02-27 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Giuliani,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giuliani, Not Yet A Candidate, Pledges Reform in NY City Hall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani has
pledged a ``clean sweep'' of appointed officials in city government,
referring to his as-yet-unannounced mayoral campaign as if it were
under way.
   Appearing Sunday on WNBC-TV's ``News Forum,'' Giuliani took Mayor
Edward I. Koch and the Democratic Party to task for allowing
inefficiency and corruption to fester.
   When appointments are dictated by political party bosses,
``You're just going right down the primrose path to inefficient
government, ineffective government, and then sometimes just corrupt
government,'' Giuliani said.
   Giuliani, a Republican, gave some of his strongest indications to
date that he would enter the mayoral race. ``I'm going to make it
very clear from the very beginning that anyone that donates money to
my campaign should do it because they want reform, nonpartisan
government in New York,'' he said.
   The only announced Republican candidate, cosmetics heir Ronald
Lauder, already has spent around $750,000 in his quest for the
nomination, according to the New York Post.
   City primary elections will be held in September, and the general
election is set for November.
   Giuliani stepped down last month after 5{ years as U.S. attorney
in Manhattan, where he gained fame with prominent prosecutions of
corrupt political figures, Wall Street executives, mobsters and
others.
   He has said he is exploring a mayoral candidacy and has
authorized fund-raising in his behalf, but has not declared his
intention to run.
   Key issues are crime, drugs, education, housing, homelessness and
jobs, Giuliani said. He urged a city law to confiscate property from
drug dealers, favored a bill curtailing the warehousing of vacant
apartments and was noncommittal on commercial rent control.
   ``The city is in very, very bad shape, and the mayor is
responsible for it,'' Giuliani said.
</TEXT>
