<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Kidnap     02-27 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Kidnap,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anonymous Caller Issues Claim on Missing Israeli Soldier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anonymous caller claimed today that a
Palestinian group abducted a missing 21-year-old Israeli paratrooper
and is holding him captive.
   The caller told Agence-France Presse he represented the
Palestinian Arab Army, a previously unknown group.
   Army officials said they did not know if the claim was legitimate
or whether the soldier was kidnapped.
   ``He told us they had kidnapped the soldier and that there will
be a videotape released in the next few days'' to authenticate the
claim, said Jean-Luc Porte, a journalist at the French news agency
in Jerusalem.
   The caller said that demands for the release of the soldier would
be made ``in the next few days.''
   Porte said the man spoke Arabic and did not identify himself by
name.
   The caller was asked if the Palestinian Arab Army was affiliated
with the Palestinian Liberation Organization, and he denied any
connection, Porte said.
   An army spokesman said he had not heard about the claim of
responsibility or that the soldier had been kidnapped. The army was
checking the claim, said the spokesman, who cannot be identified by
name under military regulations.
   The missing paratrooper, Avi Sassportas, 21, disappeared Feb. 16
after he left his base in southern Israel to return to his home in
Ashdod.
   He last was seen waiting at a junction near the Mediterranean
city of Ashkelon. He was armed with an M-16 assault rifle, Israel
radio reported.
   Thousands of police, soldiers and civilian volunteers have
searched for the soldier.
</TEXT>
