<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Goetz     02-27 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Goetz,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Subway Gunman Loses High Court Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard Goetz, who in 1984 shot four young men
he said were going to rob him on a New York City subway, today lost
a Supreme Court challenge to his conviction for illegally possessing
a gun.
   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that Goetz was
denied a fair trial.
   Goetz, who was sentenced to a year in jail and fined $5,000,
began serving his term at the Rikers Island prison in New York City
last month. He is eligible for, but not assured of, parole after 51
days.
   His case won worldwide attention, prompting debates on
self-defense and racism. Some called Goetz, a 41-year-old
electronics engineer, a hero. Others called him a cold-hearted
vigilante and racist.
   Goetz is white. The four teen-agers he shot are black.
   The subway shooting occurred Dec. 22, 1984 after one of the
youths approached Goetz and asked him for $5. Goetz later said he
feared he was going to be mugged and robbed.
   Goetz fled from the subway car and left New York City. Nine days
later he surrendered to police in Concord, N.H.
   After a 1987 trial, Goetz was acquitted of attempted murder,
assault and other charges. He was convicted only on the
gun-possession charge.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Goetz argued that he
was denied a fair trial by the judge's instructions to jurors.
   The appeal said the judge violated Goetz's rights by telling
jurors they ``must'' _ rather than ``may'' _ convict him if they
found that all elements of the illegal possession charge had been
proved beyond a reasonable doubt.
   The jurors also were told they ``must'' acquit Goetz if they
found that the proof was insufficient to sustain any element of the
illegal possession charge.
   After his trial, jurors told reporters that Goetz was justified
in shooting the men he thought were going to attack him. But they
said they had no choice but to find him guilty of illegally
possessing a gun.
   Lawyers for Goetz told the justices, ``The jury, by such
compulsive language, was even potentially precluded from considering
all factors, beyond the mere statutory elements, toward its
determination of (Goetz's) ultimate guilt.''
   The appeal noted that Goetz had been mugged several times
previously, and that he had unsuccessfully sought a permit to carry
a gun.
   Prosecutors urged the justices to reject the appeal. ``There is
not now _ and never has been _ the slightest conflict of opinion
among federal and state appeals courts about the constitutionality
of the kind of instruction delivered to (Goetz's) jury,'' they said.
   Goetz's initial sentence was overturned by a state appeals court,
and he was resentenced last Jan. 13.
   The case is Goetz vs. New York, 88-1122.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
