<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Biaggi     02-27 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Biaggi,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Biaggi, Esposito Lose Appeals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., and former
Brooklyn, N.Y., Democratic boss Meade Esposito today lost Supreme
Court appeals aimed at overturning their convictions for exchanging
illegal gratuities.
   The court, without comment, cleared the way for Biaggi's
imprisonment on a 2{-year term. Esposito was sentenced to two years
probation and 500 hours of community service.
   Each man also was fined $500,000.
   Biaggi, who served 10 terms in Congress, was forced to resign
from the House of Representatives last Aug. 5 following his
conviction on racketeering charges in another case.
   He has been sentenced to eight years in prison in that case,
which involves the Wedtech Corp. and charges that the ex-congressman
illegally took $1.8 million in stocks and cash from the Bronx, N.Y.,
business.
   The case acted on today involved charges that Biaggi accepted
free vacations from Esposito in exchange for helping a financially
troubled ship-repair company in Brooklyn.
   Biaggi was convicted in November 1987 of accepting gratuities for
official acts and obstruction of justice, and Esposito was convicted
of giving the gratutities.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the convictions last
August after rejecting arguments that prosecutors violated the
defendants' rights by excluding some Italian-Americans from the jury.
   The appeals court said the prospective jurors were excluded for
legitimate reasons other than their Italian descent, and noted that
at least two Italian-Americans served on the jury that convicted
Biaggi and Esposito.
   The case is Biaggi vs. U.S., 88-828.
</TEXT>
