<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Brunswick     02-27 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Brunswick,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Let Georgia City Collect Flood Control Legal Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to let
Brunswick, Ga., collect a $324,000 reimbursement it won, and then
lost, from the federal government for legal costs incurred in a
fight over flood control.
   The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court
ruling that the coastal city does not qualify for the reimbursement.
   The dispute dates back to Brunswick's request in the early 1980s
to participate in the federally subsidized National Flood Insurance
Program for communities that carefully control development of land
likely to be flooded.
   In 1985, Brunswick sued the Federal Emergency Management Agency,
which runs the program, and others over alleged errors in
calculating Brunswick's eligibility.
   The lawsuit ended in a settlement prior to any trial, and a
federal trial judge ordered the government to pay Brunswick $324,000
for lawyer fees and other costs the city had incurred.
   The award was made under the Equal Access to Justice Act. Under
that law, a local government that engages the federal government in
legal battle is eligible for reimbursement if its net worth is less
than $7 million and the federal government's position in the dispute
was not ``substantially justified.''
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last July 11 threw out the
$324,000 award on two grounds. It said Brunswick's net worth exceeds
$7 million and the federal government's position in the flood
control dispute was substantially justified.
   On the net-worth issue, Justice Department lawyers relied on the
city's annual financial report showing ``total municipal equity'' to
be just over $22 million when the lawsuit was filed. They said that
figure reflected the city's net worth.
   But city lawyers said the ``net worth'' term used in the Equal
Access to Justice Act should not include those assets generally not
available to pay off debts.
   The city's water and sewer system wrongly was counted as an asset
because its worth is not available for debt payment, the city's
lawyers argued.
   The 11th Circuit court said net worth is determined by
subtracting ``total liabilities'' from ``total assets'' _ including
the city's water and sewer system.
   The appeals court also ruled that U.S. District Judge Anthony
Alaimo abused his discretion in deciding that the federal
government's legal position in the underlying dispute had not been
substantially justified.
   The case is Brunswick vs. U.S., 88-948.
</TEXT>
