<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-ChicagoMayoral 1stLd-Writethru a0483 02-27 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Mayoral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0483,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll: Daley Holds Slight Lead Over Sawyer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs on end with background on other mayoral elections,
including 1987 loss of black incumbent mayor in Charlotte, N.C.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the mayoral primary in its final day, a poll
showed Mayor Eugene Sawyer narrowing the gap against Richard M.
Daley, who hopes to win the job his father held for two decades.
   The poll, taken Wednesday through Friday for WBBM-TV and the
Daily Southtown Economist, showed Daley's lead over Sawyer had
narrowed to 7 percentage points, 47-40 percent.
   A substantial 11 percent of the 885 registered voters polled were
undecided, and the poll's margin of error was 4 points.
   Two weeks earlier, the same poll showed Daley held a 10 point
lead _ 43 to 33 percent.
   ``The mayor is poised in a very good position now to overtake
Daley,'' said Sawyer's campaign spokesman Larry Horist. ``This race
is virtually tied up.''
   Daley had no immediate comment about the poll.
   Whether it's too late for Sawyer to avoid becoming the first
black mayor of a major city to be defeated by a white remains the
question.
   With the Democratic primary set for Tuesday, both candidates
campaigned vigorously during the weekend, each invoking the name of
the late Mayor Harold Washington, the city's first black mayor, and
citing the need to heal the city's racial divisions.
   ``Harold Washington was a strong mayor who loved the city,''
Daley, the Cook County state's attorney, told an all-black
congregation, one of three he visited Sunday.
   ``My father was a strong mayor who loved the city,'' added Daley,
the son of the late Richard J. Daley, who was Chicago's mayor for 21
years.
   Sawyer campaigned at 10 black churches. At the Antioch Baptist
Church, the mayor received a standing ovation for his solo rendition
of the hymn ``How Great Thou Art.''
   Jesse Jackson campaigned with Sawyer, leading supporters in
chants of ``maintain the gains,'' saying he wants to keep the
multi-racial city government that Sawyer has helped build.
   Sawyer has gained steadily in polls during recent months, while
Daley, despite his lead, remains below 50 percent.
   The latest Southtown Economist-WBBM poll indicated that the
electorate remained divided along racial lines.
   Sawyer received the support of 73 percent of registered black
voters surveyed to Daley's 8 percent. Whites split 79-14 percent for
Daley. Hispanics favored Daley by 2-1.
   The poll also found that 80 percent of blacks questioned said
they definitely will vote Tuesday, versus 73 percent of whites.
   Chicago's population is about 40 percent black, 40 percent white
and nearly 20 percent Hispanic.
   Whoever wins the primary faces the Republican challenger and the
third-party candidacy of black alderman Timothy Evans in April 4's
general election.
   However the Democratic race turns out, the GOP candidate in April
will be white _ and could be former Democratic power Edward
Vrdolyak, who has launched an 11th-hour Republican primary write-in
campaign.
   Vrdolyak, who joined the Republican ranks after losing to
Washington in 1987, is challenging the officially endorsed GOP
candidate, Dr. Herbert Sohn, a physician and lawyer.
   If Sawyer wins the Democratic primary, the black vote could split
between Sawyer and Evans in the general election, bringing a white
back into the mayor's office.
   If Daley and Vrdolyak win, Evans would gain from the split in the
white vote.
   The winner will fill out the remaining two years in Washington's
term.
   The era of big-city black mayors in the United States began in
1967, when Carl Stokes was elected in Cleveland. Cleveland now has a
white mayor, but that happened after Stokes decided not to seek
re-election.
   Amongthe nation's very largest cities, no black incumbent has
ever lost to a white. But in Charlotte, N.C., the nation's 44th
largest city, incumbent Mayor Harvey Gantt, a black, lost to a white
challeger in 1987.
</TEXT>
