<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Kinoy     02-27 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Kinoy,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Lawyer Loses Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil rights lawyer who says the government
violated his rights by eavesdropping on his conversations with
clients lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court, without comment, refused to revive Arthur Kinoy's
lawsuit for monetary damages.
   Kinoy's suit stems from FBI wiretapping from 1949 through 1970 of
various people he represented. His clients have included Julius and
Ethel Rosenberg, executed for giving atomic bomb secrets to the
Soviet Union, and members of the so-called Chicago Seven, who were
accused of conspiring to incite a riot at the Democratic National
Convention in 1968.
   Government officials said the wiretaps, installed without court
warrants, were designed to protect national security. The government
said the eavesdropping was not aimed at Kinoy, who teaches law at
Rutgers University in New Brunswick, N.J.
   Kinoy's suit was filed in 1970, and eight years of pre-trial
maneuvering ensued. The case was dormant from 1979 until 1985 when
Kinoy sought to revive it, claiming the government violated the
confidentiality of the lawyer-client relationship.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last July threw out the
suit.
   ``Kinoy, as an attorney, possessed no constitutional right,
independent of his clients' rights, to communicate with his clients
without government intrusion when national security interests were
at stake,'' the appeals court said.
   The appeals court noted that Kinoy previously won a court order
barring the government from any future surveillance that would
violate his privacy rights.
   But the 2nd Circuit court said there is no ground for Kinoy to
collect damages from the government or from FBI officials who
authorized or conducted the eavesdropping.
   The case is Kinoy vs. Tolson, 88-892.
</TEXT>
