<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Evidence     02-27 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Evidence,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Will Use Virgin Islands Case to Decide Evidence Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to use a case
from the U.S. Virgin Islands to decide whether federal juries may be
told about a defendant's alleged prior criminal conduct if a
previous trial on those charges ended in acquittal.
   The justices said they will review the bank robbery conviction
and 70-year prison sentence of Reuben Dowling.
   Federal prosecutors said Dowling used a ski mask and a pistol to
rob $7,000 from the First Pennsylvania Bank in Frederiksted, St.
Croix, on July 8, 1985.
   At his trial, prosecutors introduced evidence of Dowling's
alleged robbery of a private home weeks after the bank robbery
occurred. Dowling previously had been tried and acquitted of charges
stemming from the residential robbery.
   A federal trial judge allowed prosecutors to introduce such
evidence, and the 3rd Circuit Court of Appeals upheld that ruling.
   The appeals court said the evidence should not have been admitted
but its use was ``harmless'' _ meaning that Dowling would have been
convicted even if it had not been used.
   In the appeal acted on today, Dowling argued that telling jurors
about a crime for which he was acquitted violated his constitutional
rights and should not have been ruled harmless error.
   Justice Department lawyers argued that the evidence should not
have been ruled inadmissible. They said that although six federal
appeals courts have barred such evidence, three federal appeals
courts have allowed it.
   The case is Dowling vs. U.S., 88-6025.
</TEXT>
