<FIRST>r w PM-HanfordCleanup     02-27 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hanford Cleanup,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, State of Washington Reach Accord on Nuclear Reservation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington state and the federal government
have reached an agreement over cleaning up the Hanford nuclear
reservation, which has become the most contaminated of the nation's
nuclear weapons production facilities.
   Washington Gov. Booth Gardner and officials of the Department of
Energy and the Environmental Protection Agency were signing the
accord in a ceremony at the Capitol today.
   According to a draft summary of the 300-page ``Hanford Action
Cleanup Action Plan'' circulated on Capitol Hill:
   _$2.8 billion will needed over the next five years to begin the
cleanup effort. That is roughly twice what would be available under
current budget guidelines that limit funding growth to 3 percent.
   _Specific milestones will be included for actually cleaning up
the reservation, including an accelerated schedule for removing
pumpable liquids from 149 aging, single-shell underground tanks and
constructing a vitrification plant to turn the wastes into a
glass-like substance.
   _The Justice Department has decided that the agreement will be
enforceable, an issue that had been a key sticking point in
negotiations.
   In addition, the federal government has agreed to provide
Washington $2.9 million over the next three years to fund the
state's oversight role.
   If the needed congressional funding is provided and the agreement
is carried forward, the clean-up effort could add 2,000 people to
the Hanford payroll by 1994.
   The agreement was reached after more than a year of negotiations
and amid threats that the state would seek a ``consent decree'' in
court if negotiations failed.
   Besides being the most contaminated of the Energy Department's 16
weapons-productions sites, the 570-square mile reservation in
south-central Washington is expected to be the most costly and
longest to clean up.
   The Energy Department estimated in January that it could cost up
to $57 billion to manage and clean up the radioactive and toxic
wastes at the reservation and even then Hanford wouldn't be returned
to a ``pristine'' condition.
   Stored at Hanford is more than 60 percent of the nation's
high-level radioactive waste generated by weapons programs dating
back to World War II.
   According to some estimates, more than 200 billion gallons of
liquid radioactive waste have been dumped directly into the soil at
Hanford and roughly 1,200 sites are seriously contaminated.
   There have also been concerns that the contaminated liquids may
be seeping into the groundwater deep beneath the reservation and
could eventually reach the nearby Columbia River.
   Scientists at the reservation worked on the atomic bomb that was
dropped on Nagasaki, Japan, at the end of World War II. Hanford was
one of the largest weapon's production complexes in the 1950s.
   At present, only one commercial nuclear power plant is operating
at the reservation and the Energy Department has announced plans to
phase out all weapons production activities at the site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
