<FIRST>r i PM-AtlanticStorm 1stLd-Writethru a0511 02-27 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Atlantic Storm, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0511,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlantic Storm Kills 23, Leaves 26 Missing At Sea</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede and graf 8 pvs, ``In Spain ...'' to UPDATE with four
more deaths. Pick up 9th pvs ``In the ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL AMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers today found bodies of
three more victims of storms that churned up 80 mph winds and killed
23 people across Europe's western seaboard and Mediterranean coast,
officials said.
   Sunday's storms from Britain to Spain sank or disabled eight
ships with waves as high as 30 feet. Rescue workers said 26 people
remain missing and presumed dead today. At least 80 people were
rescued.
   Calmer weather returned to Portugal today, but storms continued
to lash northern Spain, western France and Britain.
   Antonio Loureiro, an official of the National Meteorological
Institute in Lisbon, said winds had died down to as little as 6 mph.
   The Spanish Meteorological office issued storm warnings for
extensive areas of the Mediterranean and North Atlantic coasts.
Winds could gust up to 50 mph in northwestern Cape Finisterre, said
the institute.
   Mediterranean waves washed over dikes along the French Riviera on
Sunday, inundating seaside restaurants at Cannes and washing over
the Promenade des Anglais at Nice.
   French police reported a 62-year-old man was killed when a big
wave knocked him against a wall, a nurse was caught by a 25-foot
wave and drowned and another woman's body was recovered from the
sea. There was a fourth death in France, on Saturday, when a young
man was carried away by high waves and drowned.
   Storms killed 12 people Saturday and Sunday in Spain, where
strong winds knocked over billboards and blew off parts of roofs.
They included, five deaths in the eastern city of Valencia, three
died in central Valladolid and Chinchilla towns, and another person
in eastern Aguilas, Spanish National Radio reported. A man drowned
when his canoe overturned in northern Spain. The last two victims,
whose bodies have not been recovered, are a crewmen missing from a
Spanish fishing trawler and a Swedish tourist reported missing
Saturday from the beach on Balearic Island of Majorca, where she was
swimming.
   In the most serious incident, a Nigerian cargo ship with 46
people aboard developed engine trouble two miles off Cape Espichel,
a rocky promontory of Portugal. Gale-force winds and 16-foot waves
drove the 3,000-ton River Gurara onto the rocks and broke the ship
in two, a spokesman for the Portuguese navy said.
   A Portuguese frigate picked up 27 people from lifeboats, he said.
   The navy said three more bodies were found today, bringing to
seven the number of bodies recovered.
   ``It is almost impossible there are any more survivors,'' said
Cmdr. Carlos Fidalgo.
   Off Bordeaux, France, a Singapore-registered freighter issued a
distress call and sank Saturday, and rescue workers searched
fruitlessly Sunday for 14 sailors who were aboard.
   A Bulgarian cargo ship also caught fire off Lisbon, and four
people were injured, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
