<HEAD>Five Kurdish Guerrillas, Policeman, Die in Clash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMIL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Kurdish guerrillas and a Turkish
policeman died in a shoot-out in this southeastern township Monday,
the Anatolia News Agency reported.
   It occurred when security forces called on the rebels to
surrender and they instead opened fire, the agency said.
   The guerrillas are thought to belong to the outlawed Kurdish
Labor Party, which wants to set up a Marxist state for ethnic Kurds
in parts of eastern and southeastern Turkey.
   An estimated 800 civilians and security personnel and an equal
number of insurgents have been killed since the rebels started
hit-and-run attacks in 1984, official reports say.
   About a fifth of Turkey's 55 million people are Kurds.
