<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--RedCross-Afghanistan     02-27 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Red Cross-Afghanistan,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross to Reopen Artificial Limb Center in Kabul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Committee of the Red Cross said
Monday it is sending experts back to Kabul this week to reopen an
artificial limb center in the capital of Afghanistan.
   The center was closed at the start of February when the committee
recalled half its 40 delegates because of tension as Soviet troops
completed their withdrawal, said spokesman Juerg Bischoff.
   Two orthopedic experts, both envoys of the all-Swiss
organization, are to return to Kabul this week to reopen a center
that provides artificial limbs to mine victims. About 20,000
survivors of mine explosions in Afghanistan need artificial limbs,
the committee estimated.
   More of the delegates may return if they are needed, Bischoff
said.
   ``The tension has subsided,'' he said. ``Around Feb. 15 (the
deadline for the Soviet withdrawal), nobody knew what would happen.
In the event, not so much happened.''
   Twenty Red Cross delegates have remained in Kabul, running a
hospital, Bischoff said.
</TEXT>
