<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BundyConference     02-27 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bundy Conference,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Law Enforcement Officers Share Information About Killer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUANTICO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Information exchanged by 20 law enforcement
officers familiar with serial killer Ted Bundy will be analyzed
further to see if other crimes can be linked to him, the FBI said
today.
   ``Information exchanged at the conference will be used to build a
model of homicides typically committed by Ted Bundy,'' the FBI said
in a statement after a weeklong meeting of Bundy investigators
ended. ``This model will be compared against crimes that are
unsolved in which he remains a suspect.
   Bundy was executed Jan. 24 in Florida for the 1978 murder of
Kimberly Diane Leach of Lake City, Fla.
   In the days before his death, Bundy confessed to 23 killings
across the West, although he did not provide 23 names, and also gave
information that authorities said might linke him to other cases. He
had been convicted of three killings in Florida.
   Some investigators believe the onetime law student who became
America's most notorious serial killer have slain more than 100
women as far back as two decades ago.
   The FBI said the goal of the conference was to determine the
scope of Bundy's activities.
   ``A chronological listing of his travels and activities will be
charted by the FBI Visual Investigative Analysis Unit,'' the FBI
statement said. ``This process will consist of a detailed
examination of police records from around the country.''
   FBI Special Agent William Hagmaier, who was present with Bundy at
all of his interviews with investigators and was the last law
enforcement official to speak with the serial killer, said he
believed conference participants came away with some useful
information.
   ``Some people were brought in who had not had an opportunity to
take confessions but were familiar with his crime scenes,'' Hagmaier
said. ``We're discussing his methods of operation and his
whereabouts in various cases to determine the practicality of
considering him a suspect.''
</TEXT>
