<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Scandal     02-27 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Denies Part in Stock-Profiteering Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone said Monday
three of his aides had bought bargain shares in the company at the
center of a stock-profiteering scandal, but he denied any personal
involvement in the affair.
   ``I regret my aides' purchase of shares occurred because of my
poor supervision,'' Nakasone said in a nationally televised news
conference. ``But I am innocent and played no role in the scandal.''
   The largest opposition party, the Socialists, expressed
dissatisfaction with Nakasone's remarks, and repeated demands the
government summon him to testify before Parliament concerning the
scandal.
   ``If we can't get a satisfactory response from the government, we
are ready to boycott the remaining Parliament session. I believe
other opposition parties are ready to follow our line, too,'' said
Osamu Yatabe, a Socialist member of Parliament.
   The scandal involves sales to 150 influential politicians and
businessmen of bargain-priced shares in Recruit-Cosmos Co. before
the stock was listed for public sale. When public trading began, the
share prices shot up and the bargain buyers profited handsomely.
   The scandal has shaken the government, and prosecutors have
arrested eight people on charges of bribery or violating securities
laws.
   Nakasone, who was prime minister in 1982-87, denied his
involvement in the scandal for the first time in an interview last
week with CBS News.
   Monday's news conference marked his first public comments to the
Japanese on the affair. It also was the first time Nakasone publicly
acknowledged that his aides bought shares in Recruit-Cosmos, a
subsidiary of the information service conglomerate Recruit Co.
   He said the aides bought a total of 29,000 shares in September
1986 and sold them the following month. He did not say how much
profit they made.
   Asked Monday if he would appear before Parliament, Nakasone said:
``I don't believe it is necessary now that I have made everything
clear today, but I would follow the government's decision.''
   He said he was to travel to the United States on Tuesday to give
lectures at several universities.
   Yatabe said the Socialist Party would press the government to
summon Nakasone, along with Hisashi Shinto, former chairman of
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Co., and Ihei Aoki, former secretary
to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
   Opposition parties say they suspect Nakasone directed the giant
telephone utility to buy two supercomputers from a U.S. manufacturer
and sell them to Recruit Co. The tranaction reportedly benefited
Recruit significantly.
   Two former Nippon Telegraph vice presidents are among those who
have been arrested in the scandal.
   More than 20 prominent people, including former Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa and two other Cabinet ministers, have resigned
because of links to the affair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
