<DOCNO> AP890227-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1325EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-VeteransBudget     02-27 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Veterans Budget,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of New Veterans Department Sees No Additional Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cabinet status for the Veterans Administration
does not automatically mean more money, the man designated to head
the new department told the nation's largest veterans group Monday.
   ``We realize that with the budget problems facing this
administration, we're not going to be the priority group,'' Edward
J. Derwinski told an American Legion meeting. ``We don't want any
false expectations, any false hopes in the field.''
   After his speech, Derwinski told reporters he does not believe he
will be able to win extra money for the new department in the
current fiscal year. It was his first such admission, though he
earlier had said he had not won over the Office of Management and
Budget to his view that the Veterans Administration needs more funds.
   A Legion spokesman said supplemental funds were essential this
year.
   The VA on March 15 becomes the Department of Veterans Affairs,
the government's newest and second-largest Cabinet department.
   Derwinski is scheduled to go before the Senate Veterans Affairs
Committee on Tuesday for a closed hearing that is expected to delve
into his admitted tipping off of the South Korean embassy in 1975
that a member of the Korean Central Intelligence Agency was about to
defect.
   On Monday, Derwinski began his speech with the warning, ``The
first thing we have to appreciate, and it isn't easy to accept, is
that there isn't an automatic pot of gold at the end of the rainbow
merely by being called a department,'' He returned to that theme
several times.
   Though Congress intended to enhance the influence of the agency
both inside and outside the administration through elevation to
Cabinet status, he said, ``it isn't something that is going to
happen overnight. It's going to take time, it's going to take
salesmanship, it's going to take special effort.''
   Speaking with reporters afterward, Derwinski said he was seeking
an extra $520 million for the 1990 fiscal year beginning Oct. 1,
almost all of it for medical care.
   ``If there is an '89 supplemental, which I doubt, we'll have a
shot there,'' he said.
   Veterans Administration officials have said since fall the $10.8
billion budgeted for medical care this year is $600 million to $1
billion short, and the veterans committees of both houses have urged
the administration to seek additional funds.
   Last week, the House Veterans Affairs Committee recommended to
the House Budget Committee additional spending this year of $520
million, 83 percent of it for medical care, and $1.3 billion more
for next year, 85 percent of it for medical care.
   Total spending by the Veterans Administration is budgeted at
$29.77 billion in the current year. President Bush proposed $29.96
billion for 1990, of which $10.99 billion would be for medical care.
   Jim Hanson, a spokesman for the American Legion, said when told
that Derwinski did not expect a supplemental appropriation in the
current fiscal year, ``I think we'd be terribly disappointed. It's
essential.''
   ``It's a terrifying thought that they'd start closing more beds''
in the 130 VA hospitals, Hanson said.
   Sparky Gierke of Bismarck, N.D., national commander of the
American Legion, exhorted Derwinski after the speech to be ``the
strong voice of the veterans, and carry the water of the American
veteran and not that of the Office of Management and Budget.''
</TEXT>
