<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-NumbersGame     02-27 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Numbers Game,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Say Record Seizures Don't Mean Agents Winning War Against
Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement agencies trumpet their seizure
of more than 800 pounds of heroin, calling it the largest drug
confiscation ever in the United States, but officials say that and
other similar seizures don't mean they're winning the war against
drugs.
   Every year, the government set records in the amount of drugs
confiscated, but seizures make ``just a dent'' in what's coming into
the country or being produced here, says Drug Enforcement
Administration spokesman Maurice Hill.
   ``There's more of it now'' than there was three years ago, no
matter how much is being seized, says Cornelius Dougherty, another
DEA spokesman.
   They say drugs lost to government raids are seen by drug dealers
as a mere cost of doing business.
   ``Historically, a manager of drug couriers gives up one courier
who is body carrying (drugs) to take your attention away from four
more,'' said Bill Norsworthy, a DEA agent at the El Paso
Intelligence Center in Texas.
   ``People walk away from a brand new aircraft after one load and
consider that an expense of the trip,'' he said. ``The same goes for
boats, automobiles, campers. They expect to pay a price.''
   Law enforcement agencies repeatedly seize millions of dollars in
drug profits that go unclaimed because to claim it would mean
proving ownership and thus where the money came from, Hill says.
   A better way to assess how the United States is doing in the war
on drugs is to concentrate on the price and purity level of the
drugs on the street, says Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del.
   ``For too long, when we've asked whether or not our drug strategy
is working, the administration has cited record arrest and seizure
data,'' said Biden, the Senate Judiciary Committee chairman.
   A check of price and purity of drugs on the streets, Biden said,
shows ``cocaine and heroin on the streets are much cheaper and more
potent than they were five years ago.''
   In 1982, cocaine sold at the retail level at a range, nationwide,
of $2,000 to $3,000 per ounce and was 50 percent to 60 percent pure,
Dougherty said.
   In 1988, the street price of cocaine had dropped to $500 to
$2,000 per ounce and it was 80 percent pure, said Dougherty, citing
information from drug seizures, undercover drug buys, intelligence,
and records seized.
   In 1985, a gram of heroin at 5.3 percent purity could be bought
on the street for a minimum of $115, he said. By 1988, the cost of a
gram at 6 percent to 8 percent purity was as low as $90.
   Drug busts gain a certain public popularity in part because there
are very few solid numbers about anything involving the war on
drugs, such as the level of illegal drugs in America.
   ``It's a quagmire,'' said Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Jim Simpson of
attempts to calculate the total amount of drugs confiscated. ``If
you add them up, you'll find the government got 10 times what it
actually seized. ... Everyone's trying to make themselves look
good.''
   Simpson invented a scenario in which the DEA provides the
intelligence, an Air Force radar locates the ship, a Navy jet spots
the ship, the Coast Guard tracks it and the final seizure is
conducted by a local sheriff in Florida.
   ``Even if everyone was trying to do the right thing and no one
was trying to cheat, it would still be a nightmare'' to sort out
various claims over the seizure, even though the agencies attempt to
note when they have assisted and when they have made a seizure
alone, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
