<DOCNO> AP890227-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1428EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Elections     02-27 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Elections,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Bills Municipal Vote as Referendum on PLO Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir billed Tuesday's
nationwide municipal elections as a referendum on the Arab-Israeli
conflict, saying gains for his right-wing Likud bloc would show the
world Israel will never talk to the PLO.
   ``Every vote for Likud means that Israel wants no truck with the
murderers of our sons who want to destroy Israel,'' Shamir was
quoted as saying Monday by the Jerusalem Post.
   But leaders of the left-leaning Labor Party rejected Shamir's
claim, saying local, not national, issues are at stake, and that the
personalities of the candidates take precedent over ideology.
   ``It's completely off the subject. We will focus on the issues
that count, day-to-day municipal issues,'' said Daniel Eldar,
Labor's campaign manager.
   Two issues that played a role in the November general elections
probably will spill over into the municipal voting: the
religious-secular conflict and the nearly 15-month-old Palestinian
uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Pro-Palestine Liberation Organization underground leaders of the
uprising have urged the about 70,000 Arab voters in east Jerusalem
to boycott the elections, and called a general strike for Tuesday to
enforce the order.
   At the same time, the army ordered the occupied lands sealed from
midnight Monday to 10 p.m. Tuesday, barring West Bank and Gaza
residents from entering Israel.
   Political analysts, meanwhile, predicted gains for the religious
parties similar to those in the November elections. In that vote,
relivious parties increased their representation from 14 to 18 seats
in the 120-member Parliament, alarming many secular Israelis.
   About 2.7 million Israelis, of them 400,000 Arabs, are eligible
to vote in 147 municipalities, choosing mayors and 1,341 council
members. There are 99 municipalities in the Jewish sector, and 48 in
the Arab sector.
   In the 1983 elections, 55 percent of the voters cast ballots, and
election officials expect a similar turnout this year. In the last
general elections, turnout was nearly 80 percent.
   In 1983, Labor won in 54 municipalities, compared with 26 towns
ruled by Likud. The remainder of the towns are run by local
political groups or religious parties.
   Each voter casts two ballots, one for mayor and one for a party
slate. Parties are awarded seats in the City Council according to
the number of votes won.
   Key contests are in the three largest cities: Jerusalem, Tel Aviv
and Haifa.
   In Jerusalem, Mayor Teddy Kollek is assured re-election to a
sixth term, but his Labor-affiliated ``One Jerusalem'' list might
lose control of the 31-member City Council because of the Arab
boycott and the growing strength of the religious parties.
   Working with a hostile council might force Kollek to make
concessions to right-wing and religious parties, thus further
escalating the Arab-Israeli and religious-secular conflicts dividing
the city.
   In Tel Aviv, the only major city run by Likud, popular Mayor
Shlomo Lahat is likely to win a fourth term. Lahat says he has
turned Tel Aviv into an international metropolis and promised
secular voters to keep the city free from religious coercion.
   The religious parties insist on closing entertainment spots,
including restaurants and movie theaters, on the Jewish Sabbath, the
biblically mandated day of rest that lasts from sundown Friday to
sundown Saturday.
   Haifa, a stronghold of the left for decades, has become a major
battleground for the two big parties.
   ``We have red flags all over the country, and we would like to
paint some of them blue (the color of Likud),'' said Likud's
campaign organizer, Nimrod Granit.
   ``Taking Haifa would be like taking Stalingrad,'' Granit said,
referring to the Soviet city in which the Red Army successfully
withstood a German offensive during World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
