<DOCNO> AP890227-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1528EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Baker-Trip     02-27 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker-Trip,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker to Meet with Shevardnadze, NATO Ministers in Vienna</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet overtures to Israel and Iran will be on
the agenda when Secretary of State James A. Baker III meets next
week in Vienna with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   Baker also will hold separate talks with the foreign ministers of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and participate in ceremonies
marking the opening of new East-West arms control negotiations, the
State Department announced Monday.
   The negotiations concern concentrations of NATO and Warsaw Pact
ground forces and tanks in Europe. The goal is to reduce them as a
means of easing East-West tensions.
   Spokesman Charles E. Redman said Baker would leave Washington for
the Austrian capital on Saturday and return on March 7. The
negotiations will open March 9 under a broad agreement between the
United States and the Soviet Union reached last year to supersede 15
years of futile discussions.
   The talks that failed dealt with Central Europe. The new
negotiations will cover the vast expanse of the continent _ from the
Ural Mountains in the Soviet Union to the Atlantic Ocean.
   Baker's meeting with Shevardnadze was described by Redman as a
``get-acquainted'' session. The Soviet foreign minister has just
completed a trip to the Middle East in which he offered a resumption
of relations to Israel if it would negotiate with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, and has been to Tehran.
   Shevardnadze spoke to the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the
spiritual leader of Iran, who proposed closer ties to the Soviet
Union to counter what the fundamentalist cleric called ``devilish
acts of the West.''
   Redman confirmed the Middle East and Iran were on Baker's agenda
for the Shevardnadze meeting.
   The Bush administration is in the midst of reviewing U.S. policy
toward the Soviet Union and the Middle East. President Bush said
last week he foresaw only a limited role for the Soviets in the
region and that he would not be ``stampeded'' into taking decisions
as a result of the Soviet initiative.
   Baker is due to report to the NATO foreign ministers, meanwhile,
on how he views prospects for Arab-Israeli diplomacy. Several of
them urged him during a trip to Western Europe earlier this month to
take advantage of what they considered to be Palestinian moderation.
   Baker remarked at the time that ``one has to till the ground
carefully; one has to proceed cautiously and understand that if you
push the level of discussion too high, too soon, and create too much
international attention you might pre-empt opportunities.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
