<FIRST>r w AM-US-Salvador     02-27 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Salvador,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Hails Duarte Peace Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Monday the peace plan
offered by Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte represents
``the most significant opportunity ever'' for a settlement to that
country's nine-year-old conflict.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman spoke after Duarte accepted
on Sunday a proposal by the FMLN rebel group for direct talks and
said negotiations should begin Tuesday accompanied by a three-month
cease-fire.
   ``In our judgment, this is potentially the most significant
opportunity ever for peace in El Salvador, particularly the
commitment of the government of El Salvador to undertake a cessation
of hostilities if the FMLN agrees within 48 hours,'' Redman said.
   He called on the FMLN to follow the government's example and
``immediately stop the killing so that the political process can
move forward.
   ``The time has come for the FMLN to choose between terrorist
violence and democratic balloting,'' he said.
   Redman added that U.S. officials had consulted with Salvadoran
officials about the proposal but that the plan was not imposed on
the Salvadorans.
   In a nationwide television and radio speech Sunday night, Duarte
also addressed the guerrillas' offer to participate in and accept
the results of the presidential election if it is postponed for at
least four months.
   He advocated postponing the vote, which is scheduled for March
19, until April 30 and proposed that a referendum be held on the
issue if the government and rebels cannot resolve it in talks.
   There have been no direct talks between the government and the
guerrillas since October 1987. Duarte proposed that the talks be
held in Guatemala.
</TEXT>
