<DOCNO> AP890227-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Romania     02-27 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Romania,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Denounces Human Rights Violations in Romania, Backs Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary accused its Warsaw pact ally Romania of
grave human rights violations and said Monday it will join Western
countries calling for the United Nations to investigate the
situation.
   It is believed to be the first time a communist country urges the
world body to investigate alleged abuses in another East bloc state.
   ``We are concerned that human rights and fundamental freedoms
are, in our judgment, gravely violated in Romania and this judgment
is shared by many other countries,'' Hungarian Deputy Foreign
Minister Gyula Horn told the U.N. Human Rights Commission.
   ``We are convinced that meeting the requirement of respect for
human rights is irrespective of a country's belonging to a system of
alliance and its social system,'' he told the 43-nation commission.
   Hungary's proposals to deal with the problem bilaterally with
Romania had brought no results, so the country is ready to
co-sponsor a resolution initiated by Sweden that urges the United
Nations to appoint a special investigator into Romania's human
rights situation, Horn said.
   He cited alleged violations ranging from the demolition of
villages and destruction of cultural and historic values to forced
assimilation of minorities and curbs on religious freedom.
   At a news conference after his address, Horn said Hungary did not
consult the Soviet Union or its other communist allies before making
its decision.
   In December, Hungary became the first communist country to ratify
a key human rights protocol allowing citizens to address individual
complaints of alleged rights violations to a U.N. panel.
   Hungary also was the first communist state to decide Friday to
ratify a 1951 convention defining rights of refugees.
   According to Hungarian statistics, about 15,000 Romanians have
sought asylum in neighboring Hungary, most of them illegally
crossing the border.
   Horn said 85 percent of refugees are ethnic Hungarians, although
arrivals include members of German and other minorities, as well as
Romanians.
   Some stretches of the 186-mile border are virtually unguarded,
while guards are posted every 100 yards at other areas, he said.
   Horn was asked about the fate of refugees who are caught.
   ``There are some who never reappear,'' he said. ``They are those
who are heavily beaten. There are all kinds of punishments.'' But he
added he was not aware of any shooting.
   In London, British journalist Sue Lloyd-Roberts said she and
colleague Vivian Roberts were arrested four times for clandestinely
photographing areas of Romania allegedly wrecked by President
Nicolae Ceausescu's modernization plans.
   She smuggled out her footage, broadcast Monday in Britain, by
hiding it in her underwear. The footage showed empty, brick-strewn
fields where three villages had stood until last fall.
   ``Ceausescu wants to create his `Communist Man,' and he has to
destroy the Romanian village because that's where the opposition to
communism is total,'' said Romanian emigre leader Ion Rativ. The
report said people spoke of villagers being killed resisting
eviction.
   The demolitions are part of Ceausescu's plan to raze 7,000 of
Romania's 13,000 villages and resettle people in so-called
agro-industrial centers.
   An unidentified woman was shown describing what happened: ``They
destroyed everyone's home. My house was knocked to the ground.
They've made us live in new blocks. Everything is wretched and
miserable. What can be done?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
