<SECOND>AM-People-Sawyer Producer,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sawyer and Donaldson Get Walters Producer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phyllis McGrady, former executive producer of
``The Barbara Walters Specials,'' has been named executive producer
of the ``Sam and Diane Show,'' a new ABC News prime-time program to
be co-anchored by Diane Sawyer and Sam Donaldson.
   ABC News also announced Monday that Dorrance Smith, who had been
in charge of weekend news and helped create ``This Week with David
Brinkley'' has been promoted to executive in charge of long form
programming, a title that had belonged to ABC News Vice President Av
Westin.
   Westin's contract is up at the end of March. ABC News spokeswoman
Elise Adde said negotiations are continuing, and ``we are hopeful he
will maintain a relationship with us in the future.'' Westin
continues producing ABC's ``Burning Questions'' documentary series.
The former ``20-20'' executive producer got into hot water two years
ago when he wrote a report criticizing the management of the news
division under Roone Arledge.
   Westin remains vice president for program development, but Smith
will participate in the development of the as-yet-untitled,
prime-time program, nicknamed the ``Sam and Diane Show,'' which is
slated to go on the air sometime this summer, probably in August.
   Sawyer was recently hired away from CBS where she had been a
correspondent on ``60 Minutes.'' ABC also recently hired
correspondent Chris Wallace away from NBC to be the new program's
chief correspondent.
   Ms. McGrady joined the news division in September 1988 after two
years as executive producer of ``The Barbara Walters Specials,'' and
prior to that, two years as executive producer of ``Good Morning
America.''
   Smith has been with ABC News for 12 years, the last nine as
executive producer of weekend news programming.
