<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Bush     02-27 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Bush,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Battle Riot Police Over Bush Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Student radicals with firebombs battled
riot police Monday in Seoul and five other cities to protest
President Bush's visit to South Korea.
   No serious injuries were reported, but dissidents said about 70
people were detained.
   A major clash broke out in Seoul when about 700 radical students
and dissidents, throwing rocks and firebombs, battled riot police
around Dongguk University.
   ``Bush go home!'' and ``Down with military dictatorship!''
protesters shouted, as they began a march to the U.S. Embassy, three
miles away.
   The protesters, carrying red and blue flags, tried to march into
the streets after a rally on campus, where they burned effigies of
Bush and South Korean President Roh Tae-woo. Marchers beating drums
led the procession.
   ``Drive out the imperialist Yankees and their military regime!''
a radical leader screamed. Protesters applauded and took up the
chant.
   Other radical leaders denounced Bush and the United States,
charging that Washington keeps troops in South Korea to enforce a
colonial-style rule. About 42,000 U.S. troops are stationed in South
Korea under a mutual defense treaty.
   Dozens of protesters surged from the pack and hurled firebombs at
riot police, touching off vicious fighting that lasted 45 minutes.
Several officers were set afire after being hit by firebombs, but
the flames were extinguished quickly.
   Bush, in Seoul for a brief visit on his way home from China and
Japan, moved around the capital by helicopter and was not near the
violence. The government mobilized 20,000 riot police in central
Seoul to block protests.
   Anti-Americanism was a casual subject in the conversation between
Bush and Roh before they started formal talks, and Bush asked why
even a small number of Korean students staged violent protests,
officials said.
   Roh replied there is a small group of radicals who subscribe to
communist ideology and class struggle, the officials said. There
also is a group of people who believe South Korea is subservient to
the United States, they said.
   In the southern city of Kwangju, hundreds of radicals fought with
riot police firing tear gas. Clashes also were reported in Kunsan,
Taegu, Pusan and Chongju.
   Police broke up an attempt by prominent dissident leaders to
march to the U.S. Embassy to deliver a letter addressed to Bush
demanding an end to the U.S. military presence in South Korea.
   About 15 dissident leaders shouting slogans and carrying pictures
of Bush with red crosses drawn through them were hauled away after
trying to assemble about a block from the embassy in downtown Seoul.
   ``No Bush visit!'' the small band shouted before they were
overwhelmed by charging police, who kicked and punched some of the
protesters.
   Minutes after the protest, Bush's helicopter passed overhead on
its way to the presidential mansion, the Blue House, to meet Roh.
   Hundreds of riot police ringed the U.S. Embassy and other U.S.
facilities because of radicals' threats to hold anti-American
protests. Police stepped up street checks on pedestrians downtown.
   The letter to Bush, released by the nation's main dissident
alliance, called for the withdrawal of all U.S. forces from South
Korea and charged that Washington ruled the nation like a colony.
   ``U.S.A. is the source of all suppression and sorrow to Korean
people since the division of the Korean peninsula,'' the letter said.
   The letter accused the United States of dividing the Korean
peninsula and keeping troops in South Korea to prevent its
reunification with North Korea. It also denounced Washington for
seeking greater access for U.S. imports to South Korea.
   Radicals say Roh's government is a military dictatorship
controlled by the United States.
   Radical students have little public support because of their
violent and extreme views, but they can assemble thousands of
activists and often clash with riot police.
</TEXT>
