<FIRST>r a AM-Scotus-Goetz     02-27 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Goetz,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Subway Gunman Loses High Court Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Subway gunman Bernhard Goetz's last hope of
cutting short his jail term ended Monday when the Supreme Court
upheld his gun possession conviction in the shooting of four
teen-agers on a subway.
   ``It looks like this is the end of the line,'' said Mark Baker,
Goetz's co-counsel. ``Hopefully, he'll get early parole and that'll
be the end of the criminal matter.''
   Goetz, 41, becomes eligible for parole Sunday after serving 51
days of a one-year sentence stemming from the Dec. 22, 1984,
shootings, said Ruby Ryles of the Correction Department.
   The Supreme Court, without comment, rejected arguments that Goetz
was denied a fair trial because a judge told jurors they ``must'' _
rather than ``may'' _ convict him if they found that the illegal
possession charge had been proved beyond a reasonable doubt.
   Gerald McKelvey, a spokesman for Manhattan District Attorney
Robert Morgenthau, said the prosecutor would not comment.
   Baker said he had spoken with Goetz last week, and Goetz had
anticipated the ruling would go against him.
   Goetz, who also was fined $5,000, began serving his sentence at
Rikers Island on Jan. 13 and also spent time in prison upon his
arrest.
   Supporters portrayed Goetz as a hero while detractors labeled him
a vigilante and a racist. Goetz is white. The four teen-agers he
shot are black.
   Goetz was acquitted of attempted murder, assault and reckless
endangerment in 1987, and convicted on just a single weapons
possession count.
</TEXT>
