<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1543EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Mideast     02-27 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Criticizes PLO Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Monday that the
Palestine Liberation Organization ``cannot escape responsibility''
for an attack by three guerrillas on Israeli soldiers and Christian
militiamen in southern Lebanon.
   Spokesman Charles E. Redman said the U.S. administration would
``convey this message'' at its next meeting with PLO representatives
in Tunisia.
   The guerrillas were from the Democratic Front for the Liberation
of Palestine, which claimed three Israeli soldiers and two Christian
militiamen were killed. Israeli authorities said the guerrillas'
mission was a raid on Israel and that there were no fatalities
before they were gunned down.
   The group is considered a radical faction, but Redman stressed it
is part of the PLO, which would be held accountable by the U.S.
government.
   ``The PLO cannot escape responsibility for the actions of its
constituent elements,'' the spokesman said.
   Redman added: ``We have made it clear to the PLO that these kinds
of operations have a negative impact on the U.S.-PLO dialogue and on
the atmosphere necessary for a positive Palestinian-Israeli
dialogue. We do not condone this type of activity.''
   The State Department spokesman and then Secretary of State James
A. Baker III were also harshly critical of the PLO for an earlier
clash involving two other PLO factions in southern Lebanon. But
there is no indication the Bush administration will break off talks
with Chairman Yasser Arafat's organization.
   Begun last December by the Reagan administration, the talks were
based on a pledge by Arafat to renounce terrorism and accepting
Israel's right to exist.
   Several U.S. officials, including Richard W. Murphy, then the
assistant secretary of state for Near East affairs, said the
dialogue would be suspended if the PLO engaged in terrorism.
   But Baker said on Feb. 11, after the first incident, ``we are not
prepared at this time to say this constitutes action by the PLO to
cause us to break off the dialogue.''
   At the same time, he said Robert Pelletreau, the U.S. ambassador
to Tunisia, had informed PLO officials that ``actions such as this _
directed against civilian or military targets, inside or outside of
Israel _ were something that gave us trouble.''
   Pelletreau has had four meetings with PLO representatives since
the Reagan administration ended a 13-year ban on dealing with the
Arafat organization.
   ``There is going to be a meeting on that subject, but as for
timing, I really don't have anything yet,'' Redman said, referring
to the incident last Thursday about a mile north of the Israeli
border.
   Meanwhile, William B. Quandt, a former National Security Council
analyst who is now a scholar with the Brookings Institution, said
the talks with the PLO had fallen short of PLO expectations and U.S.
promises.
   Quandt, who met recently with Arafat and other PLO officials in
Tunis, said they were ``a bit frustrated and disappointed with the
virtual non-existence of the U.S.-PLO dialogue.''
   He said at a news conference: ``They had been promised at the
time the dialogue began there would be substantive talks. There have
been virtually none.''
   Asked about Quandt's account, Redman said he ``couldn't speak to
someone else's expectations.''
   The spokesman said the decision to talk to the PLO ``was made at
the end of the previous administration, and we're now in the early
stages of a new administration. But beyond that, I don't really have
any way to interpret somebody else's expectations.''
   On another subject, Redman offered the State Department's
``warmest congratulations'' to Egypt and Israel on the signing
Sunday of agreements on Taba, a tiny beach enclave on the Red Sea.
   Israel had taken control of Taba when it defeated Egypt in the
1967 Six-Day War and captured the Sinai Peninsula. All of the
territory except for the 750-yard-long resort had been returned as
part of the 1979 peace treaty between the two countries.
   Redman, reading from a statement, said the agreements udner which
Israel is yielding Taba and a hotel it built there were ``a tribute
to the serious and statesmanlike approach adopted by the two
parties.''
   He said the agreements also proved that negotiations worked
between parties of good will.
</TEXT>
