<FIRST>r a AM-Biaggi     02-27 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Biaggi,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Congressman Loses Appeal To Supreme Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Rep. Mario Biaggi's appeal of a 1987
illegal gratuities conviction was rejected Monday by the U.S.
Supreme Court, clearing the way for his imprisonment on a 2{-year
term.
   No surrender date was scheduled. Prosecutors said that after they
received official notification of the ruling, they would send Biaggi
a letter ordering his surrender in two to three weeks.
   Biaggi, 70, who was one of the most decorated police officers in
the city before entering politics, is still appealing a conviction
in another case in which he was sentenced to eight years.
   The Supreme Court, without comment, let stand a lower court
ruling that upheld the September 1987 conviction of Biaggi and
former Brooklyn Democratic boss Meade Esposito.
   In the case, Esposito paid for a Florida vacation for Biaggi and
a companion and arranged to pay for a second one in exchange for the
congressman's efforts on behalf of a Brooklyn ship-repair company
that was a major client of Esposito's insurance firm.
   Biaggi, who for 10 terms represented the Bronx and part of
Westchester County, was forced to resign from office last Aug. 5
following another conviction on racketeering charges in the Wedtech
case.
   He was sentenced to eight years in prison in that case, which
involved charges that he illegally took $1.8 million in stocks and
cash from Wedtech Corp., a now-defunct defense contractor in the
Bronx.
   Biaggi is appealing the Wedtech conviction.
   ``We are very disappointed,'' said a Biaggi attorney, John
Pollok, of the Supreme Court ruling. ``We would have preferred the
court to consider some of the issues which we considered very
important.''
   Biaggi was convicted of accepting gratuities for official acts
and obstruction of justice, and Esposito was convicted of giving the
gratuities.
   Esposito was sentenced to two years probation and 500 hours of
community service. Each man also was fined $500,000.
</TEXT>
