<FIRST>u i AM-China-Dissidents Bjt   02-27 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissidents, Bjt,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Resents Fang Invitation; Dissidents Call Gov't Action `Stupid'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Monday it resented the United
States having invited a leading dissident to a banquet given by
President Bush, and regretted that a fuss was made when police
barred him from attending.
   Chinese intellectuals, meanwhile, said the action against Fang
Lizhi was ``stupid,'' ``neolithic'' and ``unacceptable.''
   Fang, an internationally respected astrophysicist who has
criticized Marxism and called for democratic reform in China, was
invited to the banquet along with his wife, Li Shuxian.
   But dozens of police converged to block his car and bar him from
entering the hotel where the Texas-style barbecue was held Sunday.
Police then refused to allow him to ride in a taxi and made a bus
driver pass a stop where he was waiting.
   ``All the arrangements concerning President Bush's stay in China
had been agreed upon by both sides beforehand,'' the official Xinhua
News Agency said, quoting an unidentified Foreign Ministry spokesman.
   ``The U.S. side, without consulting the Chinese side, invited
Fang to attend the dinner, which was especially in honor of Chinese
leaders. Therefore, the Chinese side resented this,'' the spokesman
said.
   Visiting world leaders generally hold banquets for their Chinese
hosts, but it would be highly unusual for them to submit the guest
list for Chinese approval
   ``Some people'' are trying to ``make an issue'' of Fang's
absence, said the Foreign Ministry spokesman.
   ``We feel sorry that such a thing should happen,'' Xinhua quoted
the spokesman as saying.
   Bush told Vice Premier Wu Xueqian at the airport he regretted the
actions that kept Fang away.
   At Bush's direction, U.S. Ambassador Winston Lord met with Vice
Foreign Minister Zhu Qizhen later and ``reiterated the regret that
the president had expressed,'' said U.S. Embassy spokesman McKinney
Russell.
   Russell said Lord also asked for ``clarification of what the
circumstances were.''
   Fang told reporters Monday that Bush's statement of regret was
``a beginning'' but added: ``I hope they (the Americans) say
something more in the next few days.''
   ``Regarding the United States I have a principled criticism: I
want it to adopt a single standard toward human rights and not a
double standard,'' he said. ``I think there are indeed some double
standards'' in the United States' open criticism of the Soviet
Union's human rights record but not China's.
   But Fang added, ``Of course, we Chinese must win our own human
rights for ourselves.''
   Bush did not raise human rights issues during his two days of
meetings with Chinese leaders. However, senior leader Deng Xiaoping
and Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang stressed that
domestic stability is more important now than democratic reform.
   Zhao said dissident demands for ``multiparty and parliamentarian
politics'' in China are unrealistic under current conditions and
will only undermine efforts to reform the nation's central planning
economic system.
   However, Fang said, ``Only after democracy is achieved can the
reforms be carried out. People must independently supervise the
government.''
   ``I can't change my views because of fear,'' he said, pledging to
continue speaking out. He said many fellow intellectuals telephoned
him Monday to express support.
   Bei Dao, a poet, said he was worried that the incident could be
the prelude to a political crackdown after a period of relative
cultural freedom.
   ``I was all ready to go back to my work and forget about
politics,'' he said. ``But if this is how they are openly
interfering in human rights, then I must fight back.''
   Bei is the author of a recent open letter signed by 100 others
who called for the release of political prisoners. The letter echoed
an earlier one, written by Fang in January.
   Dai Qing, a leading journalist who attended the banquet, said she
was shocked by the news.
   ``Their methods are neolithic,'' she said. ``Our government has
changed so much for the better, it was pitiful for them to do this
now.''
   Fang gained fame in 1986 with eloquent speeches to college
students in which he called for democracy and human rights.
   Authorities blamed him for a nationwide wave of student
demonstrations in the winter of 1986-87 and expelled him from the
Communist Party. They barred him this year from traveling to the
United States to attend a scientific conference and teach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
