<FIRST>r w AM-MemotoOllie     02-27 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Memo to Ollie,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Courier's Memo to North Criticized Contra Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Owen, who shuttled from Washington to
Central America with help for the Contra fighters, said in a 1986
memo that rebel leader Adolfo Calero surrounded himself with
second-rate people who ``are liars and greed and power motivated.''
   The six-page memo from Owen to Oliver North was introduced into
evidence Friday at North's trial and released by the court on
Monday. It was from ``TC'' to ``BG'' _ pseudonyms Owen used for
himself, ``The Courier,'' and North, ``Blood and Guts.''
   ``Perhaps Adolfo Calero is the man to lead Nicaragua back to
democracy,'' Owen wrote North on March 17, 1986, when North was a
National Security Council aide. ``He is a creation of the USG (U.S.
government) and so he is the horse we chose to ride. Have no problem
with this, as long as we know and understand his shortcomings.''
   The best way to do that, Owen said, was to look at the people
Calero trusted.
   ``Unfortunately, they are not first rate people; in fact they are
liars and greed and power motivated. They are not the people to
rebuild a new Nicaragua.''
   Owen said the Democratic National Front, headed by Calero ``has
done a good job of keeping competent people out of the
organization.''
   Calero testified in the trial last week, praising North's efforts
on behalf of the Contras.
   Later in his memo, Owen told North that a coalition of Contra
groups called United Nicaraguan Opposition (UNO) ``is a name only''
and ``there is no substance.''
   ``I care and believe in the boys and girls, men and women who are
fighting, bleeding, dying,'' Owen said, contending that few of the
leaders of the movement did.
   ``This war has become a business to many of them; there is still
a belief the Marines are going to have to invade, so let's get set
so we will automatically be the ones put in power,'' he wrote.
   At the end of the memo, Owen said he would like to ``move on''
and get involved in counterterrorism.
   ``I will continue in whatever position you recommend,'' he
concluded. ``You have been my Godfather through this.''
</TEXT>
