<FIRST>r a AM-Scotus-Mailbox     02-27 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Mailbox,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Vows to Continue Mailbox Fight Despite Supreme Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN PLATERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POMPANO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Timothy Haggerty lost to city hall,
lost in state court and on Monday lost in the highest court in the
land, but he vowed he'll continue his $50,000 fight _ over the size
of his mailbox.
   The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday let stand, without comment, a
lower court ruling that Haggerty's mailbox _ or at least the
15-foot-high structure it was part of _ had to go.
   Haggerty, a towing service mechanic, said from his home the
decision was expected.
   ``Let no one wonder why respect for the legal system is
collapsing,'' he said. ``But it's not over until I give up, and I
haven't given up yet.''
   He said he would consult his attorneys about further action.
   At the city attorney's office, Sharon Delegal, the latest in a
string of lawyers who handled the case, said she hoped the decision
ends the matter.
   ``We're pleased, to say the least,'' Ms. Delegal said. ``The
bottom line was that the structure, which was much bigger than a
mail box, was on public property. The city just felt very
uncomfortable with it.''
   The structure was built in front of his house in the spring of
1982, and within a few months had aroused the wrath of local
officials.
   Anchored by two subterranean truck engine blocks, two water pipes
rose 15 feet in the air. The mail receptacle was attached to a
horizontal bar about three feet above the ground. A second
horizontal bar several feet above the receptacle served as the base
of a flagpole.
   The structure, about six feet wide at its widest point, contained
an old bed frame, part of a golf cart and was topped off by a model
airplane with an ``air mail'' designation.
   About nine months after Haggerty completed it, city officials
told him the mail box violated a city ordinance barring obstructions
in the public right-of-way portion of his property.
   Haggerty said he was initially accused of blocking traffic _
despite the fact that he lives at the end of a dead-end street.
   Haggerty lost a first round in court, and the city removed the
structure. He won on appeal, and built another one _ this time 22
feet tall _ to take its place.
   The city won round three, and Haggerty was forced to remove the
second structure.
   He then sought help from the nation's highest court. His appeal
contended, among other things, that the city ordinance is violating
his freedom of expression.
   Lawyers for the city urged the justices to reject Haggerty's
appeal, arguing that he is free to express himself somewhere else on
his property, off the public right-of-way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
