<FIRST>r a AM-NightStalker     02-27 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Night Stalker,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer's Illness May Force Mistrial In Night Stalker Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for ``Night Stalker'' murder
defendant Richard Ramirez is suffering from trial-related nervous
exhaustion, the judge said Monday, and the prosecutor said they
might have to start the trial over.
   ``Probably the chances of a mistrial are good,'' Deputy District
Attorney P. Philip Halpin said. ``We can't keep this jury hanging
around indefinitely.''
   A mistrial would mean a new jury would need to be selected in the
3{-year-old case.
   Ramirez, 28, is charged with 13 murders and 30 related felonies
in a series of grisly nighttime attacks that terrified Southern
California in the summer of 1985.
   Testimony began Jan. 30 after six months of jury selection.
   A doctor's report submitted to the judge said attorney Daniel
Hernandez is suffering from stress-related nervous exhaustion
resulting from his participation in the long-delayed trial. The
doctor recommended psychological counseling and said recovery could
take six weeks.
   ``The doctor feels he is not presently able to function
effectively as trial counsel,'' said Superior Court Judge Michael
Tynan, who declined to disclose the doctor's name.
   Jurors had been excused since Hernandez called in sick Tuesday.
   ``This is a novel experience for the court,'' said Tynan, adding
that he would hold hearings before he decides on a remedy for the
situation.
   He ordered Hernandez and his former co-counsel, Arturo Hernandez,
no relation, to be in court Wednesday for an inquiry on the state of
Hernandez' health and the trial's future.
   Arturo Hernandez disappeared from the case without public
explanation during jury selection. He remains a counsel of record in
the case, but Halpin said it was unlikely that he would be ordered
to take over for his ailing colleague.
   During the 1985 crime spree, an intruder entered homes at night
through unlocked windows or doors, then raped women, killed men and
women with gunshots to the head, and stole jewelry and other
valuables. One victim's eyes were gouged out, and the killer often
left behind drawings of pentagrams, inverted five-pointed stars
associated with devil worship.
   The press dubbed the killer the ``Night Stalker,'' and people in
the Los Angeles area shut their windows at night despite a heat
wave. Terror spread through the state as related crimes were
reported in San Francisco and Orange County, where charges against
Ramirez are pending.
   Ramirez was arrested after he was chased and beaten by an angry
mob in East Los Angeles during the 1985 Labor Day weekend, when his
picture first appeared in newspapers as the prime suspect in the
crime wave.
   During his 1985 arraignment, Ramirez yelled ``Hail Satan!'' and
flashed a picture of a pentagram drawn on his palm. Several women
testified at his 1986 preliminary hearing that after their husbands
were murdered, they were raped and ordered to ``Swear to Satan.''
</TEXT>
