<FIRST>r w AM-AdmiralDisciplined     02-27 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Admiral Disciplined,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Admiral Reimburses Navy for Moving Expenses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired four-star Navy admiral has reimbursed
the government $3,400 for using military personnel to help him move
files and other possessions from Honolulu to begin his retirement,
the Navy said Monday.
   The service, in a brief statement, said retired Adm. James A.
``Ace'' Lyons Jr. ``was requested to reimburse the excess costs
incurred by the government'' and has ``voluntarily paid'' $3,420.94
to the Navy.
   The Navy said Lyons made the payment after Navy Secretary William
L. Ball III ``determined that some of the benefits received by Adm.
Lyons upon his retirement exceeded entitlements.''
   Lyons, the former head of the Navy's Pacific Fleet in Honolulu,
Hawaii, left his job on Oct. 1, 1987 on short notice not long after
John F. Lehman resigned as Navy secretary. Lyons' departure also
came soon after he publicly complained about the manner in which the
Navy was overseeing operation of warships assigned to the Persian
Gulf.
   According to the Navy, an anonymous complaint shortly after the
admiral stepped down from active duty alleged that Lyons had
improperly shipped personal property on a military plane.
   The Navy said that Lyons had shipped some personal property on a
Navy plane when he left Honolulu, but that those aircraft flights
had not been ordered just for Lyons' benefit and the ``additional
costs were minimal.''
   He was asked to reimburse the $3,400, however, because the
investigation also found that Lyons had asked ``four military
personnel'' to help him in traveling from Honolulu to Washington to
start his retirement.
   Lyons has said he had only a week's notice to prepare for
retirement and that he did, in fact, ask four servicemen to help him
move his files and other possessions from Hawaii.
</TEXT>
