<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--PipelineShutdown     02-27 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Pipeline Shutdown,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storm Shuts Oil Pipeline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow driven by wind blasts of more than
110 mph shut down a pumping station on the trans-Alaska oil pipeline
and halted the flow of oil in the line for several hours during the
weekend, an official said.
   ``It cost some people a lot of sleep,'' said Tom Brennan,
spokesman for the Alyeska Pipeline Service Co.
   The wind was part of a huge storm that pounded the Arctic Ocean
coast during the weekend, ripping aluminum roofing from homes in
Barrow and knocking at least one residence off its pilings.
   Brennan said the wind gusted to more than 110 mph at the Prudhoe
Bay oil field.
   One of three pumps at Pump Station One failed Saturday when snow
got into its ventilation system, melted and caused an electrical
short, he said. The station's other two pumps failed that night when
air intakes froze shut on their booster pumps, he said.
</TEXT>
