<DOCNO> AP890227-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1701EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     02-27 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEAR SPRING, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Good things come in threes at Rocky
Haven Farm, where triplet brothers Donald, Robert and John Smith
acted like proud papas after their 1,300-pound Holstein named Candy
gave birth to triplet calves.
   ``I don't know if it's any big thing or not, but it seems kind of
rare,'' said Donald Smith, 35, the eldest of the human siblings by
five minutes.
   David Burrows, the brothers' veterinarian, said cows give birth
to triplets about one in every 50,000 births. Burrows said he
usually sees at least one set of triplet cows a year _ none owned by
triplet farmers.
   The brothers, who live about 10 miles west of Hagerstown in
western Maryland, usually sell bull calves a few days after birth,
but hope they can find a university or feed company to buy the
calves for research, such as testing how triplets grow and respond
to feeding patterns.
   The calves, which were born last week, haven't been named or
tagged, but the Smiths can tell them apart. All are black and white,
but one has a larger black spot on its rump and the youngest of the
trio is the smallest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forget about a roof over your head and three
square meals. America's wealthy these days say they simply can't
survive without their microwave ovens, VCRs and answering machines,
a study shows.
   ``What just a few years ago were clearly novelties or luxuries
have today become necessities of speed and convenience,'' said
William S. Doyle, president of the company that initiated the study
of households with annual incomes above $100,000.
   According to the figures compiled for the Doyle Graf Raj
advertising agency by The Roper Organization:
   _57 percent said they couldn't live without a microwave oven.
   _49 percent called their answering machines a necessity.
   _42 percent absolutely needed their home computers.
   _36 percent considered their videotape recorders indispensable.
   Those four items ranked above such important but apparently
dispensible matters as sending children to an elite college (30
percent) or a private school (25 percent).
   The survey of 600 adults represented 100 households apiece in New
York, Chicago, Washington, Houston, Los Angeles and San Francisco.
It has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
   The study asked the participants to choose between luxuries _
``things they could live without'' _ and necessities _ ``things that
have become so important they are thought to be necessities.''
</TEXT>
