<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Tower     02-27 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Tower,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nearing A Time For Decisions _ With No One To Make Them</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon is inching closer to several
deadlines for important policy decisions as John Tower's nomination
to become defense secretary founders on Capitol Hill.
   Foremost among those decisions are several involving the 1990
budget.
   While the four military services have prepared recommendations to
achieve the spending cuts promised by Bush, officials would normally
be receiving guidance from a defense secretary by now.
   ``If this drags on much longer, I don't know when we're going to
get a budget,'' observed one official who works in the financial
arena and who spoke only on the condition of anonymity.
   Tower's nomination comes before the full Senate Wednesday. The
Armed Services Committee recommended by an 11-9 vote last week that
he not be confirmed.
   ``Is the department functioning? Sure,'' observed one source who
insisted upon anonymity. ``We are awarding contracts every day and
training people to fight every day.
   ``But, without a secretary of defense, we don't have any kind of
new team in the top bureaucratic positions. And that means months of
delays down the road in having people geared up to deal with budget
and policy matters.''
   Beyond the budget problems, the Bush administration is facing
deadlines for policy decisions and debates have begun without the
Pentagon really being represented, said several sources, all of whom
spoke on the condition they not be named.
   For example, Bush is scheduled to report Wednesday his view of a
proposal to develop a limited Star Wars defense system known as the
Accident Launch Protection System. On March 15, the president is to
provide a study of how a new nuclear arms treaty with the Soviets
would affect the structure of U.S. nuclear forces.
   By early May, Bush has promised completion of a special 90-day
national security policy review. And at some point soon, he must
advise Congress whether he wants to develop the single-warhead
Midgetman missile or a rail-car version of the huge MX missile.
   Finally, the administration has pledged to oversee reform of the
Pentagon's weapons-buying process in the wake of the continuing
federal fraud investigation.
   ``We need somebody in the job,'' said one official. ``You can't
muddle through forever.''
</TEXT>
