<FIRST>r a AM-MarineLesbian     02-27 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marine Lesbian,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Female Marine Captain Says She Wanted to Face Accusers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Marine Corps captain facing possible
dismissal for associating with lesbians said Monday she wanted a
court-martial instead of the board of inquiry that ruled against her.
   ``I wanted to see my accusers,'' Capt. Judy Meade said in a
telephone interview. ``Instead (the prosecutor) put in statements.
(The witnesses) made many statements but (prosecutors) just took
what they wanted to put in.''
   A board of five colonels recommended Sunday that Ms. Meade
receive an ``other than honorable'' discharge after concluding that
her association with lesbians constituted conduct unbecoming an
officer.
   Ms. Meade's attorney, Vaughn Taylor, criticized the proceedings
during the five-day hearing last week, saying it did not allow for
the defense to cross-examine witnesses.
   The board of inquiry differs from a court-martial in that five
Marine officers hear the government's presentation and then rule.
The board has a legal adviser available to them.
   Ms. Meade said she was not allowed to subpoena witnesses.
   Maj. Stuart Wagner, a Camp Lejeune spokesman, said there wasn't
enough evidence to have a court-martial for a criminal charge.
   ``It isn't a crime (to associate with a lesbian) and this was not
a criminal procedure,'' Wagner said. ``This was an administrative
procedure ... akin to an employer deciding if an employee had
further service. ... I think what was in question was her judgment
and the effect that that judgment had with her personal relations
and her Marine Corps relations.''
   Professor Barry Nakell of the University of North Carolina School
of Law, a civil rights specialist, said he thought Ms. Meade's
choice of friends should be constitutionally protected by the right
of freedom of association.
   ``My position would be that as long as there is nothing about the
... friendships that would compromise security and there is nothing
to show what her sexual preference is, it should be constitutionally
protected,'' he said.
   But Wagner said a question of leadership was involved.
   ``I don't think the question at any time was whether Capt. Meade
was a homosexual,'' Wagner said. ``The question was whether her
relationship and the consequences of that relationship affected her
ability to be an effective Marine officer and remain in the Marine
Corps. The Marine Corps is a way of life.''
   Ms. Meade said she hopes for an honorable discharge for her 12
years of service. The final decision will be made by the secretary
of the Navy.
   Ms. Meade, 36, a military police officer, said she is angry over
the treatment she has received, but also said she would not
criticize the corps.
   ``The Marine Corps is a good organization. I'm never going to put
the Marine Corps down. It's not the organization, it's just some
individuals in it,'' she said.
   Most of the allegations against Ms. Meade stemmed from a February
1988 visit she made to the home of Paula Berry of Beaufort, S.C.
   Government witnesses said they saw Ms. Meade in Ms. Berry's bed
with her then.
   Both Ms. Berry and Ms. Meade acknowledged during the hearing that
Ms. Berry is a lesbian, but denied that the two ever had sexual
contact. Ms. Berry said they slept in the same bed once when Ms.
Meade fell asleep watching television.
   The board also said Ms. Meade had failed to report suspected
lesbian activity, and had misled her superior officers by
withholding information that Ms. Berry was a lesbian. It also said
Ms. Meade frequented a bar which was ``known by her to have a
questionable reputation.''
   Ms. Meade said she plans to pursue a career in security or law
enforcement.
</TEXT>
