<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1858EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--RanchFire     02-27 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Ranch Fire,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire At Troubled Stanford Ranch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire officials said Monday they don't
suspect arson in a blaze that destroyed a house on a ranch embroiled
in a labor dispute with migrant workers.
   The fire caused at least $110,000 damage to a single-story home
at Webb Ranch early Sunday when its residents, Gary Webb and his
family, were away. No one was injured. The ranch is operated by
Gary's father, Stanley Webb, on land owned by Stanford University.
   California Department of Forestry fire investigator Mike Martin
said nothing indicates arson, ``but I'm not ruling it out because of
all the attention the media has given the ranch lately.''
   Workers at the ranch have sued the Webbs and the university,
charging that they have been intimidated and threatened with loss of
jobs. A hearing is set for March 20.
   They claim harassment began after United Stanford Workers told
reporters Webb workers are subjected to unfair employment practices
and inadequate housing. The Webbs have denied the charges.
</TEXT>
