<FIRST>r a AM-MrsLetterman     02-27 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mrs Letterman,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Arraigned After Arrest At David Letterman's Home ... Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was arrested after she was
found wandering around the home of television talk show host David
Letterman was released Monday.
   Margaret Ray, 36, was released on her own recognizance at an
arraignment hearing in Superior Court.
   But Judge Edward Levitt also suggested that Ray re-enroll in the
psychiatric program at Fairfield Hills Hospital. She had been
released from the state hospital last fall.
   Ray, who was caught driving Letterman's car and breaking into his
house last year, was arrested again Friday night when she was found
wandering around the foyer of his home in southwestern Connecticut,
police said.
   She was charged with one felony count of first-degree trespass
and one misdemeanor count each of possession of marijuana and
possession of drug paraphernalia, police said.
   Ray was scheduled for another court appearance Friday to enter a
plea, according to her attorney, Anita Cason.
   On May 22, 1988, Ray was arrested on the New Jersey side of the
Lincoln Tunnel as she was driving into New York in Letterman's 1988
Porsche with her 3-year-old son. The toll collector thought it was
suspicious that a woman driving an $80,000 automobile did not have
the $3 toll.
   Police said Ray identified herself as Letterman's wife and
introduced her son as David Letterman Jr.
   After the incident, New Canaan police discovered that someone had
broken a living room window to enter Letterman's three-bedroom home.
Police said Ray apparently had moved into the house with her son and
lived there for a couple of days while Letterman was out of town.
   Although Letterman refused to press charges against Ray for the
first incident, Ray was arrested by New Canaan police three days
later after she took a taxi to Letterman's house.
   In September, Levitt ordered Ray to give up contact with
Letterman except through the mail and to remain at Fairfield Hills,
where she had been undergoing psychiatric treatment since August
1988.
</TEXT>
