<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos-Condominium     02-27 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos-Condominium,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos-Linked Condo Sold For $3.7 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippine government on Monday sold for $3.7
million a Manhattan condominium said to have been purchased by
then-President Ferdinand Marcos with money looted from his nation's
treasury.
   It was the second piece of Marcos-linked real estate in the
United States sold by the Philippine Commission on Good Government.
The first, a house in Princeton, N.J., was sold in 1987 for $1
million.
   Teresa Roxas, a commission official, said the seven-bedroom
apartment on the 43rd floor of the Olympic Towers, a glass tower
next to St. Patricks Cathedral on Fifth Avenue, was purchased for
$3.675 million as a home for a buyer who asked not to be identified.
   The apartment was surrendered to the Philippine government in
1986 by a Marcos associate, Antonio Floirendo, as part of a deal to
avoid prosecution. It was among several properties allegedly owned
by Marcos through fronts.
   Roxas said two other such residences are on the market _
Lindenmere, an estate on Long Island, with an asking price of $4.5
million, and a home in Honolulu, for $2.5 million.
   The commission is fighting in court to gain title to four
commercial buildings in Manhattan that are worth an estimated $400
million.
   The New York holdings allegedly were purchased with some of the
$10 billion that the Philippine government alleges Marcos and his
associates embezzled before he was ousted and fled to Hawaii in 1986.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, has pleaded innocent in New York to federal
racketeering charges and is free on $5 million bail. Lawyers have
argued that Marcos, 71, is too ill to appear in court, and he is
currently hospitalized in Honolulu.
   In Manila, Nievelena Rosete, a commission member, said profits
from the condominium sale will help finance the government's land
reform program.
</TEXT>
