<FIRST>r a AM-People-Hale     02-27 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Hale,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honor For New York City Woman Who Cares For Drug-Addicted Babies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDEPENDENCE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clara Hale, an 83-year-old New York City
woman who cares for drug-addicted babies, has been named the 1989
winner of the Truman Award for Public Service.
   Her choice was announced Monday by a selection commission
including Barbara Potts, mayor of Independence, the Kansas City
suburb that was the home to the late President Harry Truman.
   Mrs. Hale is founder of Hale House, a refuge for infants and
toddlers born chemically dependent. She and her daughter, Lorraine
Hale, will attend an award ceremony May 6 at the Truman Library and
Museum.
   Clara Hale raised more than 40 children as a foster parent in
Harlem from 1941 to 1968. The following year her daughter met a
woman and her addicted baby and referred them to her mother for
care. Since then ``Mother Hale'' has provided a home for more than
600 babies born to addicted mothers.
   In most cases, the children are reunited with their mothers after
the mothers have undergone drug rehabilitation.
</TEXT>
