<FIRST>r w AM-Sullivan     02-27 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sullivan,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sullivan Heads for Confirmation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis Sullivan, apparently heading for
confirmation as health and human services secretary, repeated his
opposition to abortion and fielded a broad range of questions on
other topics from a Senate committee Monday.
   The abortion issue, which has dogged the Atlanta doctor since his
nomination was announced, got only brief mention at the hearing
before the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee, as it did
before the Senate Finance Committee last week.
   In his opening statement, Sullivan said that ``abortion is wrong
and that it is inconsistent with the best of family values.''
   He said that, like President Bush, he opposes abortion except in
cases of rape, incest or danger to the life of a mother, and is
against federal funding of abortions except to save a mother's life.
   Later, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, asked Sullivan to restate his
views on abortion, which the doctor did, adding that he has never
performed the procedure.
   In response to subsequent questions from Hatch, Sullivan also
said he would welcome a Supreme Court decision overturning its 1973
ruling that legalized abortion. He said he supported the Health and
Human Services Department's position that family planning funds
should not be used for abortions.
   Sullivan, however, again sidestepped the question of whether the
federal government should pay for research that uses tissue from
aborted fetuses. He said he would not state a position on the issue
until he had read the recommendations of an advisory committee.
   Hatch, a fervent opponent of abortion, said he was satisfied with
Sullivan's views and fully supported his nomination.
   The Finance Committee last week recommended full Senate approval
of Sullivan's nomination on a 19-0 vote, and Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., chairman of the labor committee, predicted a unanimous
Senate vote for Sullivan on Tuesday.
   Both committees have jurisdiction over department programs, but
the Finance Committee is the panel that recommends action on the
nomination to the full Senate. Kennedy's committee will not vote
separately on the nomination.
   His committee covered much of the same ground that the Finance
Committee did, devoting little time to abortion, the issue that has
caused Sullivan the most problems. Last week, he apologized to Sen.
Bob Packwood, R-Ore., saying he ``misspoke'' in private remarks on
the subject. He was quoted earlier in an interview with The Atlanta
Journal Constitution as supporting a woman's right to abortion.
   On Monday, senators focused more attention on President Bush's
fiscal 1990 budget proposal that would trim anticipated Medicare
spending by $5 billion and the effects of soaring medical costs on
the federal budget.
</TEXT>
