<FIRST>r a AM-Survey-Clymer     02-27 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Survey-Clymer,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Clarifies Statement On Minimum Wage, Admits It Was `Terrible'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Rep. Paul Clymer admitted Monday he
reached ``the wrong conclusions'' when he suggested Pennsylvania's
minimum wage was adequate because minorities, slow learners and
students take home the paychecks.
   But some black legislators labeled Clymer's remarks ``racist''
and rooted in ``a slave mentality.''
   ``It's sad, really sad,'' said Sen. Hardy Williams, a black
Democrat from Philadelphia. ``His reasoning has no place in our
society. What he's saying is that he wants to underpay a whole class
of society.''
   Clymer, a five-term Republican from a largely rural,
predominantly white district in Bucks County, made the statements
about lower-wage earners in a survey of state lawmakers by The
Associated Press. Answering a question about the state's $3.70
hourly minimum wage, which was boosted 35 cents in February, he
responded:
   ``The 35-cent increase is adequate. Remember, the people earning
minimum wage are minorities, slow learners, students and part-time
employees.''
   Clymer went on to say that the federal government should be
setting the minimum wage, and that any further increases at the
state level would send a negative signal to business.
   In an interview Monday, Clymer admitted his statements appeared
``terrible,'' but he denied that any malice was involved.
   ``I just didn't put it right,'' he said. ``I thought it through,
but the conclusions I wanted to draw were not there. They were the
wrong conclusions. It's unfortunate I did not take more time; what I
should have done is take more time.''
   Clymer said he had been trying to explain that the minimum wage
sometimes provides the only employment opportunities for workers in
areas with high unemployment or where jobs are scarce.
   The minimum wage ``would give them a chance. This doesn't mean
that they shouldn't be making more money,'' he said.
   Clymer stopped short of apologizing for the remarks, saying he
meant no harm and had simply misstated his position.
   But Williams said the remarks showed ``a slave mentality'' and
were ``very racist.''
   Rep. David Richardson, a Philadelphia Democrat who chairs the
National Black Caucus of State Legislators, said Clymer should
retract the statement and apologize.
   ``It is very clear to me that this recent outburst of racial
intimidation and racial slurs ... is a shame, abominable and a
disgrace,'' he said.
   Althea Simmons, director of the Washington office of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said the remarks
carried ``racial overtones.''
   And David Wilderman, a spokesman for the state AFL-CIO, said
``there's a cross section of Pennsylvania men and women who are
working at the minimum wage,'' not only the groups listed by Clymer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
