<FIRST>r a AM-Tower-Doctor     02-27 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower-Doctor,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Becomes Key To Tower's Offensive For Defense Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tower, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The doctor whose opinion on the health of John
Tower's liver has become a key to the defense secretary-designate's
last-ditch effort to rescue his nomination said he didn't know how
the information would be used.
   Dr. Warren Lichliter, who is not Tower's primary physician, said
he was unaware until notified by reporters Sunday that the opinion
had become a weapon in Tower's new offensive for the post.
   Tower, on ABC-TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley'' and CNN's
``Newsmaker Sunday,'' launched a campaign Sunday to overcome last
week's 11-9 rejection by the Senate Armed Services Committee when
his appointment comes before the full Senate.
   On both shows, Tower read portions of a letter from Lichliter,
who is on the staff of Baylor University Medical Center here, saying
that an examination after Tower's recent colon surgery showed ``no
evidence at all of alcoholic impairment or alcoholism.''
   Tower then issued a pledge to swear off alcohol if he is approved
as defense secretary.
   Lichliter said he didn't see the shows. ``I'm just finding out
about all this,'' he told the Dallas Times Herald.
   Lichliter said he prepared the statement only because Dr. R.D.
Dignan, who removed a benign lump from Tower's colon in January, was
out of town when Tower's staff called, asking for the letter to be
sent by facsimile machine. Lichliter said he routinely takes calls
in Dignan's absence.
   Dignan, Tower's primary physician, released a statement earlier
this month saying tests ``indicated no abnormalities within organ
systems that might be involved with alcohol abuse.''
   Lichliter said he spoke Sunday with Dignan about his letter, and
said Dignan backed it ``100 percent.''
   Phone calls to both doctors' offices Monday were referred to
Baylor University Medical Center spokesman Steve Habgood, who said
neither Lichliter nor Dignan would have any further comment.
   ``Both have indicated that their previous statements stand as
is,'' Habgood said.
</TEXT>
