<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1934EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0630 02-27 0873</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Soviet, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0630,0896</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Ends Visit to Tehran</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to include British request that Soviets bring
up Rushdie case; picks up 10th `His success'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze of
the Soviet Union ended a visit to Iran on Monday that he said forged
closer relations despite ``ideological differences.''
   Tehran's official Islamic Republic News Agency reported that
Shevardnadze also said in meetings with President Ali Khamenei and
Hashemi Rafsanjani, the Parliament speaker, that U.S. naval forces
should withdraw from the Persian Gulf.
   Shevardnadze was the highest Soviet official to visit Iran since
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's fundamentalist Islamic revolution
overthrew the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi in February 1979.
   ``We believe relations between Iran and the Soviet Union have
been substantially transformed,'' he said before leaving for Moscow.
   IRNA said Shevardnadze renewed an invitation to Rafsanjani to
visit Moscow and the speaker accepted.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said the two governments
can ``constructively cooperate'' on many international problems.
   With Iran confronting the West over Khomeini's order that Salman
Rushdie be killed for his novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' which many
Moslems say blasphemes Islam, Soviet-Iranian relations are at their
best since the revolution.
   Khomeini and Shevardnadze met Sunday, but Iranian reports
indicated they did not discuss the Rushdie controversy despite
Britain's request to the Soviet foreign minister that he bring it up.
   After meeting Khamanei on Monday, Shevardnadze conferred with
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati and signed political and
cultural agreements, IRNA reported. The agreements underscored ``new
horizons in political ties between Tehran and Moscow,'' Shevardnadze
was quoted as saying.
   His success in bolstering Soviet-Iranian relations climaxed a
10-day, five-nation Middle East tour aimed at widening the Soviet
role in a region that has long been considered a U.S. preserve.
   IRNA did not quote Shevardnadze as saying what differences remain
between Iran and the Soviet Union, but the communist bloc's state
atheism is anathema to Iran's fundamentalist Moslem leaders. The
Soviets were the main arms suppliers to Iraq during the war with
Iran.
   Many Iranian leaders, while prepared to bolster ties with the
Soviets, remain wary of their giant northern neighbor who briefly
occupied part of their country after World War II. The Soviet
withdrawal from Afghanistan, Iran's eastern Islamic neighbor, has
eliminated a major source of friction.
   ``We have come to the conclusion that it is a must to acknowledge
others' beliefs and respect them,'' Shevardnadze said. ``In our
opinion, Iran enjoys high international prestige.''
   He said the Soviets would push for progress in the Iran-Iraq
peace talks, which have been stalled since the Aug. 20 cease-fire.
   Khamenei called on the Soviets to pressure Iraq to stop its
alleged stalling in the negotiations so that a peace treaty can be
signed.
   Shevardnadze reiterated his call in Baghdad for the withdrawal of
foreign forces from the gulf. He had said in Baghdad that Moscow was
willing to withdraw its ships.
   ``We have explicitly announced to the American president that we
condemn the U.S. military presence in the Persian Gulf, and will
continue this policy until the Americans withdraw their troops from
the region,'' he said.
   The United States has 23 warships in and around the gulf. The
Soviets have seven to nine. Most European warships have left.
   The major powers either sent warships into the gulf or increased
their naval squadrons to protect merchant ships from Iranian attacks
launched in retaliation for Iraqi air raids.
   IRNA said that Khamenei told Shevardnadze that ``Iraq must be
pressured'' to break the deadlock in the peace talks, ``and we think
your government can exert this pressure more than anyone else.'' The
Soviet Union has a friendship treaty with Baghdad and is believed to
be one of its largest creditors.
   Tehran radio broadcast excerpts of the meeting between
Shevardnadze and Khomeini. IRNA said Shevardnadze was the first
foreign official to talk to Khomeini at his home.
   Khomeini seldom meets foreign dignitaries, and it was the first
he had been heard speaking publicly in months.
   IRNA said Khomeini agreed to meet Shevardnadze because he wanted
to hear a response to a message he sent to Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev in January.
   Shevardnadze said Khomeini's message, praising Gorbachev's
reforms and urging him to accept Islam, had received a ``good
response'' from Soviet leaders who read it, although they did not
agree with all of it.
   Khomeini stressed the importance of ``the expansion of strong
ties in various dimensions in confronting the devilish acts of the
West,'' Tehran radio said.
   Iran's Majlis, or parliament, votes Tuesday on a bill to sever
relations with Britain for publishing ``The Satanic Verses'' and
leading European nations in recalling their senior diplomats from
Tehran to protest the Khomeini's ``kill Rushdie'' religious decree.
   Tehran newspapers Monday supported severing ties. IRNA quoted
Qorban-Ali Saleh-Abadi, a member of parliament, as predicting
relations will be broken off. ``God willing, we will approve this
bill tomorrow,'' he said.
   Britain recalled its diplomats from Tehran and asked Iran's to
leave London after Khomeini issued his execution order Feb. 14.
   Fourteen other Western nations have withdrawn their top diplomats
from Iran in the furor over Khomeini's death sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
