<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Low-IncomePhones     02-27 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Low-Income Phones,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Eases Requirements for Phone-Installation Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Monday said low-income
applicants for subsidized telephone service no longer will have to
show they've had no phone for the previous three months or that
they've received no federal phone aid for two years.
   The Federal Communications Commission said those requirements for
``Link Up America'' aid were denying service to 15 percent of all
applicants.
   The year-old federal assistance plan is designed to encourage
low-income households to obtain telephone service by helping pay for
installation.
   Qualifying households may receive up to $30 to help defray such
costs.
   Gerald Brock, chief of the FCC's common carrier bureau, said
there were 385,000 people in 37 states, the District of Columbia and
Puerto Rico in the program.
   Brock said the commission decided to loosen the requirements when
it was shown it would not cost the government very much.
   ``We are finding that it has been an effective program but it has
not been so well used that the financial requirements were
overwhelming,'' Brock told reporters. ``That's one of the reasons
why we put more restrictions on at the beginning.''
   In another action Monday, the FCC ruled that radio equipment used
to provide phone service to remote areas will be considered as
belonging to the telephone companies, and consumers will not have to
buy it.
   The commission made its ruling on a petition filed by the
Colorado consulting firm of Tallon, Cheeseman &amp; Associates regarding
the Basic Exchange Telecommunications Radio Service.
   The commission said the antenna and radio equipment located on or
near the premises of users of the service should be treated as
regulated network equipment and is eligible for federal and state
programs designed to assist telephone companies that provide service
in high-cost areas.
   The company estimated the cost of this equipment to range from
$2,200 to $2,400, the commission said.
   The ruling means the FCC will increase the federal assistance
available to rural phone companies and their customers to install
such equipment, and the users will pay the same basic service
charges as regular phone users in the area.
</TEXT>
