<FIRST>r w AM-Americans-PLO     02-27 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Americans-PLO,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Tells Scholars Uprising on West Bank Will Not Be Curbed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization will not
call a halt to the uprising on the West Bank and in Gaza before
Israel agrees to negotiate, a group of scholars who met recently
with Yasser Arafat said Monday.
   The 15-month uprising could be ``notched up a bit or notched
down'' as part of the PLO's strategy for drawing Israel into
negotiations, former White House official William B. Quandt said.
   However, recounting recent talks in Tunis with Arafat and other
PLO officials, Quandt said they did not offer to call off the
``intefadeh,'' in which 386 Palestinian Arabs and 17 Israelis have
died, if Israel yielded.
   Quandt, who was an analyst on the Middle East and the Persian
Gulf at the National Security Council, was accompanied to Tunis for
the PLO meetings by former Assistant Secretary of State Harold H.
Saunders and Helena Cobban, a scholar. They are now at the Brookings
Institution, a private research group.
   Israel has refused to negotiate with the PLO, accusing it of
terrorism and citing a provision in the PLO covenant calling for the
destruction of the Jewish state. The United States last December
opened talks with the PLO.
   However, Quandt said the talks had fallen short of PLO
expectations and U.S. promises. He said he found Arafat and other
PLO officials ``a bit frustrated and disappointed with the virtual
non-existence of the U.S.-PLO dialogue.''
   The former Carter administration official added: ``They had been
promised at the time the dialogue began there would be substantive
talks. There have been virtually none.''
   Asked about Quandt's account, Charles E. Redman, the State
Department spokesman, said he ``couldn't speak to someone else's
expectations.''
   The U.S. official said the government decision to talk to the PLO
``was made at the end of the previous administration, and we're now
in the early stages of a new administration. But beyond that, I
don't really have any way to interpret somebody else's
expectations.''
   On a related subject, Saunders said the PLO envisioned a
two-state solution to its dispute with Israel, with no Berlin Wall
or barbed wires in between.
   ``Amyone who commits a terrorist act against Israel would be
punished,'' Saunders said.
   The PLO leaders told the American delegation they had hoped in
the past to create a single secular state, Saunders said. But they
said in Tunis ``we are transformed'' and are prepared to live in
permanent peace alongside Israel, he said.
   Saunders said Arafat envisioned open borders and full diplomatic
relations with Israel, plus economic relations with Jordan as well.
</TEXT>
