<FIRST>r a AM-SpyPlane     02-27 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spy Plane,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Spy Plane To Be Mothballed After Near Quarter-Century Of Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY39</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIC LEYVA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The SR-71 Blackbird, a futuristic-looking spy
plane whose speed records have never been broken and which can
photograph a license plate from 17 miles up, will retire after
nearly 25 years of service, the Air Force said Monday.
   The black, twin-engine jet was the original stealth aircraft and
was never armed because it can easily outrace enemy missiles and
fighters, Air Force officials said.
   Exact figures are classified, but the Air Force reportedly will
save up to $300 million a year by retiring the SR-71 squadron on
Oct. 1.
   Defense budget priorities are forcing the SR-71 fleet into
mothballs and satellites will take over its duties, a Pentagon
spokesman said.
   ``We will rely on existing reconnaissance capabilities, which I
can't be real specific about, but you can assume that it is mainly
satellite capability,'' Air Force Lt. Col. Joe Purka said in a
telephone interview.
   Although still largely shrouded in secrecy, some details of the
elusive photo reconnaissance plane have been made public and it was
even featured in a 1984-85 television series, ``Call to Glory,''
about an Air Force family.
   Despite its age _ the first one was delivered in 1966 _ it still
holds world records for jet-powered speed and altitude, set in 1976
with a speed of 2,193 mph and an altitude of 85,000 feet.
   In September 1974, a Blackbird flew from London to Los Angeles in
3 hours, 47 minutes, or, taking into account the time zones it
crossed, four hours before it left.
   Air Force pilot Lt. Col. Bill Orcutt says the jet carries
considerable mystique despite its vintage.
   ``It looks like something from outer space,'' Orcutt said
recently. ``The SR-71 excites the boy in all of us who love to fly.''
   At peak altitude, pilots can view the curvature of the Earth, and
when they look straight up they see the blackness of space.
   The Blackbird's speed of more than 2,000 mph is three times the
speed of sound, or 33 miles a minute, faster than a rifle bullet. It
can survey 100 square miles an hour, he said.
   The Air Force tried to retire the Blackbird squadron last year,
but was overruled by Congress.
   House Armed Services subcommittee staffer Jim Waters said no such
move has been made in Washington so far, but couldn't predict
whether Congress would fight the planned retirement.
   ``It's a very costly system to operate, but there are people,
both in the military and in Congress, that want to keep it around,''
Waters said.
   Nine or 10 Blackbirds reportedly remain from the original lot of
about 30.
   The SR-71 squadron is headquartered at Beale Air Force Base near
Marysville in northern California. Its support facilities are at Air
Force Plant 42, about 50 miles north of Los Angeles in Palmdale.
   Plant 42 is the site of the Air Force's stealth research and
development, which began with Blackbird's sleek design and
radar-evading capabilities, officials said.
   The supersecret plane built by Lockheed Corp. as a successor to
the U-2 was officially acknowledged by then-President Lyndon Johnson
on July 24, 1964.
   Development began in February 1963, and the first model was
delivered in January 1966, Purka said.
   Operated under the Strategic Air Command, the SR-71s also operate
out of bases in England and Japan, said SAC spokeswoman Maj. Suzanne
Randall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
