<FIRST>r a AM-Aflatoxin-Corn     02-27 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aflatoxin-Corn,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Officials Say Food Supply Safe from Aflatoxin Health Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public health is not threatened by
aflatoxin, a cancer-causing substance found in part of the nation's
corn supply, agricultural leaders said Monday.
   Directors of agriculture from key farm states said recent reports
that corn containing aflatoxin had escaped detection and gotten into
food products were misleading.
   ``Consumers need not be afraid that tainted products are in the
food chain,'' said Dale Cochran, Iowa secretary of agriculture.
``Yes, I'm quite convinced ... that the supply is being checked
quite carefully.''
   The heat and drought of 1988 provided ideal conditions for
development of the fungus that produces aflatoxin, which has been
linked to the development of liver cancer in laboratory rats.
   The Wall Street Journal reported last week that aflatoxin-tainted
corn is moving through the nation's food supply.
   The newspaper, which conducted a five-month-investigation,
reported that inadequate sampling and unreliable testing of corn
after the harvest contributed to the distribution of tainted grain.
   But Illinois agriculture director Larry Werries said tests by the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration showed no aflatoxin contamination
of finished food products in his state.
   Werries said his own agency's tests of milk samples also showed
no contamination. Dairy cattle are fed corn, and he said that should
be ``the first place it shows.''
   The limit for aflatoxin is 20 parts per billion for corn that
will be used in food production or will be fed to dairy cattle, said
Werries. Under current regulations, corn with higher levels of
aflatoxin may be fed to meat-producing animals such as cattle and
hogs.
   So even if a farmer sold corn with more than 20 parts per billion
of aflatoxin, ``the elevator likely has an outlet for it,'' said
Werries.
   ``In my opinion, the system works,'' he said.
   Cochran said tests by his agency in Iowa showed 98 percent of the
milk samples were safe. Milk from three farms was tainted, so it was
not distributed and other milk sales by those farms was stopped, he
said.
   Missouri's director of agriculture, Charles Kruse, said there
probably was no greater problem with aflatoxin in his state this
year than in some previous years.
   ``There is a greater awareness ... than perhaps there was five or
10 years ago,'' said Kruse. ``There is certainly more testing going
on now.''
   The Journal said some experts do not believe the government or
the grain industry can deal adequately with the aflatoxin outbreak
of 1988.
   ``There is just no way of policing a massive system of commerce
and trade,'' plant pathologist David Wilson of the University of
Georgia told the newspaper.
   Officials at the world's largest cereal mill _ Quaker Oats Co. in
Cedar Rapids, Iowa _ say they test incoming corn for aflatoxin.
   ``It's the most serious thing we look for,'' plant manager
Kenneth Dykes told the Journal. ``I don't think farmers and
elevators do screen for aflatoxin.''
   But Steve Wentworth, an Illinois farmer and president of the
National Corn Growers Association, said there is extensive aflatoxin
testing by both the government and private industry.
   And he said it was misleading to suggest that farmers are
ignorant of the problem or are willing to try to sell corn that
exceeds federal limits for aflatoxin.
   ``Farmers are consumers and want the nation's food supply to be
as safe as possible,'' Wentworth said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
