<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Imhausen     02-27 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Imhausen,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Head of Firm Implicated in Libyan Scandal Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAHR, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a Black Forest chemical
company suspected of helping Libya build a poison gas plant will
resign at the end of next month, the company announced Monday night.
   Juergen Hippenstiel-Imhausen will leave his post as director of
the Imhausen-Chemie company of Lahr, spokesman Moritz Hunzinger told
reporters.
   Hippenstiel did not appear at the news conference and has not
been seen in public since mid-January, when suspicions mounted that
his firm organized construction and outfitting of a chemical weapons
plant in Rabta, Libya.
   No charges have been filed against anyone at Imhausen or other
West German firms said to have played a role in building the plant,
which Libyan officials say is intended to produce medicines.
   Imhausen officials said last month that Hippenstiel fled with his
family after receiving death threats, but he is believed to have
since returned to West Germany.
   His resignation, effective March 31, appears to be the result of
pressure from the federal Research and Development Ministry, which
refused to pay the firm for three projects it has under contract
with Imhausen as long as Hippenstiel remained in charge.
   The local parliamentary representative and business council also
demanded that Hippenstiel step down.
   Federal authorities have been investigating U.S. allegations that
Imhausen played a key role in the Rabta plant, but they say no
evidence has been uncovered that could stand up in court.
   Officials conceded privately they fear any incriminating evidence
may have been taken out of the country prior to the investigations,
which began months after U.S. officials first brought up the
Imhausen name with West German authorities.
   Company managing director Hans-Joachim Renner attempted suicide
in mid-February and remains hospitalized in critical condition.
   Hunzinger said Uwe Kunze, director of Cologne's Phospholipid
company, would take over Hippenstiel's job.
</TEXT>
