<FIRST>r a AM-Agents-Discrimination     02-27 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agents-Discrimination,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Female ATF Agents Charge Discrimination In EEOC Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Female agents of the Detroit office of the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms have filed
complaints charging they have been victims of sex discrimination and
harassment.
   The complaints filed with the federal Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission say women are denied promotions and
significant assignments, and are punished with unjustified
suspensions for complaining about it.
   ``The agency is run by reprisal,'' said Memphis, Tenn., civil
rights attorney Prather Randle, who is handling the complaints of
Detroit agents Vernon and Valerie Park, Sandra Davis and former
agent Kathleen Kubicki.
   Kubicki, a supervisor in Detroit until 1987, says she was demoted
and transferred for filing discrimination complaints.
   Mrs. Park said she suffered retaliation since complaining about
Davis being harassed, and her husband said his support of the women
brought him the same treatment.
   ATF officials said they couldn't discuss individual cases, but
said the agency has an affirmative action program for women and
minorities.
   Of 1,540 ATF agents nationally, 125 are female. In Detroit, there
are nine female agents and 69 males.
   Since 1983, 14 sex discrimination cases have been brought
nationwide by ATF employees and applicants, including four in which
an employee filed more than one complaint, the agency said. The
total excludes informal complaints, internal grievances and
ombudsman proceedings.
</TEXT>
