<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Patierno     02-27 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Patierno,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Of B-2 Stealth Bomber Dead At 54</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Patierno, who pioneered research and
development of the Air Force's new B-2 stealth bomber, has died of
cancer, Northrop Corp. officials said Monday. He was 54.
   Patierno died Satuday at Hoag Memorial Hospital in Newport Beach,
said Northrop spokesman Jim Hart.
   ``John was the father of the B-2 and guided the bomber's
development since its inception,'' Thomas V. Jones, chairman and
chief executive of Northrop, said in a statement.
   Jones said Patierno was one of America's most respected leaders
in advanced aeronautical design and development.
   The Newport Beach man spent 17 years developing the highly
classified aircraft designs and technology meant to enable stealth
aircraft to fly through enemy radar without being detected.
   For his work on stealth technologies, Patierno was honored by the
American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics this year with
the Reed Aeronautics Award, the institute's highest honor.
   Patierno, the former corporate vice president and general manager
of Northrop's B-2 division in suburban Pico Rivera, spent 33 years
in aerodynamics.
   Patierno, a native of Clifton, N.J., is survived by his wife,
four children, his mother and a sister.
</TEXT>
