<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Namibia     02-27 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Africans Reject U.N. Buying South African Military Equipment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black African leaders on Monday attacked
suggestions that the U.N. peacekeeping force in Namibia may buy or
lease military equipment from South Africa. Squabbles over
purchasing have delayed funding approval.
   On April 1, U.N. peacekeepers plan to begin implementing a
one-year plan for Namibia's independence from 74 years of South
African rule.
   U.N. officials have said they need make purchases from South
Africa, which lies on Namibia's southern border, to keep down the
cost of the mission that has a proposed budget of $416 million.
   Ambassador Isack Stanislaus Gorerazvo Mudenge of Zimbabwe,
representing the non-aligned movement, said Monday no need exists to
depend on South Africa for military equipment. He said he accepted
that South Africa dominates the economy of the region and said
peacekeepers could buy anything except military equipment from that
white-dominated nation.
   Zambian Ambassador Peter Dingiswayo Zuze, representing the black
African front-line states, joined Mudenge at the news conference.
   The front-line states border on South Africa or are particularly
concerned with events there. They are Zimbabwe, Zambia, Botswana,
Mozambique, Tanzania and Angola.
   Mudenge said dependence on South Africa may be unavoidable in the
early stages, ``but we expect them (the U.N. officials) to plan so
as to minimize that dependence.''
   The General Assembly's finance committee has been deadlocked over
the procurement issue since last week.
   The General Assembly has had to hold up approving the funding for
the Namibia force.
   Front-line states insist on inserting language into the funding
resolution referring to U.N. embargoes on buying military equipment,
oil or other goods from South Africa.
   The United States, Britain and France oppose including such
language.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
