<FIRST>r a AM-Sony-Columbia     02-27 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sony-Columbia,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sony Won't Comment on Rumors It's Buying Columbia Pictures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sony Corp. of America refused to comment
Monday on published reports that the company was set to purchase
Columbia Pictures Entertainment.
   Trade newspapers Daily Variety and The Hollywood Reporter both
reported Monday that a Sony acquisition of the struggling film
studio was imminent.
   ``The deal is done,'' Variety quoted three ``well-placed
sources'' as saying. The Hollywood Reporter said industry
speculation hinted that Sony had ``cinched a deal to buy Columbia.''
   ``We have no comment on that item at this time,'' said Ronald
Petty, Sony's director of corporate communications.
   But, Petty added, ``It's a well-known fact ... we are looking to
get into the entertainment industry.''
   Last year, Sony completed its purchase of CBS Records for about
$2 billion.
   A spokesman for Columbia who asked not to be identified said the
studio wouldn't comment on the reports. Columbia is 49 percent owned
by Coca-Cola Co. of Atlanta.
   Rumors regarding Sony's buying a major film studio have
circulated in Hollywood for months, and the company has been linked
to MGM-UA as well as Columbia.
   The latter studio has labored through a flood of box-office
disappointments, including ``Punchline,'' ``Rocket Gibraltar,''
``The New Adventures of Pippi Longstocking,'' ``Things Change'' and,
most recently, ``Physical Evidence.''
