<FIRST>r w AM-ASNEWritingAwards     02-27 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ASNE Writing Awards,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalism Awards Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Francis X. Clines, London correspondent for the
New York Times, and David J. Remnick, Moscow correspondent for the
Washington Post, will receive journalism awards for outstanding
stories written while under a deadline, the American Society of
Newspaper Editors announced Monday.
   Other award winners are Mark Davis, staff writer for the Tampa,
Fla., Tribune, state and local government reporting; Samuel T.
Francis, deputy editorial page editor, the Washington Times,
editorial writing; James Lileks, staff writer for the St. Paul,
Minn., Pioneer Press Dispatch, non-deadline writing; and Michael
Skube, book page editor for the Raleigh, N.C., News and Observer,
commentary and column writing.
   The awards will be presented April 14 at the closing banquet of
the ASNE convention in Washington.
   Clines and Remnick will share a $2,500 prize given by ASNE
Foundation to recognize exceptional writing in five categories. The
other winners will receive $2,500 each.
   The winning writers and eight runners-up were chosen by a panel
of ASNE editors from 550 entries.
   Runners-up in the competition were Henry Allen, Washington Post,
commentary and column writing; Robert Barnes, Washington Post, state
and local government reporting; Pete Dexter, Sacramento, Calif.,
Bee, commentary and column writing; Thomas French, St. Petersburg,
Fla., Times, non-deadline writing; Ken Fuson, Des Moines, Iowa,
Register, non-deadline writing; Ann Daly Goodwin, St. Paul Pioneer
Press Dispatch, editorial writing; Arnold Markowitz, Miami Herald,
deadline writing, and Lynne Tuohy, Hartford Courant, deadline
writing.
