<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     02-27 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Independent Blue Collar Union Formed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrial workers have formed the first
independent blue-collar union in postwar Hungary, using Poland's
banned Solidarity as a model and intending to campaign for trade
union pluralism.
   About 500 men and women launched Workers' Solidarity during a
meeting Saturday, and the group plans to hold its founding meeting
in May, the official MTI news agency reported Monday.
   The union blamed the ruling Communist party for failing to live
up to one of its fundamental tenets _ the protection of workers'
rights.
   About half a dozen independent trade unions have sprung up in
Hungary over the past year. To date, however, they have been
dominated by white-collar workers rather than factory labor.
   The new union was formed amid a growing economic crisis in
Hungary, where living standards are falling as inflation reaches 20
percent.
   Meanwhile, a veteran Communist party member asked a party's
district committee in Budapest at an a weekend public debate that it
should take a stand in favor of the one-party system, the daily
Magyar Nemzet said Monday.
   Another party conservative, Gyula Sandor, secretary of a local
party chapter comprised of old age pensioners, claimed ``an open,
anti-communist aggression has been going on'' in Hungary.
   ``A section of the intellectual aristocracy, who is well off, is
waging an open struggle against us (communists),'' Magyar Nemzet
quoted Sandor as saying. He reportedly did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
