<FIRST>u a AM-PlaneEmergency 3rdLd-Writethru a0682 02-27 0945</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Emergency, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0682,0968</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Of Damaged United Jet Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd graf, `The preliminary ...,' and 3
grafs after 14th graf pvs, ``United President ...'', to UPDATE with United
fleet inspection; SUBS 11th graf pvs, `Boeing Co ...,' to conform; SUBS
15th graf, `Meanwhile, Doughty ...,' to conform; INSERTS 2 grafs after
17th graf pvs, ```Although we ...,' to UPDATE with union assisting in investigation;
pickup 18th graf pvs, `A three-day ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plane-Cargo Doors Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airlines worldwide were advised to check the
cargo doors of their Boeing 747s as federal investigators focused
Monday on the cargo door latch system of a United jumbo jet that
ripped open at 22,000 feet.
   U.S. Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said he thinks
``it's very important that we not jump to conclusions until that
report (on the investigation) is done.''
   ``The preliminary indications, of course, are that the (cargo)
door opened or at least the skin peeled around the door. But let's
wait until the board reports, then we'll know finally what went
on,'' Skinner said in an interview Monday with ABC's ``Good Morning
America.''
   United Airlines announced that it conducted detailed examinations
of all cargo doors in every plane in its fleet. Seven doors required
repairs, the airline said, but spokesman Rob Doughty said none of
the repairs was urgent.
   ``The items we repaired did not affect operating performance or
airworthiness,'' he said.
   United's Flight 811 was gaining altitude 100 miles south of here
after taking off for Auckland, New Zealand, early Friday when a
10-by-20-foot section of the fuselage ripped away, including the
right front cargo door.
   Nine passengers disappeared when 10 seats in the business class
on the right side were blown out through the gaping hole,
investigators said.
   There was no indication from the ground crew or cockpit crew that
anything was amiss when the cargo door was secured for flight, said
Lee Dickinson, a National Transportation Safety Board investigator.
   Dickinson said investigators have found no evidence of a bomb,
sabotage or metal fatigue that might have caused the mishap, and
``are focusing on and looking at the latching mechanism.''
   ``We're also trying to get a better handle on these latch pin
supports and comparing them to others,'' he said.
   The cargo bay door closed electrically, with eight latching
mechanisms along the bottom, attached to the plane's frame, as well
as a latching mechanism and a hook pin on each side, Dickinson said.
   Investigators determined Sunday that a warning system, that would
have alerted the cockpit crew if the door was not closed properly,
did work, Dickinson said at the NTSB's news briefing Sunday night.
   Boeing Co. on Sunday advised all airlines to check the cargo
doors of their 747s, and National Transportation Safety Board
investigators inspected the doors of other United 747s at Honolulu
International Airport the next day, Doughty said.
   Boeing said it has delivered 712 Boeing 747s of all types around
the world.
   ``What this is from us is by no means interfering or speculating
on the probable cause of the accident,'' Boeing Spokesman David
Jiminez said Monday. ``It's more of a prudent act on our part to
keep customers appraised of what we know.''
   United President Stephen Wolf said an FAA-licensed mechanic would
inspect each 747's cargo doors upon arrival and departure and would
oversee the closing of each cargo door before departure.
   In a statement issued from its Chicago headquarters, United said
it conducted detailed examinations Sunday and Monday of more than
900 cargo doors in its fleet of 399 aircraft, including Boeing 727s,
737s, 747s, and DC-10s made by McDonnell Douglas Corp.
   The seven repairs included repairing a 2-inch crack in the
doorframe of a 737, replacing a doorstop on a 737, replacing two
small brackets on a 747 latch mechanism and adjusting a DC-10 motor,
the statement said.
   ``All of these repairs ... would have been performed in the
normal course of maintenance,'' the statement said. ``Of more than
1,700 daily United flights, only two delays and one cancellation
were necessary.''
   Meanwhile, Doughty hailed the pilot of the crippled jet, Capt.
David M. Cronin, as a hero for controlling the craft.
   Cronin and the other 17 crewmembers of the plane have not been
allowed to talk to the media, Doughty said.
   ``Although we have nothing but praise for Capt. Cronin and the
rest the crew, we don't want anyone to draw conclusions about the
crash based on a brief interview,'' he said.
   Unions representing the flight and ground crews of Flight 811 are
working with investigators in an effort to reassure the public
following last Friday's incident, union leaders said Monday.
   ``Instead of seeing who might be blamed, it's our primary concern
to find out what happened and make sure we can keep it from
happening again,'' said Sam Poomaihealani, assistant general
chairman of District 141, International Association of Machinists.
The union represents all ground employes of United.
   A three-day search by Navy and Coast Guard ships and aircraft
resulted on the recovery of 57 pieces of debris that fell from the
plane, incuding airline seat cushions, an overhead compartment, a
section of fuselage, and personal itmes, including a teddy bear.
   Not recovered was the cargo door.
   ``Obviously, if we had the door it would be very helpful to us,''
Dickinson said, but said he was confident other information will
pinpoint the cause of the accident.
   Of the 354 people aboard the plane, incuding 18 crewmembers, 27
were treated at Honolulu hospitals, mostly for minor injuries caused
by flying debris. One was released from the hospital Monday, leaving
two still hospitalized.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
