<FIRST>r a AM-Fox-`COPS'     02-27 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fox-`COPS',0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fox Moves `COPS' To Saturday Network Schedule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fox Broadcasting Co. is moving its new
real-life police show ``COPS'' to its national network to boost its
anemic Saturday night schedule.
   ``COPS,'' which had been running at various times and days on
Fox-owned stations, will have a one-hour premiere at 9 p.m. on March
11 in place of ``Beyond Tomorrow.''
   It will move into its regular 9 to 9:30 p.m. time slot the
following Saturday. ``Beyond Tomorrow'' will be trimmed from an hour
to a half-hour and follow ``COPS.''
   Since its debut on the seven Fox-owned stations Jan. 7, ``COPS''
has received good ratings and critical praise.
   The reality show follows the personal and professional lives of
sheriff's deputies in Broward County, Fla. It uses no actors and has
no script.
   Fox's Sunday night schedule, led by ``Married ... With
Children,'' ``America's Most Wanted'' and ``21 Jump Street,'' has
scored impressive ratings.
   ``Married ... With Children'' has been beating such network shows
as ABC's ``Hooperman'' and ``thirtysomething'' and NBC's ``Miami
Vice.''
   The Saturday night schedule of ``The Reporters'' and ``Beyond
Tomorrow'' has consistently been at the bottom of the ratings, along
with ``Duet'' from Sunday night.
