<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0700 02-27 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0700,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Men Raid Colombian Ranch, Kill 18 People</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with raid on ranch kills 18. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 50 men disguised as soldiers raided
a ranch in search of a drug trafficker on Monday and killed 18
people, police said.
   The Colombian radio chain RCN speculated that the gunmen were
members of the country's largest leftist guerrilla group, the
Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces.
   A colonel with the national police, Carlos Francisco Hernandez,
said the gunmen arrived at the ranch, about 40 miles northwest of
Bogota, during a party and told guests they were looking for Gonzalo
Rodriguez Gacha.
   Rodriguez Gacha, nicknamed ``The Mexican,'' is said by the U.S.
Drug Enforcement Agency to be a member of the so-called Medellin
Cartel, one of the two biggest drug trafficking groups in Colombia.
   The gunmen searched the ranch and unable to find Rodriguez Gacha,
they began killing bodyguards of a wealthy emerald dealer at the
party, Gilberto Molina, the colonel said in a communique.
   The bodyguards were handcuffed together and shot at point-blank
range with pistols and automatic assault rifles, he said.
   The dead included the ranch owner; the emerald dealer; 15 of his
bodyguards and a retired police colonel, Julio Cesar Martinez
Moncayo, who was the emerald dealer's chief of security, the
communique said.
   Guerrillas had said in communiques in recent months that the
emerald dealer and the drug trafficker had organized death squads to
kill peasants who sympathized with leftist rebels.
   Also Monday, a bomb exploded in the Bogota offices of a U.S.
missionary group, slightly injuring five people, the organization's
local director reported.
   National police said leftist guerrillas freed 11 policemen Monday
who were captured during a raid in early February.
   The bomb exploded at the Summer Institute of Linguistics, which
is based in Duncanville, Tex. Three Americans and two Colombians
suffered minor cuts, local director Abe Coop told The Associated
Press by telephone.
   RCN said an anonymous telephone caller claimed responsibility on
behalf of the leftist People's Revolutionary Army and warned of more
attacks on the institute.
   Summer Linguistics, which has operated in Colombia since 1962,
devises written languages for Indian tribes and translates the Bible
into those languages.
   Coop said the Americans injured Monday were Ken Pagel of El Paso,
Tex.; Jim Cartwright of Hartland, Mich., and Warren Storm of Tampa,
Fla.
   Guerrillas kidnapped and murdered one of the institute's
missionaries, Chester Bitterman, in Bogota in 1981, accusing him of
working for the CIA.
   Kidnappers seized two American missionaries from another
organization Jan. 10 in western Colombia. Those kidnapped were
Richard Grover of Minneapolis and Roy Libby of Atlanta, both of the
Colombian Evangelical Confederation.
   Hector Pardo, president of the group, said Monday no
communications had been received from the kidnappers. Pardo said he
assumed guerrillas were responsible because they oppose the presence
of missionaries in Colombia.
   The 11 policemen were captured Feb. 8 during an attack on
Valencia in Huila state, southern Colombia. At the time, police said
five officers were killed.
   A national police statement said the Colombian Revolutionary
Armed Forces, turned the 11 policemen over to Monsignor Jose Luis
Serna, a Roman Catholic bishop.
   It said they were freed near Pitalito, about 240 miles south of
Bogota, apparently in good health.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
