<FIRST>u i AM-AntarcticShip 1stLd-Writethru a0642 02-27 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antarctic Ship, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvian Research Ship Runs Aground In Antarctica, Spill Alert Issued</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with small diesel slick sited.
Pickup 4th graf `A cutter...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chilean navy cutter and British repair
ship were on alert Monday against the threat of an oil spill from a
Peruvian research vessel that ran aground in Antarctica, officials
said.
   The British ice patrol ship Endurance earlier Monday rescued 64
scientists and sailors from the crippled vessel, the 1,980-ton
Humboldt, and took them to Chile's Marsh Base antarctic station,
according to the Chilean navy.
   In a communique, the navy said the Endurance tried unsucessfully
to lighten the Humboldt, which ran aground and began taking on water
after hitting rocks Sunday night off King George Island.
   In a second communique later Monday, the navy said some diesel
oil had spilled, creating a slick 150 yards by five yards. It said
that apparently two of the ship's four fuel tanks had split.
   A cutter from the Chilean navy, the Yelcho, was sent quickly
Monday from Punta Arenas, on the southern tip of the South American
continent, to ``lend all the necessary support both in efforts to
rescue the Humboldt and to control the pollution from the oil spill
that may occur,'' the navy said.
   The Humboldt is listing slightly to the right but is not in
danger of sinking, it said.
   A spokesman for the British navy said in London the repair ship
Stena Seaspread will stand by the stricken ship to monitor pollution
and help with any salvage work.
   The site is 300 miles from the area where the Argentine ship
Bahia Paraiso ran aground and sank Jan. 28, spilling fuel oil into
the region's usually pristine waters. The spill was cleaned up by
ships from the United States, Chile and Argentina. Damage to the
Antarctic environment is still being evaluated.
</TEXT>
