<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0676 02-27 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Opposition Seeks Outside Support for Fair Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERT 2 grafs after 16th graf pvs, His decree ... UPDATING
with foreign minister saying order to free prisoners could come Tuesday.
Pick ups 17th graf pvs, The Defense ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A delegation from the opposition left
on Monday for talks with the presidents of Costa Rica and Venezuela,
seeking their support to make sure Nicaragua meets its obligations
under a Central American peace pact.
   Opposition leader Gilberto Cuadra said the presidents' backing
``is necessary, apart from our own efforts'' to ensure fair
elections in Nicaragua.
   The government party, the leftist Sandinista National Liberation
Front, already has begun what amounts to a veiled election campaign,
with President Daniel Ortega as the obvious candidate.
   Also Monday, Ortega sent the National Assembly a proposed decree
that would pardon 1,932 former members of ousted dictator Anastaso
Somoza's hated and feared national guard. The assembly will consider
the decree Tuesday.
   Cuadra heads the Superior Council of Private Enterprise, the most
important association of private business executives in Nicaragua,
and is a member of the delegation that left Monday.
   He said the delegates will meet with President Oscar Arias on
Tuesday in San Jose, the Costa Rican capital, and with President
Carlos Andres Perez in Caracas, Venezuela, on Thursday.
   Cuadra said they will discuss the accord which Ortega, Arias and
the presidents of El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras reached at a
summit in El Salvador on Feb. 14.
   Ortega agreed then to institute reforms to guarantee free
elections, which he called to be held Feb. 25, 1990, 10 months ahead
of schedule. Nearly every elective post will be on the ballot, from
president and National Assembly deputies through town mayors.
   The five Central American presidents also agreed to draft by May
14 a plan to dismantle the U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebel force. An
estimated 11,000 rebels, known as Contras, are living in camps with
their families in Honduras near the Nicaraguan border.
   While the opposition continues trying to form a united front _ by
all indications its only chance at winning the presidential race _
the Sandinistas are making it increasingly clear their nominee will
be Ortega.
   The first placards calling for Ortega to run for re-election
appeared at a rally Saturday in Masaya, 17 miles south of Managua.
   ``We will win the 1990 elections just like we won the 1984
elections,'' Ortega told the rally.
   Interior Minister Tomas Borge meanwhile was telling foreign
correspondents in Managua that the Sandinista Front had not yet
chosen a presidential candidate.
   Ortega said in a televised interview on Feb. 15 that running for
re-election ``is no sin,'' the closest he has come to saying he will
run for another term.
   Ortega had promised to release the former guardsmen at the Feb.
14 Central American summit.
   His decree names 1,932 ex-guardsmen convicted of ``crimes against
the people'' during the Somoza dictatorship that was overthrown by
the Sandinista revolution in 1979. The list includes 1,688
imprisoned ex-guardsmen and 244 who are either under house arrest or
free on conditional liberty.
   Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto said ``many former Somocista
guards will go free very soon, maybe tomorrow (Tuesday). The
Legislative Assembly of Nicaragua will decree very shortly the
liberty of those former national guardsmen.''
   He spoke to reporters Monday in San Pedro Sula, Honduras, where
he was attending a conference of foreign ministers from Latin
American and West European governments.
   The Defense Ministry said Monday that Honduran troops fired on
three Nicaraguan border outposts near Teotecancinte, about 112 miles
from Managua, on Thursday, Saturday and Sunday. The ministry said
nothing about casualties.
   Honduran officials were not immediately available for comment on
the charges. Such allegations are frequent and usually denied by
Honduras.
</TEXT>
