<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-27 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Snow In North Carolina Mountains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a foot of snow fell in North Carolina on Monday as wet
weather prevailed from the lower Mississippi Valley to Virginia and
the Carolinas.
   Dry weather prevailed across the rest of the nation, with clear
skies over the Florida Peninsula, much of new england and much of
the Southwest.
   The snowstorm stretching from eastern Kentucky and eastern
Tennessee to the middle Atlantic Coast left 14 inches of new snow on
Mount Mitchell in North Carolina, leaving a total of 21 inches on
the ground.
   A winter storm warning remained in effect for the mountains of
western North Carolina, and snow advisories were posted for
southeastern Kentucky, southern West Virginia, southwestern
Tennessee, most of Virginia, southern Maryland and southern Delaware.
   Light snow fell in the northern Rockies, northern Plains and the
upper Mississippi Valley. Redwood Falls, Minn., received 3 inches of
snow by Monday evening.
   In six hours ending at 7 p.m. EST, 2 inches of snow fell at
Fargo, N.D., and an inch fell at Binghamton, N.Y.; Great Falls and
Missoula, Mont., and Nashville, Tenn.
   A snow advisory was in effect for central and southeastern
Minnesota, and a a blowing snow advisory was issued for western
sections of the state. Advisories for snow and blowing snow was
posted for eastern North Dakota and northwestern Montana. The rest
of western Montana and much of central Montana were under a snow
advisory.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees at Detroit Lakes and Roseau, Minn., to 89 degrees at
Thermal, Calif.
   The forecast for Tuesday called for snow in the northern Rockies
and the northern High Plains and across much of the Great Lakes and
Ohio Valley; rain prevailing from the lower Mississippi Valley to
the Carolinas and the Middle Atlantic States and over the Pacific
Northwest; and fair to partly sunny skies prevailing in the rest of
the nation.
   Temperatures were expected to remain below freezing from the
northern Rockies to Nebraska and the Dakotas and in northern New
England, with highs in the teens from Montana to Minnesota and
northwest Michigan; above 50 degrees from California to much of
Texas and the southern Atlantic Coast; and in the 70s and lower 80s
from Southern California to the lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas,
Florida and southern Georgia.
