<SECOND>AM-Wildfires, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0650,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed As More than 200 Fires Burn in Florida</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Fort Lauderdale</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with two firefighters killed, Everglades fire
burning 2,700 acres, quotes, details; ADDS byline; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   MIAMI (AP _ Two firefighters were killed Monday in the battle
against a wildfire in central Florida, while other blazes scorched
miles of Everglades sawgrass and threatened a major power line that
serves the Miami area.
   The two volunteer firefighters from Bushnell, about 45 miles west
of Orlando, had just arrived at the scene of a mile-long grass fire
in the median strip of Interstate 75 when a tractor-trailer slammed
into their smoke-obscured pickup, crushing both men, the Florida
Highway Patrol said.
   Paul J. Reid, 20, was dead on the scene, while Ervin W. Fort, 33,
was airlifted to Bayfront Medical Center in St. Petersburg, where he
was pronounced dead, the patrol said.
   The truck driver, Denver Lewis, 31, of Clarkton, Mo., was not
seriously injured, Sumter County Sheriff's Capt. James Fussell said.
The accident two miles south of Bushnell tied up southbound traffic
for about three hours.
   The firefighters were the first to die so far this wildfire
season. The last time a death occurred fighting a wildfire was more
than four years ago, state forestry officials said.
   A fire emergency was declared at midday by officials in both
Broward and Palm Beach counties, just north of Miami, placing all
available firefighters on alert.
   The largest of the wildfires engulfed 2,700 acres of the
Everglades in Broward County, and was a major concern because it was
approaching a major transmission line owned by Florida Power &amp;
Light, forestry officials said.
   Five to 10 miles of lines were threatened by Everglades fires
near U.S. 27 at the Palm Beach-Broward County line, said David
Utley, a state forestry duty officer.
   Stacey Shaw, a spokeswoman for FP&amp;L, said three 500-kilovolt
lines were taken out of service Monday morning when fires burned
into the corridor where they are located.
   The utility reactivated the lines after the blaze moved away from
them early Monday evening, state forester Peter Burke said.
   Firefighters were depending on weather conditions to help contain
the Everglades blaze after withdrawing from the area Monday evening,
Burke said.
   ``It will probably be burning overnight but we expect it will be
under control as the humidity rises, the winds die down, and the
temperatures get cooler,'' Burke said. ``I expect we'll be mopping
up hopefully tommorrow.''
   Charles Maynard, assistant chief of fire control at main division
offices in Tallahassee, said the Everglades fire was one of about
200 wildfires reported since Friday. Some were in Palm Beach County,
where ``we had a problem with arson,'' he said.
   The annual bout with brushfires started much earlier this year in
south Florida because rainfall has been about half the normal amount
since November.
   The Miami area has received 7{ inches of rain since September,
compared with an average rainfall of 24 inches for that period,
according to the National Weather Service.
   A fire which swept through 397 acres of grass and timberlands
forced the evacuation of some 200 people and closed a highway Sunday
in Putnam County in northeast Florida.
   Putnam County Sheriff's Sgt. Pat Westberry said residents were
allowed to return home early Monday. No homes or businesses were
damaged, he said.
   Arson was believed responsible for that fire, said Assistant
Palatka Fire Chief Owen Preston.
</TEXT>
