<FIRST>r a AM-HazardousWaste     02-27 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hazardous Waste,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Carolina May Close Major Hazardous Waste Landfill To Other
States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half the nation may be
temporarily prohibited from using South Carolina's hazardous waste
landfill beginning Wednesday, state health officials said Monday.
   Gov. Carroll Campbell said last month that he would shut the
state's borders March 1 to states seeking to dispose of hazardous
waste in South Carolina that they won't dispose of themselves.
   As of Monday, 27 states had not responded to the state Department
of Health and Environmental Control's request for information needed
to enact Campbell's order, officials said.
   The order affects the massive GSX hazardous waste landfill in
Sumter County east of Columbia, which now holds close to a billion
pounds of hazardous waste, about 70 percent of it from out of state.
The site is one of only two commercial hazardous waste landfills in
the Southeast and accepts roughly 135,000 tons of chemical garbage
annually. The other site is in Alabama.
   State health officials sent letters to all 50 states and Puerto
Rico informing them of Campbell's order and asking for information
on their waste handling laws by Feb. 15
   But by Monday afternoon, only 23 states had responded.
   Thirty-three states, Puerto Rico and the District of Columbia
used the facility in 1987, and South Carolina officials said some
states may not be responding because they will not be affected by
the order.
   But until they know about the states' policies, all states that
don't respond will be banned, said Hartsill Truesdale, head of the
health agency's hazardous waste division.
   Of the states that have responded, eight or nine have been
tentatively put on the list to be banned, which will be presented to
Campbell for approval.
   The list could change before Wednesday's deadline, or even
afterwards, as new information is received, Truesdale said.
   Campbell's staff initially said they expected the ban would fall
on nine states: North Carolina, Florida, Massachusetts, Rhode
Island, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Kentucky, Louisiana and Kansas.
They estimated those states accounted for about 40 percent of the
waste going to GSX.
   Truesdale would not comment Monday on individual states, and said
the states now listed are not necessarily those suggested earlier by
the governor's office.
   Campbell, speaking from the National Governors Association
conference in Washington, said governors from North Carolina,
Florida and other states had approached him about his order.
   He said that states would have to certify they had no impediments
to disposal within their own borders or that the repeal of such
impediments was imminent in order to be allowed to continue burying
waste in South Carolina.
   ``Our policy has to be flexible enough to work with a state that
is genuinely moving to eliminate prohibitions,'' Campbell said.
   But, he said, ``I look for us to reach a point where there will
be some states that will be cut off.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
