<FIRST>r a AM-Herbicide-Timber     02-27 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Herbicide-Timber,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Service To Use Herbicides On Calif. Timberland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time since 1984, herbicides
might be used again this year or next in national forests in
California to protect growth of commercial timber, a Forest Service
official said Monday.
   At the same time, Ray Weinmann, regional timber management
director, said he expected a legal challenge by ``zealots'' over
concern for possible threats to water supplies, humans and wildlife.
   Such challenges, currently under appeal, have stalled forest
herbicide use in Washington and Oregon.
   Production in the California region could drop an average of
about 20 percent without herbicide use, Weinmann said. He said the
California region represents annual production of about 1.7-1.8
billion board feet. A board foot is a unit of measure equal to a
board 1 foot square and 1 inch thick.
   ``We will limit the (health) risk to acceptable levels ... We
believe the risks are well within acceptable limits,'' he said.
``The decision is based on an environmental analysis of all the
factors relating to herbicide use.''
   The 50,000 acres slated for annual herbicide applications are
cut-timber country and forests burned in wildfires, he said,
promising that herbicides ``will only be used where other treatment
methods cannot do the job effectively.''
   Weinmann, demonstrating the level of favored herbicides, produced
a spray container of ``Weed-B-Gon,'' a consumer product. But printed
material handed reporters made clear that the service wasn't ruling
out the use of atrazine and 2,4-D, both under suspicion as possible
cancer-causing agents.
   Use of these agents, said the reports, would be ``last-choice''
and limited ``to sites where no other alternative will meet
management objectives.''
   Failure to take the described tough measures against competing
vegetation can cost as much as 300 million to 400 million board feet
of lumber annually, he estimated.
   The idea is to control certain clovers, brush and weeds that rob
trees of nutrition in a national forest-based industry that last
year produced enough lumber to erect ``a city the size of San
Francisco,'' said Weinmann.
   Before the moratorium in 1984, herbicides had been used in the
California national forests since the mid-1960s. The Forest Service
manages 20 million acres of California forest land, about a third in
commercial wood product production. Lumber companies pay to harvest
wood from national forests.
   ``We know there is going to be a challenge,'' he said. ``There
are some people who very sincerely and honestly believe that
herbicides are a poison that should not be used, and they are going
to take whatever aggressive actions they believe they should. We
have to deal with them when they come up.''
   He called such people ``zealots.''
</TEXT>
