<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolAds     02-27 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Ads,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principals' Group Against Classroom TV With Ads</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0742 to DELETE unneeded editor's note.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the nation's largest group of
school administrators voted Monday to urge principals around the
country to avoid programs which force commercials into the classroom.
   ``We know selling junk food in the cafeteria is bad nutrition,
and we know it's bad education to bring commercials into the
classroom,'' Scott Thomson, executive director of the National
Association of Secondary School Principals, said after the 18-0 vote
by the group's board of directors.
   The board voted to urge schools not to participate in ventures
disguising commercials as learning programs and to oppose ads which
students must watch or which replace instruction time.
   Although the program wasn't mentioned, spokesman Lew Armistead
said the vote was a reaction to plans for ``Channel One,'' a daily
12-minute news show including up to two minutes of ads.
   ``We think it's a premature response. The program has not even
been aired,'' said Christopher Whittle, chairman and founder of
Whittle Communications LP of Knoxville, Tenn., which plans to test
the show at six schools in early March.
   ``We're conducing an entire battery of research to find out what
educational value it has, to find out the effects of commercials, if
any, on teen-agers,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Whittle Communications gives schools about $50,000 of electronics
equipment in exchange for an agreement that the satellite-carried
program will be shown to students every day.
   Whittle said Walter Cronkite told the association in 1980 that a
daily news program should be beamed to high schools.
   ``He said the only question is funding. His attempt to do that,
getting major corporations to put up the money, failed,'' said
Whittle.
   ``Furthermore, let's find out what's the alternative plan,'' he
said. ``Meaning, how do the critics expect education to be funded if
new ideas aren't allowed to even be tested.
   ``If you're going to get real funding from business, business is
going have to get real results,'' Whittle said. ``When you talk
about small dollars, yes, maybe business is going to provide it.
When you talk about real dollars, it's going have to be quid-pro-quo
partnerships.''
   Thomson, a former social studies teacher, said his major
objection at first was the idea of bringing advertisements into the
classroom. But after seeing a preview segment, he said, he was even
more set against ``Channel One.''
   ``After I reviewed the program, I became more concerned about the
superficiality of the curriculum,'' Thomson said.
   ``It results in pop social studies. That's not the right way to
get students to understand concepts and have basic information,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
