<DOCNO> AP890227-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2205EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     02-27 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Albert Innaurato's `Gus and Al' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ed: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Are you ready for a comedy about big-gun
classical composer Gustav ``Gus'' Mahler and his friendship with a
modern-day playwright who is not unlike author Albert ``Al''
Innaurato?
   You'll get both of them in ``Gus and Al,'' Innaurato's strange
comic fantasy that opened Monday at off-Broadway's Playwrights
Horizons.
   Innaurato's weird tale of time-travel begins in New York 1989 and
then jumps backwards to Vienna 1901. Al, who is fat, 40 and gay, has
fled his problems in the present to help his hero Mahler confront
difficulties in the past.
   And Mahler does have his troubles _ an overbearing sister as well
as a mad housekeeper Natalie who is in love with him. She is jealous
of his romancing the bossy Alma Schindler who later becomes his wife.
   Much of the bickering between the composer and his female
entourage in Act 1 is tedious. Mahler or music buffs might find some
fun in Innaurato's inside jokes about the composer. Others may find
it pretentious, especially when the playwright suggests there is a
similarity between the two artists, both, according to Innaurato,
unappreciated in their own time.
   The second act perks up considerably when Al meets Camillo, his
Italian grandfather as a young man before he emigrates to America.
The link between past and future is forged sweetly and with a great
deal of humor. It's a fascinating conceit and one that is more
interesting than the rest of the play.
   Mark Blum, padded with stuffing, turns the hefty and neurotic
playwright into an appealing character. Sam Tsoutsouvas as the
driven composer is a model of the frustrated, unfulfilled artist,
but his trio of female tormentors, Cara Duff-MacCormick, Christina
Moore and Jennifer Van Dyck, are all variations of the same
unattractive shrew. Bradley White turns Al's ancestor into an
attractive, common-sense individual in contrast to all the loonies
swirling around him.
   Still, Innaurato has a fine sense of the bizarre, particularly
when he is dealing with his frustrated playwright. ``Gus and Al''
would have been twice as good if only it had concentrated on half
its title characters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890227-0199 </DOCNO>
