<FIRST>u i AM-PriceRiots 2ndLd-Writethru a0734 02-27 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Price Riots, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0734,0914</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Violence Hits Venezuela Over Transport Price Increases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to CORRECT to damage in millions, sted hundreds
of millions, UPDATE with one dead, 200 injured, 100,000 Caracas commuters
stranded. Pickup 11th graf `Interior Minister...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CAR5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry mobs across Venezuela set fire to
cars and buses, battled police and national guardsmen and looted
hundreds of stores on Monday to protest increases in gasoline prices
and transportation fares.
   The wave of riots injured at least 200 people alone in Caracas
and the Guarenas shantytown 30 miles east of the capital, a police
report said. Rioting broke out in at least seven cities and towns
and independent reports estimated damage nationwide to be in the
millions of dollars.
   Sackings continued in downtown Caracas at nightfall and public
transportation ground to a halt, leaving about 100,000 commuters
stranded, officials said. Many employees remained in their offices,
while a pitched battle went on between police and looters.
   ``It is a popular uprising. There are riots everywhere. They are
all furious,'' Metropolitan Police Inspector Jose Lara Montilla, who
commanded a police unit armed with shotguns in downtown Caracas,
told an Associated Press reporter.
   All 6,000 policemen in Caracas were mobilized, said Alex
Martinez, deputy police commissioner.
   Riots were reported across the country and authorities broadcast
appeals for calm. No official figures were available on deaths or
injuries.
   A 32-year-old pregnant woman was fatally shot in Guarenas,
according to a reporter for the newspaper La Voz de Guarenas,
quoting police sources who gave no further details.
   Television showed rioting in Maracaibo, San Cristobal, Valencia
and Puerto La Cruz, among other cities.
   Police helicopters were seen flying over the capital trying to
disperse rock-hurling mobs. In the downtown area of El Silencio,
site of the AP offices, almost all the stores were sacked. In the
twin Simon Bolivar towers, home of several ministries, not one shop
window was left intact.
   ``Every single business around here has been sacked and
destroyed,'' said Victor Hugo Carvajal, an AP reporter who has lived
in Venezuela since 1973. ``It is the worst I have ever seen.''
   The outburst turned Caracas into one solid traffic jam.
   By all accounts, the violence occurring during the new
administration of Social Democratic President Carlos Andres Perez
was the worst this usually peaceful, oil-producing nation has
suffered in decades.
   Interior Minister Alejandro Izaguirre warned in a national TV
address that the government would not tolerate further public
disorder. ``Burning buses and cars, lootings and sackings of shops
are not the expression of a democratic society. We will not tolerate
this,'' he said.
   He said the increases were ``not capricious, but mandated by
necessity. ... The government was compelled to dictate economic
measures given the seriousness of an unprecedented economic crisis.''
   The Caracas bus terminal of Nuevo Circo (New Circus) became a
battlefield between police and mobs. Officers fired tear gas.
Rioters set cars and buses ablaze. Hundreds of passangers who were
waiting for transportation to neighboring areas fled in panic.
   At nightfall the police had cordoned off the terminal area, where
about 500 buses and taxis daily transport at least 100,000
commuters. Most of the commuters are workers who live in Maracay and
Valencia.
   The fury spilled over Monday morning as new transport fares went
into effect, in many cases doubling previous bus rates, as a result
of gasoline price increases of more than 100 percent.
   The round-trip fare between Guarenas and Caracas went up from 16
to 32 bolivars (roughly from 41 cents to 82 cents). In monthly
terms, it represents roughly a quarter of the minimum salary
included in the economic package announced two weeks ago by the
government of Perez, inaugurated on Feb. 2.
   The government hopes to end subsidies on such necessities as
transportation, food and housing.
   ``We cannot stand this. We are already half-starving. The new
rates condemn us to eat nothing,'' said Carlos Rodriguez, 45, who
works in a shop in downtown Caracas.
   Venezuela's economy, prosperous during the 1970s, is now trapped
in a deep recession because of persistently weak oil prices and a
$33-billion foreign debt.
   The country is also set to sign this week a letter of intent with
the International Monetary Fund for a $1.5 billion credit.
   Around 120 people were injured, including 14 policemen, when
looters formed human chains to face national guard units firing
birdshot from armored cars, said reporter Igor Camacho.
   Three guardsmen were hurt by rocks thrown by students in Merida,
more than 300 miles southwest of Caracas. Stores were trashed and
vehicles set ablaze.
   ``It's an outright battle between students and the national
guard,'' said Ramon Suarez, a reporter for the newspaper Frontera in
Merida, home to the 10,000 students of the University of the Andes.
Tanks patrolled the streets.
   Students took the state governor, Orlando Guttierez, prisoner for
about an hour Monday when he approached rioters in an attempt to
talk with them.
   The national guard, part of the Defense Ministry, is used for
internal security.
   In Maracay, 60 miles east of Caracas, rioting students told
reporters to stay away or their cars would be burned, said Orolis
Rodriguez of the newspaper El Siglo. She said students blocked land
transport between Caracas and Maracay, threatening to burn buses and
cars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
