<FIRST>r a AM-Demjanjuk     02-27 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Demjanjuk,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demjanjuk Says On Anniversary Of Imprisonment That He's Still Hopeful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Demjanjuk, the retired auto worker
convicted of being the sadistic Nazi death camp guard ``Ivan the
Terrible,'' said Monday that he hasn't given up hope three years
after being deported to Israel.
   ``I feel OK ... I'm waiting,'' Demjanjuk said in a telephone
interview with WJW-TV of Cleveland. ``It's hard for me waiting
because it's a long time. But you know I feel that everything will
be OK because I'm the wrong man.''
   Demjanjuk became the first American sent to Israel to stand trial
for Nazi war crimes three years ago on Monday. Last April, he was
sentenced to death after being convicted of being ``Ivan the
Terrible,'' who operated the gas chambers at the Treblinka death
camp in Poland.
   Demjanjuk is appealing the conviction.
   Demjanjuk, a Ukrainian immigrant who settled in the Cleveland
suburb of Seven Hills after World War II, said it has been difficult
for him to be separated from his family. He has spent the past three
years in a Jerusalem prison and six weeks ago his second grandchild
was born.
   ``This is hard, and I already have (a) grandson and granddaughter
(who) I don't see,'' he said. ``I miss family; I miss my other
friends; I miss all the people from Cleveland.
   ``The world should be learning what is true ... the world knows
... I know the world knows already. Everybody prays for me, and I
pray for myself, and I think God helps me show the truth.''
   Demjanjuk's appeal has been delayed until next fall because one
of his Israeli attorneys committed suicide and another, Yoram
Sheftel, is recovering from an eye injury he received when an
Israeli Holocaust survivor threw acid at him.
   ``I worry about him (Sheftel) you know that it won't happen a
second time,'' Demjanjuk said.
   Family members are still attempting to raise money for
Demjanjuk's defense and to find evidence that will help in his
appeal.
   ``We're working as hard as ever every single day to get at the
information that we know exists to prove his innocence,'' said
Demjanjuk's son, John Jr.
</TEXT>
