<FIRST>u i AM-Pacific-Earthquake     02-27 0126</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pacific-Earthquake,0131</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Recorded In South Pacific</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake was recorded Tuesday in an
isolated area of the south Pacific off the Molucca Islands, the Hong
Kong Observatory reported.
   The quake measuring 6.1 on the Richter scale struck at 7:44 a.m.
(6:44 p.m. Monday), observatory said, and was centered in the sea
just north of the Moluccas, an Indonesian island chain.
   The observatory had no additional details.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of energy released by an earthquake
and each increase of one number means ground motion is 10 times
greater.
   A quake of magnitude 6 can cause severe damage in a populated
area, while one of magnitude 7 is capable of causing widespread and
heavy damage.
</TEXT>
