<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     02-27 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Notes Round-Table Talk Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa told a rally Monday that
round-table talks with the government are at the halfway mark and
``new obstacles keep appearing every day.'' But he remained upbeat
and he begged young Poles to show restraint.
   Walesa spoke to 7,000 people in southwest Poland in the latest of
a series of appearances to build support for his still-outlawed
Solidarity free trade union movement.
   Walesa expressed hope the government would make ``new,
further-reaching political decisions'' necessary to allay the
difficulties.
   In the meantime, he asked young people to use restraint when
demonstrating, saying, ``I am begging you on my knees.''
   The 1983 Nobel Peace laureate appeared to be referring to student
unrest over the weekend. Young people demanding legalization of the
banned Independent Students Association, or NZS, clashed with police
in Krakow. Authorities said 39 police were injured.
   On Monday, 2,000 student supporters of NZS rallied in front of
Krakow's Jagiellonian University and declared a 48-hour boycott of
classes, said an opposition spokesman in the city, Zygmunt Lenyk.
   Negotiators in Warsaw meanwhile reported progress Monday on the
question of legalizing the NZS, which is the campus equivalent of
Solidarity, and which like Solidarity was banned after Poland's 1981
martial-law crackdown.
   Both sides agreed to consider a declaration of intention to
legalize the NZS and several other groups banned because of their
support for Solidarity, said NZS representative Piotr Czerwiec.
   But government spokesman Jerzy Urban, appearing on state
television, said legalization ``must depend'' on whether NZS leaders
disassociate themselves from violent or anti-Soviet protests.
   Authorities have agreed in principle to restore legal status to
Solidarity and to a parallel union for farmers, Rural Solidarity.
   The unprecedented round-table talks among representatives of
authorities, the opposition and the official trade union alliance
OPZZ began Feb. 6 and were expected to last about three more weeks.
   The talks aim for a new ``social contract,'' in which the
opposition would promise social peace and participation in official
institutions such as Parliament in exchange for legalization of
Solidarity and adoption of other political and economic reforms.
   ``The round-table is midway, but new obstacles keep appearing
every day,'' Walesa told a legal rally in Wroclaw. ``It demands new,
further-reaching political decisions. I believe that they will take
place.''
   Opposition negotiators in Warsaw expressed annoyance that
Parliament took action Friday on subjects that were still under
negotiation at the round table.
</TEXT>
