<FIRST>r a AM-ReservationSlayings     02-27 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reservation Slayings,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced to Five Life Terms In Reservation Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARQUETTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was sentenced to five life prison
terms Monday for murdering his brother-in-law, his sister-in-law and
two of their children on an Indian reservation on Michigan's Upper
Peninsula.
   ``Society must be protected,'' U.S. District Judge Robert Holmes
Bell told Vincent Loonsfoot. ``I order you confined to a federal
facility for the rest of your natural life.''
   Loonsfoot, who was silent and showed no emotion, was convicted
Dec. 9 of four counts of first-degree murder, kidnapping, possession
of a firearm during a crime of violence and of felony possession of
a firearm.
   Loonsfoot, 26, shot David Smith, 29, Sherry Smith, 27, and their
daughters, Amy, 10, and Laura, 2, on the Hannahville Indian
Reservation last June 14.
   The sole survivor was the couple's daughter Amanda, 11. After the
shootings, Loonsfoot abducted his estranged wife, Peggy, and took
her with him for 10 days in remote Delta County before turning
himself in.
   Bell sentenced Loonsfoot to four life prison terms for each
murder, and a fifth life term for possession of a firearm during a
violent felony. He also sentenced Loonsfoot to 12 years in prison
for kidnapping, and another five years for felony possession of a
firearm.
   All but the five-year term are to run concurrently. The five-year
term is to run consecutively.
   Defense attorney Dennis Girard said he would appeal to the 6th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati.
</TEXT>
