<FIRST>r a AM-AlcoholMarch     02-27 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alcohol March,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gallop Residents Seek Anti-Alcohol State Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of a northwestern New Mexico city
pleaded for anti-alcohol legislation Monday at the end of a 200-mile
march to the state Capitol that was spurred by a fatal accident
caused by a drunken driver.
   More than 1,000 people joined the couple dozen marchers and heard
pledges of support from Gov. Garrey Carruthers, Gallup Mayor Edward
Munoz, Navajo Nation Vice Chairman Johnny Thompson and others.
   Later, the state Senate heard a series of emotion-filled speeches
and testimonials describing the alcoholism problem in Gallup, a city
of about 18,000 peole in northwestern New Mexixo near the Arizona
border.
   ``We could walk from here to China and it wouldn't do a bit of
good unless we had the support of the people to enact the laws,''
Munoz told the Senate.
   The march, which began Feb. 17, was dubbed the Journey for Jovita
after an infant who was killed in an alcohol-related traffic
accident in January.
   The National Institute of Alcoholism and Alcohol Abuse has
reported that surrounding McKinley County's rate of alcohol-related
deaths per 100,000 people was nearly six times the U.S. average from
1975 to 1979.
   The marchers asked lawmakers to support anti-alcoholism
legislation, including a liquor tax to fund alcohol-rehabilitation
programs, funding for a detoxification program and a ban on drive-up
windows at liquor stores.
   Although only a couple of dozen walked most of the 200-mile trip
from Gallup to Santa Fe, groups from Indian schools and pueblos and
other McKinley County residents joined the group for the final few
miles to the Capitol.
</TEXT>
