<FIRST>r a AM-DallasMurder     02-27 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dallas Murder,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas Teen Arrested in New York for Killing Mom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Texas teen-ager was arrested Monday at a
Manhattan shelter for runaway children and charged with the shotgun
murder of his mother, whose body was found stuffed in a garbage can
earlier this month.
   Mario Reid, 18, of Dallas, is also wanted for questioning in the
disappearance of his stepfather, said Dallas police Detective Robert
Alexander. Police believe the stepfather is dead, although his body
has not been found and the teen has not been charged in that case.
   Reid was jailed pending his transfer to Texas, said Detective
John Clifford, a New York police spokesman. Authorities were unsure
whether the teen planned to waive extradition proceedings or when he
would be returned to Dallas.
   The teen had spent the weekend at Covenant House, telling workers
there his mother had died several months earlier of a heart attack
and he didn't know where his father was, said John Kells of the
shelter.
   ``He looked like the average runaway kid,'' said Kells. ``He did
what the other kids do here on weekends _ read books, eat, sleep.''
   Reid was arrested Monday after officials at the shelter near
Times Square discovered he was wanted for murder and called city
police, said Clifford. Dallas police contacted Covenant House after
staffers there called Texas to get background on Reid, said Kells.
   The teen-ager arrived at the shelter Friday, Clifford said.
   Dallas police believe Reid shotgunned his mother, 37-year-old
Marie King Dials, and stuffed her into a garbage can at an
elementary school two blocks from their home, said Alexander. Her
body was found Feb. 7, but she was not identified until eight days
later.
   Police then searched the family's home and found evidence that
the teen's stepfather, Robert Dials, 44, had also been killed, said
Alexander. The search for his body continues, ``but we believe he is
deceased,'' the detective said.
   A warrant was subsequently issued for Reid's arrest.
   Family members told Dallas police that Reid was ``fascinated with
death, Satan worshipping and that type of thing,'' said Alexander.
Police have not determined a motive in the slaying, he said.
</TEXT>
