<FIRST>r a AM-Cocaine-Jewelry     02-27 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine-Jewelry,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Brothers Were Honest Businessmen, Not Money Launderers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers accused of masterminding a $1
billion operation to launder cocaine profits were honest gold
bullion dealers, an attorney said Monday after winning postponement
of their bail hearing.
   The lawyer for Nazareth Andonian told a magistrate that evidence
indicating the two men's innocence should be considered before bail
is decided.
   U.S. Magistrate John Kronenberg scheduled the bail hearing for
next Monday.
   The government has asked that Andonian and his brother, Vahe, be
held without bail on grounds that they were key figures in an
international cocaine money laundering scheme centered in the Los
Angeles wholesale jewelry mart.
   More than 40 persons have been arrested so far in the government
investigation code-named Polar Cap, which was revealed last week.
   Defendants were charged with aiding the distribution of thousands
of pounds of cocaine by laundering up to $1 billion in cash. The
money, packed like bricks and shipped by armored car, was generated
from cocaine sales in Los Angeles, New York, Houston and other
cities, authorities said.
   The complaint alleged the funds were counted, deposited in banks
and wire transferred to South America for purchase of more cocaine.
   But attorney Allan Sigel, representing Nazareth Andonian, said
outside court that the government may have been misled by informants
in the drug trade.
   ``They have a snitch, an informant, who finds himself in great
difficulty and in exchange for freedom will say anything,'' said
Sigel.
   An affidavit filed in federal court shows that the probe of
wholesale jewelers began with a tip from an informant in Uruguay who
told an agent about the alleged money laundering operation.
   ``The complaint is inference and innuendo because of the
government view that they (the Andonians) have large amounts of
unexplained cash,'' said Sigel.
   But he added that, ``One who deals in gold bullion deals in huge
amounts of cash. It's quite common to deal in millions of dollars in
the gold business.''
   Thus, he said that government surveillance videotapes which
showed employees counting vast amounts of cash at Andonian Brothers
Manufacturing Co. may reflect legal activities.
   Sigel said he would show at the bail hearing next Monday that the
Andonians were ``men of modest circumstances'' who made a legitimate
living by brokering gold at a modest commission.
   He said the Andonians are worth less than $500,000 each, that
each man owns a $250,000 home and ``they make car payments like the
rest of us.''
   He said the Andonians, American citizens who are of Lebanese and
Syrian descent, have been active in community and church affairs and
that religious leaders were anxious to vouch for them in court.
</TEXT>
