<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-BoatAccident     02-27 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Boat Accident,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Witness Testifies on New Year's Eve Capsizing That Killed
55</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California businessman testified
Monday that he saw a Navy sergeant take a bribe to release an
overcrowded tourist boat on New Year's Eve that sank minutes later,
killing 55 people.
   Peter Tripp, an electronics equipment dealer from Beverly Hills
who was on the fateful cruise, told police he was ``certain'' he had
seen one of cruise's organizers pay off a Navy port authority
official who stopped the vessel as it headed for a fireworks display
on Rio's famous Copacabana beach.
   The double-decked Bateau Mouche IV was carrying an estimated 150
people, three under its legal limit, when it flipped over and sank
minutes before midnight. A Navy report later said the boat could not
safely carry more than 62 people.
   In a sworn statement given to Special Investigator Wladimir
Sergio Reale of the Rio de Janeiro state civil police department,
Tripp said a Sgt. Braga of the Port Authority was counting
passengers when a fat bearded man named Mr. Garcia gave him money.
   Francisco Garcia Riveiro, an owner of the Itatiaia Turismo travel
agency that hired the Bateau Mouche IV for the cruise, was briefly
arrested last month, along with the boat's owners, and then
released. Also questioned at that time was Port Authority Sgt.
Antonio Braga Vasconcellos, who boarded the boat for an inspection
but denied taking money.
   The accident caused a national outcry and demands for the
punishment of those responsible. The Bateau Mouche, which sold
tickets at $220 apiece, tipped over amid what survivors said was
overcrowding aggravated by rough water, with life preservers hard to
find or tied down.
   The Rio de Janeiro state government, which has vowed to
aggressively prosecute the case, paid for a first-class round-trip
ticket for Tripp, 40.
   Riveiro's lawyer, Nilo Batista, said Tripp's deposition ``wasn't
worth a second-class ticket on a train.''
</TEXT>
