<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-INS-CentralAmericans     02-27 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-INS-Central Americans,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Granted Asylum In First Week Of Rapid Processing Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAYVIEW, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first week of a crackdown on political
asylum applications ended Monday with approvals granted to only 2
percent of those applying, federal officials said.
   Of 329 applications submitted here, seven have been approved for
asylum since Tuesday, when the Immigration and Naturalization
Service sped up its procedures for handling asylum applications.
   Under the new procedures, all applications are processed in a
single day, but those whose applications are rejected are subject to
immediate arrest and detention and are marked for deportation.
   All seven approved for refugee status are from Nicaragua, said
Virginia Kice, spokeswoman for the agency's Harlingen District at
the southern tip of Texas.
   Political asylum is granted to people who are judged to be
fleeing persecution. The INS instituted its new policy because it
believes most of the emigrants are traveling to the United States
for economic reasons.
   The number of applicants has plunged since the new get-tough
procedure began. INS examiners processed 233 last Tuesday, 51
Wednesday, 10 Thursday, 19 Friday and 16 Monday.
   Two weeks ago, when applicants still were able to travel on to
their U.S. destinations to pursue their cases, the agency was seeing
500 a day.
   Things have slowed down so much that some of the extra personnel
brought in last week to carry out the new procedures went home
Monday, said Al De Leon, assistant district director for
examinations. Twenty-six examiners left Monday, he said, leaving 24
here to process cases.
   One of two State Department personnel on hand since last week to
issue advisory opinions on the cases left Thursday, according to the
INS.
   Sixteen cases processed Monday resulted in 11 denials of asylum,
four approvals and one notice of ``intent to deny,'' meaning that
person was given 15 days to supply improved documentation to bolster
a borderline case.
   An exact number of people affected by the decisions was
unavailable because dependants sometimes file jointly with the
principal applicant, Ms. Kice said.
   The number of people detained as a result of the new procedure
was unavailable, but the inmate count at an immigration service
detention center on Monday was double the population of a week ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
