<DOCNO> AP890227-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PrisonAIDS     02-27 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison AIDS,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York to Begin Testing Departing Prison Inmates for AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state will soon begin voluntary AIDS
testing for convicts leaving the New York prison system, Corrections
Commissioner Thomas Coughlin said Monday.
   Any inmate being released from prison can be tested at their
request, under the program administered by the Corrections, Health
and Parole departments, he said. The program is set to begin April 1.
   Currently, only inmates who exhibit symptoms of acquired immune
deficiency syndrome or who are considered high-risk AIDS candidates
may be tested voluntarily.
   Under the new program, any departing inmate who tests positive
for the AIDS virus will be referred to counseling and health
services, Coughlin said.
   The test is ``kind of a backhanded way of seeing if there is any
(AIDS) transmission'' in the prisons, said the commissioner, who
discussed the new testing program during a joint legislative hearing
on the 1989-1990 prisons budget.
   Coughlin said he doesn't believe AIDS is spread among inmates.
   ``I think there is sexual activity and I think there is drug
abuse going on, ... but I don't think that you're going to find
massive transmission of the AIDS virus within the prison system,''
he said.
   The AIDS epidemic has not exploded within the prison system, as
some people expected, Coughlin said.
   ``Everybody said four, five years ago that the prisons would have
thousands and thousands of AIDS cases,'' Coughlin said. ``But it
just hasn't happened.''
   The AIDS patient rate has remained constant, at about three per
thousand, for three years, he said. There are now about 400 inmates
with AIDS symptoms.
   Coughlin gave the AIDS education program for all inmates partial
credit for averting an explosion of AIDS in the prisons.
   However, he said he's still preparing for an increase in inmate
AIDS cases ``because of the number of drug abusers we have in the
system.''
   AIDS is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
