<FIRST>u p AM-ChicagoMayoral 3rdLd-Writethru a0752 02-27 0964</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0752,0989</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daley, Sawyer Busy on Final Day of Chicago Mayoral Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, ``Sawyer, the ...'' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
church rally, Jackson quotes; picks up 4th graf, ``Daley was ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer stepped up the pace of his
campaign Monday, buoyed by late poll results showing him closing in
on Democratic rival Richard M. Daley one day before a court-ordered
primary election.
   ``We're going to get our people to knock on doors all during the
day today and tonight and tomorrow morning,'' Sawyer said during a
campaign stop at a West Side high school, one of at least 10
campaign events during the day.
   Sawyer, the city's second black mayor, was joined by Jesse
Jackson at the school and at a South Side church. He also campaigned
at a public housing project, two senior citizens centers and other
spots.
   At the South Side church Monday night, the finale of Sawyer's
primary campaign, Jackson tried to rally blacks by recalling the
long struggle for the right to vote.
   ``We died too young, bled too profusely and lost too many martyrs
to not vote,'' he said. ``We stand tonight on the tombstone of the
martyrs who paid not with the dollar but their lives for the right
to vote.
   ``Vote for Sawyer with a passion!'' Jackson said.
   Daley was busy, too. The son of legendary Mayor Richard J. Daley
visited restaurants, shook hands with commuters at elevated train
stations and walked through neighborhoods in a frenetic final day of
campaigining.
   ``I'm campaigning very hard,'' Daley assured reporters as he made
one of more than 15 planned campaign stops.
   Tuesday's primaries in the nation's third-largest city are a step
toward filling the vacancy left by former Mayor Harold Washington,
Chicago's first black mayor, who died in November 1987. The Illinois
Supreme Court last year ordered the special election to fill the
last two years of his term.
   Sawyer, who was elected acting mayor by fellow aldermen days
after Washington's death, has been struggling to keep the seat. But
as election day neared, he steadily closed on Daley, the Cook County
state's attorney.
   Poll results released Monday showed Sawyer 7 percentage points
behind.
   Until the last two weeks, the campaign had been relatively free
of the racial rancor that had marked recent mayoral elections. Since
then, Daley has been accused of being a racist and Sawyer's camp
made use of a videotape in which Daley appears to tell a
predominantly white audience that ``you want a white mayor.''
   Daley denied making the statement. His supporters say the
candidate, who is well known for garbling his syntax, slipped and
inserted an extraneous word that sounded like ``what,'' not
``white.''
   The election marks the fifth time in two years that Chicago
voters have been called to the polls, and some residents appear to
be turned off by the campaign.
   ``What they need to do is stop this black and white stuff and get
a qualified person,'' said Sidney Turner, 43, an undecided voter.
   The Chicago election is one of three mayoral elections taking
place around the nation Tuesday.
   In St. Petersburg, Fla., three challengers are trying to unseat
Mayor Robert Ulrich in a nonpartisan primary. And in Wichita, Kan.,
where residents approved a change in the structure of city
government last November, 16 candidates are vying in the first
mayoral election since 1916.
   In Chicago, the Board of Election Commissioners predicted 68
percent of the city's 1,549,367 registered voters would go to the
polls. Temperatures are expected to be in the 20s with a threat of
light snow.
   Although early polls showed Daley far ahead of Sawyer, both
candidates said the latest results confirm what they maintained
throughout the campaign _ Tuesday's vote would be close.
   ``This race is virtually tied up,'' Sawyer campaign spokesman
Larry Horist said.
   Daley and Sawyer are the top contenders in the four-way
Democratic primary Tuesday, while three candidates are running on
the GOP ballot.
   But the wild card in the race is former Alderman Edward Vrdolyak,
who bolted the Democratic Party after a 1987 third-party loss to
Washington. He is running as a write-in candidate on the Republican
ticket, and could give Sawyer an edge by siphoning off white votes
from Daley.
   Because of the difficulty of counting write-in votes, the outcome
of the Republican race might not be known until Thursday, when the
Board of Elections makes its final count.
   The winners of Tuesday's election will run in a general election
April 4 to determine who will finish the final two years of
Washington's second term.
   Washington's former City Council floor leader, Alderman Timothy
Evans, will be running in that election as a third-party candidate,
hoping to stake a claim to Washington's solid black voting bloc.
   The latest poll indicates that the electorate remains divided
along racial lines.
   Sawyer received the support of 73 percent of the black voters
surveyed to Daley's 8 percent. White voters split 79 percent for
Daley, 14 percent for Sawyer. Hispanic voters, who could hold the
key to the election outcome, favored Daley by a 2-1 margin.
   Despite the polarization _ and some eleventh-hour racial
controversy _ the election has been remarkable for its lack of
racial animosity, many observers have said.
   ``I think that this campaign marks a real positive movement for
the city,'' said John McDermott, chairman of The Committee on Decent
Unbiased Campaign Tactics, a watchdog group formed after the
racially divisive 1983 elections that led to Washington taking power.
   ``Despite the ... racial rhetoric in the past week, the number of
incidents of ... appealing to bigotry or bias or using fear of the
other group has declined considerably,'' McDermott said.
 
</TEXT>
