<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LibelCase     02-27 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libel Case,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Reinstates Libel Judgment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $3 million libel verdict against The
Detroit News has been reinstated by the Michigan Court of Appeals,
which ruled in an opinion released Monday that somebody can be
defamed by implication.
   Even if no specific sentence in a story is false and libelous,
the court said in its 3-0 ruling, a lawsuit can be successfully
brought over the full context of the article, including the
headlines, photographs and page layout.
   ``You can libel someone by innuendo ... in the false impression
that it creates,'' said Jeremiah Kenney, attorney for two men who
sued the Evening News Association, publisher of The Detroit News,
and several reporters.
   Joseph Locricchio and Gary Francell charged that a series of 11
articles in 1978 and 1979 ``falsely portrayed, implied and
insinuated'' they had organized crime ties and were engaged in other
criminal conduct in the development and operation of Pine Knob, an
outdoor entertainment center northwest of Pontiac, the appeals court
said.
   Kenney said in filing the lawsuit that the plaintiffs ``pointed
to the totality of the articles'' which included implications of mob
ties, two unsolved murders, and a series of illegal financial
arrangements.
   A Wayne County Circuit Court jury awarded $3 million to Francell,
but didn't give anything to Locricchio.
   Judge Michael Connor subsequently dismissed the case, saying the
men hadn't proven the articles were false. Connor said that to find
the inferences of the articles libelous was contrary to both
Michigan law and federal law.
   The appeals court, however, said the two men had a case even
though their charges weren't based on a specific false statement in
a particular article.
   The court said it believed that Michigan law has not eliminated
defamation by implication reinstated the jury award.
   Kenney said he didn't think the ruling upholding defamation by
implication represented a new step in libel law. ``In our view, it
has been the law in Michigan for many, many years,'' he said.
   James Stewart, an attorney for the News, said he disagreed with
the ruling.
   ``We believe the decision is regrettable and wrong,'' he said. He
said the ruling means that a person can sue successfully for libel
despite stories being factually correct.
   He said lawyers would consult with newspaper officials on whether
to appeal the case to the state Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
