<FIRST>r a AM-CrackKid     02-27 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack Kid,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>10-Year-Old Crack Dealer Ordered Put in Group Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Monday ordered a 10-year-old
convicted crack dealer taken out of detention and placed in a group
home for troubled children pending the boy's sentencing.
   Suffolk County Family Court Judge Donald Auperin ordered the boy
placed in the custody of the Little Flower Children's Service in
Wading River, on the northern shore of Long Island, until the boy is
sentenced.
   Auperin heard testimony behind closed doors from a psychologist
and a psychiatrist about their evaluation of the child.
   The boy has been in the Nassau Children's Shelter since his Jan.
14 arrest, when undercover police saw him and a 14-year-old
companion selling crack from the back of a bicycle in a rundown
suburban neighborhood.
   Police said the 10-year-old dropped a bag containing three $20
vials of crack, and that the boys also had $226 in cash.
   Auperin found the 10-year-old guilty of juvenile delinquency for
selling and possessing a controlled substance. The 14-year-old's
case was being handled separately.
</TEXT>
