<FIRST>r a AM-TireFire 1stLd-Writethru a0772 02-27 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tire Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0772,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tire Dump Burns and Owner Alleges Arson</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT distance to 40 miles, sted 80.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CATSKILL, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About five acres of burning tires continued
to send smoke billowing into the air Monday, and the operator of the
unlicensed tire dump contended that arsonists were to blame for the
blaze.
   ``Have they caught the arsonist yet?'' asked Richard Evans, owner
of Casings Inc. ``Those tires sat there for a long time and they
don't set fire to themselves, so it has to be arson, right?''
   Evans blamed opponents of the dump for the crisis. ``It was
probably the townspeople who say they don't want it here that
started it.''
   The tire dump has been operating without a license for the last
year since landowner Dominick Valentine's permit application was
turned down. Valentine allows Casing Inc. to operate the dump on his
property.
   No cause has been established for the fire, which began Saturday
and forced the overnight evacuation of 200 families. While schools
were closed Monday, stores near the fire reopened and there were no
evacuations.
   Fire crews used heavy equipment to pull the tires apart in an
effort to halt the fire's spread, and about 40 trucks brought in
loads of dirt and cement dust to smother the flames.
   The tires may be as deep as 30 feet to 130 feet, according to
Harold Tompkins, president of Fire Hose Co. No. 1 in Catskill, and
the fire could burn on for days.
   Tompkins said the federal Environmental Protection Agency had
declared that the level of toxins in the acrid, black smoke was no
danger to human health.
   He said one firefighter suffered heat exhaustion, but no other
injuries were reported. Health alerts were posted for people with
respiratory problems, officials said.
   Catskill is about 40 miles south of Albany.
</TEXT>
