<FIRST>u w AM-Tower 6thLd-Writethru a0763 02-27 1063</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tower, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0763,1,030</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Democrats Unmoved on Tower Pledge as Bush Flies Home to Lobby</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: To update with Warner, Dole quotes from meeting, adds 2 new
grafs after 5th graf previous ``White House''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats remained unmoved Monday in
their opposition to John Tower's nomination as defense secretary
despite his unprecedented pledge to abstain from alcohol if
confirmed. President Bush returned home declaring that he hasn't
``wavered one iota'' in his support.
   Moments before Air Force One touched down at Andrews Air Force
Base, Bush told reporters that only ``time will tell'' as to whether
Tower will win Senate confirmation.
   ``I don't have any predictions nor do I plan to, except to say I
haven't wavered one iota and I don't intend to,'' Bush said.
   Asked if Tower's pledge would help his cause, Bush shrugged his
shoulders and said, ``I don't know.''
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu met with Republican
senators and Vice President Dan Quayle on Monday night to discuss
the embattled Tower nomination.
   After the meeting, Sen. John Warner, R-Va., ranking Republican on
the Armed Services panel, said there was no discussion about a
withdrawal by Tower. ``The strategy is to go all the way to the mat
and there will be a vote.''
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., who was also in the
meeting, agreed. ``There wasn't any plug mentioned. No pulling of
any plug.''
   During the day, senators trekked to a special committee hearing
room to read the latest FBI report on Tower, while those members the
Bush administration hopes to sway indicated they are either
undecided or leaning against confirmation.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, speaking to reporters on
Air Force One as Bush returned to Washington, said the president
will meet with 12 senators beginning early Tuesday morning.
   Fitzwater declined to identify them but congressional staff said
Sens. George Mitchell, D-Maine; Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas; Charles
Robb, D-Va.; Bennett Johnston, D-La.; Bill Bradley, D-N.J., and
Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., were among those invited to the White
House.
   Bush also telephoned DeConcini from aboard Air Force One and
urged him to reserve judgment until he had a chance to see all the
evidence, according to the senator's staff.
   ``We're going to work real hard. We're going to talk to a lot of
people and ask them to keep an open mind and to read the FBI report
and to talk to John Tower,'' Fitzwater said.
   Of Tower's pledge not to drink if confirmed, Fitzwater said, ``I
think it should help. It should take care of the drinking
situation.''
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., considered by some a swing vote, told
reporters in Miami that Tower's pledge helps but ``it's not just the
drinking which is a problem to me.''
   ``It's a pattern of bad judgment _ bad judgment in the 1970s in
drinking, bad judgment by placing himself in compromising positions
as the U.S. arms negotiator in Geneva in the mid-80s, bad judgment
in accepting large sums from the defense industry in the late
1980s,'' Graham said.
   The Democratic-controlled Senate Armed Services Committee voted
11-9 along party lines last Thursday to recommend tha the full
Senate reject the nomination, with panel chairman Sen. Sam Nunn,
D-Ga., citing Tower's drinking habits among other concerns.
   Tower on Sunday sought to allay the fears of his former
colleagues by issuing an extraordinary pledge not to take a single
drink if he is confirmed. The full Senate is expected to take up the
nomination Wednesday.
   Democrats hold a 55-45 majority in the Senate, meaning Bush must
pick up at least five Democrats and hold all Republicans to assure
confirmation. Under that scenario, Quayle would break the tie.
   Those Democrats who hinted that they will oppose confirmation
emerged from the special Senate hearing room saying that Tower's
promise and a reading of the FBI report did little to change their
mind.
   ``It's like marrying someone who says, `Trust me, I'll reform,'''
said Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill. ``You can't do that ... The experience
with people who have problems with drink is that these pledges get
broken much too easily.''
   ``I have not heard of any vote changes as a result'' of Tower's
pledge, said Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., an opponent of the nomination.
He said the pledge could be a ``double-edged sword .... It might be
interpreted that he wants the job too bad.''
   Sen. Thomas A. Daschle, D-S.D., said the pledge ``will have a
marginal effect.'' And Sen. John Breaux, D-La., said he would vote
against Tower if the vote were today.
   ``If any senator has a serious doubt about the competence of a
candidate, that he should err on the side of safety,'' said Breaux.
``In that case, it indicates voting negatively.''
   The president flew home from his five-day Asia trip Monday and
planned to meet with undecided Democrats in hopes of capturing
enough votes for Tower.
   The administration is also faced with some wavering Republicans.
Over the weekend, Sen. Nancy Kassebaum of Kansas said she was
undecided and Sen. Larry Pressler of South Dakota said he would vote
against confirmation.
   Robb, also undecided, said he was keeping ``an open mind.'' But
he called Tower's action an ``astute move on his part. He addressed
at least one of the outstanding questions.''
   Sen. Howell Heflin of Alabama, one of several Southern Democrats
still considered open to the White House lobbying effort, said he
has ``to review all the evidence'' was trying to be ``open-minded,
judicial and fair.''
   Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., said he admired Tower for his pledge
and declined to disclose his decision. But he said he doesn't intend
to read the FBI report. Earlier this month, Pryor said Tower has
``become his own worst enemy'' and predicted that he would not be
confirmed.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., told a news conference in
Hartford that he remains undecided and will make a decision after
reading the FBI report.
   Republicans repeated their support for Tower with Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., saying he didn't find ``anything more (in the report)
than I've found so far'' and Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., claiming
that the pledge ``puts to rest any doubts about his capabilities or
any impairment.''
   The White House is preparing a version of the confidential FBI
report for public release in hopes of demonstrating that allegations
against Tower are baseless.
</TEXT>
