<FIRST>r a AM-Haitian-Drugs     02-27 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haitian-Drugs,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Haitian Colonel's Drug Trial Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drug trial of a retired colonel in the
Haitian army began in federal court Monday with the prosecutor
saying the case was about treachery and betrayal.
   Gary Leon was arrested Nov. 18 when he allegedly accepted a
package containing cocaine from a close friend who is a distant
cousin. The cousin claimed he unwittingly transported the drugs from
Haiti at the request of Leon's wife.
   Leon is charged with conspiracy to traffic in drugs, possession
of cocaine and drug importation.
   His attorney, Calvin David Garber, said in opening arguments in
U.S. District Court in Brooklyn that Leon led ``an exemplary life''
and that until a few months ago had held a high position in the
Haitian military.
   Garber said the Port-au-Prince man's career held no hint of
corruption or drug use.
   Assistant U. S. Attorney Martin Coffey said in his opening
statement that the case was about ``treachery and betrayal.''
   Coffey said the case began Nov. 17 in Haiti when Leon's wife,
Edith, went to the home of the cousin, Marcel Neptune, who was
preparing to leave that day for New York.
   She asked Neptune to take five gift-wrapped packages, which she
said contained perfume and cosmetics, and give them to her husband,
who was in New York, according to Coffey.
   Neptune, a prominent businessman in Port-au-Prince, was arrested
at Kennedy International Airport when Customs agents discovered two
pounds of cocaine inside four of the packages.
   Coffey said Neptune agreed to cooperate with U.S. authorities and
arranged a meeting the next day with Leon at a fast-food restaurant.
   Neptune wore a recording device during the meeting and was under
surveillance by federal agents, the prosecutor said. During their
meeting, Neptune told Leon that the packages contained drugs and
Leon denied knowing anything about it.
   Leon accepted one cocaine-filled package and told Neptune he
would call his wife to clear up the problem, Coffey said. He was
arrested as he left the restaurant.
</TEXT>
