<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq     02-27 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraq To Hold First Presidential Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq will hold its first presidential
election, state-run television reported Monday, without saying when
the ballotting will take place.
   The decision to hold a presidential election was originally made
in 1980, but the war with Iran which broke out in September that
year forced postponement, the report said.
   Under Iraq's Constitution, the president and vice president are
elected by the ruling nine-member Revolutionary Command Council.
   The television said talks were under way to include a provision
for regular presidential elections in a new constitution now being
drafted by a special government committee. The committee is headed
by Izzat Ibrahim, vice chairman of the Revolutionary Command Council.
   The government said Sunday a referendum will be held to approve
the proposed new constitution and a new parliamentary election law,
allowing new parties to form.
   General elections for the 255-member National Assembly, or
parliament, are scheduled for April 1 after being delayed since
August.
   The television gave no details about the decision to hold the
presidential election.
   But it said President Saddam Hussein's office notified a TV law
program on the issue after a citizen asked, ``Why is the presidency
a monopoly of the Baath Party?''
   No presidential election has taken place in Iraq since the army
overthrew the monarchy in a 1958 coup.
   After further coups, the Baath Socialist Party ousted the
military in a bloodless 1968 putsch with army Brigadier Ahmad Hassan
al-Bakr, a former prime minister, named president.
   Hussein, his vice president after 1969, became president on July
16, 1979, after a peaceful transfer of power.
   The political developments came as Hussein made tentative moves
to liberalize Iraq following the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the Iraq-Iran
war.
   Iraq has a population of 16 million.
</TEXT>
