<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 0733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Hitler'sBirthday Adv06   02-27 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hitler's Birthday, Adv 06,0852</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs March 6 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Neo-Nazis Prepare for Hitler's 100th Birthday in April</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, ``next month'' in lead is April.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neo-Nazis are preparing
commemorations on the 100th anniversary of Adolf Hitler's birth next
month and West German officials are bracing for possible outbreaks
of rightist violence.
   The Nazi dictator was born April 20, 1889, in the Austrian
village of Braunau just over the border from Bavaria.
   ``This is the most important event we've had in a long time,''
said Michael Kuehnen, West German neo-Nazi leader.
   The preparations come as West Germans warily eye a rise in
extreme-rightist sentiments in their country. In January, for
example, the Republican Party made a strong showing in West Berlin's
elections by calling for the expulsion of foreigners and
asylum-seekers.
   Neo-Nazis from several countries are expected at the ``European
Hitler convention'' specifically designed to commemorate the
dictator's 100th birthday, but Kuehnen declined to specify exactly
when or where it will take place.
   ``We don't want to give the country time to gear up to prevent
it,'' he said but added that Spain or Scandinavia were possible
places. Federal law bars such a meeting in West Germany, although
Kuehnen promises smaller birthday commemorations in the Frankfurt
area.
   The neo-Nazi leader, who often wears a brown shirt and black
pants, said the number of participants at the Hitler convention
could range from 1,000 to ``several thousand'' depending on the
location.
   Kuehnen, whose organizing committee even has a logo with the
initials ``AH'' in the center, insisted there will be no ``organized
violence'' on the Hitler anniversary.
   ``But we aren't responsible for every young person and every
soccer rowdy,'' the 33-year-old neo-Nazi added in a telephone
interview. Fringe groups espousing neo-Nazi and rightist beliefs
occasionally disturb professional soccer games in West Germany.
   Kuehnen, who has spent more than seven years in prison for
neo-Nazi activities, has set up an office in Frankfurt to organize
the birthday event with the help of his followers. He's hoping
neo-Nazis and right-wing extremists from Spain, France, Denmark,
Belgium and Norway as well as West Germany will attend the European
convention.
   Although the birthday falls in April, there were reports as early
as January about plans for an observance in the West German news
media.
   The newsmagazine Der Spiegel said on Jan. 30 that this year's
celebrations are meant to attract public attention and distribute
propaganda, in contrast to previous years.
   In the past ``right-wing extremist cronies drank to the Fuehrer
in the back rooms of German bars and in hotels of Hitler's Austrian
birthplace of Braunau,'' Der Spiegel noted.
   Braunau itself was the site of a clash between neo-Nazis and
pro-Communists on Hitler's 90th birthday in 1979.
   This past Jan. 22, the conservative Welt am Sonntag newspaper
said officials already were bracing for acts of violence and that
Jews and foreigners were possible targets.
   Matthias Strohs, a spokesman on internal security issues for the
Baden-Wuerttemberg state Interior Ministry, agrees that trouble
could break out.
   ``There's no question _ you can count on acts of violence,'' he
said. ``The possible targets range from foreigners, to German
officials and allied military installations.''
   Allies France, Britain and the United States drew the neo-Nazis'
wrath for keeping Rudolf Hess, Hitler's deputy, in prison until he
died in what was officially determined as a suicide in 1987,
although the Soviets were primarily responsible for rejecting pleas
for clemency.
   Strohs, speaking by telephone from his office in Stuttgart, said
vandalism and pro-Nazi slogans painted on walls were also a
possibility around the time of the birthday.
   The spokesman said officials assume older-generation Nazis will
also commemorate Hitler's birthday, but in a much less public way.
   ``The older ones are much more careful in the way they act,''
Strohs said. ``They won't make such a spectacle out in the public.
It will be more of an internal affair.''
   Alfons Metzger, spokesman for the Bavarian Interior Ministry also
said ``violence can't be ruled out'' as a possibility on the Hitler
birthday and that police are alerted to it.
   Several smaller neo-Nazi groups also routinely celebrate Hitler's
birthday, and are expected to do so again this year. Federal
officials say there are about 28,300 right-wing extremists in this
country of 61.3 million people.
   The Deutsche Volksunion (German People's Union), identified by
federal authorities as West Germany's largest right-wing extremist
organization, has totally disassociated itself from the Hitler
commemorations.
   ``We are convinced that on April 20, 1989, there will be several
birthday celebrations for Hitler,'' said Bernd Droese, spokesman for
the party, which claims a membership of 25,000. ``Fifty percent of
them will take place in loony bins, where some people assert they
are the reincarnation of the Fuehrer.
   ``The other 50 percent will be organized by agents and
provocateurs who want to let the specter of the Fuehrer ghost wander
around.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs March 6</NOTE>
