<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 0742EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv06   02-27 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv06,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, March 6</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, March 6, the 65th day of 1989. There are 300
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On March 6, 1836, the Alamo in San Antonio, Texas, fell to
Mexican forces after a 13-day siege. All 187 defenders of the
mission compound _ including Davy Crockett and James Bowie _ were
killed.
   On this date:
   In 1806, poet Elizabeth Barrett Browning was born in Durham,
England.
   In 1834, the city of York in Upper Canada was incorporated as
Toronto.
   In 1853, Verdi's opera ``La Traviata'' premiered in Venice, Italy.
   In 1857, in its ``Dred Scott'' decision, the U.S. Supreme Court
held that Scott, a slave, could not sue for his freedom in a federal
court.
   In 1933, a nationwide bank holiday declared by President Franklin
D. Roosevelt went into effect.
   In 1935, retired Supreme Court Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr.
died in Washington.
   In 1944, U.S. bombers staged a daylight raid against Berlin
during World War II.
   In 1957, the former British African colonies of the Gold Coast
and Togoland became the independent state of Ghana.
   In 1967, the daughter of Josef Stalin, Svetlana Alliluyeva,
appeared at the U.S. Embassy in India and announced her intention to
defect to the West.
   In 1981, Walter Cronkite signed off for the last time as
anchorman of ``The CBS Evening News.''
   In 1982, author-philosopher Ayn Rand died in New York at age 77.
   In 1983, in a case that drew much notoriety, a woman in New
Bedford, Mass., said she had been gang-raped atop a pool table in a
tavern called Big Dan's. Two men were later convicted of the crime.
   In 1983, the pro-environment, anti-nuclear ``Greens'' party won
seats in West Germany's lower house of parliament for the first time.
   In 1987, 189 people died when water rushed through the open bow
doors of the ``Herald of Free Enterprise,'' causing the British
ferry to capsize off the Belgian port of Zeebrugge.
   Ten years ago: A jury was empaneled in Oklahoma City in the case
of nuclear plant worker Karen G. Silkwood, who was contaminated with
plutonium through what Silkwood's family charged was the negligence
of her employer, Kerr-McGee Corp., shortly before her death in a
1974 car crash. Although the jury ruled against Kerr-McGee, an
appeals court in 1985 ordered a re-trial.
   Five years ago: Democratic presidential hopeful Gary Hart won
Vermont's preference vote by a wide margin over Walter F. Mondale,
following victories over Mondale in the New Hampshire primary and
Maine caucuses.
   One year ago: The board of trustees at Gallaudet University in
Washington D.C., the world's only liberal arts college for the deaf,
chose a hearing woman, Elisabeth Ann Zinser, school president over
two deaf candidates. Outraged students shut down the campus, forcing
Zinser's ouster and the selection of a deaf president in her place.
   Today's Birthdays: TV personality Ed McMahon is 66. Conductor
Sarah Caldwell is 65. CIA director William Webster is 65. The
chairman of the Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan, is 63. The first
woman in space, Soviet cosmonaut Valentina Tereshkova, is 52. Actor
Ben Murphy is 47. Opera singer Dame Kiri Te Kanawa is 45.
Actor-director Rob Reiner is 42.
   Thought for Today: ``Caveat actor.'' Let the doer beware. _ Latin
proverb.
   End advance for use Monday, March 6
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890227-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 0745EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv07   02-27 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv07,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday, March 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, March 7, the 66th day of 1989. There are 299
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On March 7, 1926, the first successful trans-Atlantic
radio-telephone conversation took place, between New York and London.
   On this date:
   In 1849, horticulturist Luther Burbank was born in Lancaster,
Mass.
   In 1850, in a three-hour speech before the U.S. Senate, Daniel
Webster endorsed the Compromise of 1850 as a means of preserving the
Union.
   In 1875, composer Maurice Ravel was born in Cibourne, France.
   In 1876, Alexander Graham Bell received a patent for his
telephone.
   In 1911, the United States sent 20,000 troops to the Mexican
border as a precaution in the wake of the Mexican Revolution.
   In 1936, Adolf Hitler ordered his troops to march into the
Rhineland, thereby breaking the Treaty of Versailles and the Locarno
Pact.
   In 1945, during World War II, U.S. forces crossed the Rhine River
south of Cologne, Germany.
   In 1965, a march by civil rights demonstrators was broken up in
Selma, Ala., by state troopers and a sheriff's posse.
   In 1975, the U.S. Senate voted to revise its filibuster rule,
allowing 60 senators to limit debate in most cases, instead of the
previously required two-thirds of senators present.
   In 1986, former Senator Jacob K. Javits, R-N.Y., died in Palm
Beach, Fla., at age 81.
   In 1987, Britain's Queen Elizabeth II and Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher led their nation in grieving for the 189 people who died
when a British ferry capsized off the Belgian coast the day before.
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter left Washington on a
personal mission to the Middle East to try to personally negotiate
final details blocking a peace treaty between Israel and Egypt.
   Five years ago: Three Israelis were killed when a bomb exploded
on a bus in the port city of Ashdod, south of Tel Aviv, in the third
major attack on Israeli Jews in three months.
   One year ago: Three Israelis were killed when three Arab gunmen
hijacked a commuter bus in the Negev Desert; the hijackers were
themselves killed when Israeli forces stormed the vehicle.
   Today's Birthdays: Photographer Lord Snowdon is 59. TV weatherman
Willard Scott is 55. Auto racer Janet Guthrie is 51. Actor Daniel J.
Travanti is 49. Actor John Heard is 44. Rock singer Peter Wolf is
43. Football player Franco Harris is 39. Football player Lynn Swann
is 37. Tennis player Ivan Lendl is 29.
   Thought for Today: ``I would rather live in a world where my life
is surrounded by mystery than live in a world so small that my mind
could comprehend it.'' _ Henry Emerson Fosdick, American clergyman,
1878-1969.
</TEXT>
