<HEAD>For Release Wednesday, March 8</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, March 8, the 67th day of 1989. There are 298
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On March 8, 1782, the Gnadenhutten massacre took place as some 90
Indians who had converted to Christianity were murdered by
militiamen in Gnadenhutten, Ohio, in retaliation for raids carried
out by other Indians.
   On this date:
   In 1702, England's Queen Anne ascended the throne upon the death
of William III.
   In 1841, U.S. Supreme Court Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr. was
born in Boston.
   In 1854, U.S. Commodore Matthew C. Perry made his second landing
in Japan. Within a month, he concluded a treaty with the Japanese.
   In 1874, the 13th president of the United States, Millard
Fillmore, died in Buffalo, N.Y.
   In 1894, New York enacted the first dog-licensing law in the
nation.
   In 1917, the first of two Russian Revolutions began with rioting
and strikes in St. Petersburg.
   In 1917, the U.S. Senate voted to limit filibusters by adopting
the cloture rule.
   In 1930, the 27th president of the United States, William Howard
Taft, died in Washington.
   In 1942, the Japanese captured Rangoon, Burma, during World War
II.
   In 1965, the United States landed about 3,500 Marines in South
Vietnam.
   In 1983, the House Foreign Affairs Committee endorsed a nuclear
weapons freeze with the Soviet Union, a proposal denounced the same
day by President Ronald Reagan as a ``very dangerous fraud.''
   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter met for 2{ hours in Cairo
with Egyptian President Anwar Sadat in an effort to help bring about
a peace treaty with Israel, but both sides said afterward that
``unresolved issues'' remained.
   Five years ago: A Gallup survey said Democratic presidential
hopeful Gary Hart led President Ronald Reagan in a national sample
of voters, 52 to 43 percent. The sampling of 719 registered voters
contained a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
   One year ago: Vice President George Bush was the big winner in
the ``Super Tuesday'' Republican presidential primaries. Among
Democrats, Michael S. Dukakis, Jesse Jackson and Albert Gore split
the lion's share of delegates.
   Today's Birthdays: Retired Senator Jennings Randolph, D-W.Va., is
87. Actress Claire Trevor is 80. Actress-dancer Cyd Charisse is 68.
Actress Sue Ane Langdon is 53. Former baseball player and author Jim
Bouton is 50. Actress Lynn Redgrave is 46. Actress Susan Clark is
45. Actor Mickey Dolenz is 44. Actress Jaime Lyn Bauer is 40.
Baseball player Jim Rice is 36.
   Thought for Today: ``Never vote for a tax bill nor against an
appropriations bill.'' _ American political maxim.
</TEXT>
