<HEAD>For Release Saturday, March 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, March 11, the 70th day of 1989. There are 295
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On March 11, 1888, the famous ``Blizzard of '88'' struck the
northeastern United States. In the days that followed, some 400
people died as a result of the harsh weather.
   On this date:
   In 1810, Emperor Napoleon of France was married by proxy to
Archduchess Marie Louise of Austria.
   In 1847, John Chapman, better known as ``Johnny Appleseed,'' died
in Allen County, Indiana.
   In 1861, the Confederate convention in Montgomery, Ala., adopted
a constitution.
   In 1865, during the Civil War, Union forces under General William
T. Sherman occupied Fayetteville, N.C.
   In 1930, former President and U.S. Chief Justice William Howard
Taft was buried in Arlington National Cemetery.
   In 1941, President Franklin D. Roosevelt signed into law the
Lend-Lease Bill, providing war supplies to countries fighting the
Axis.
   In 1942, during World War II, General Douglas MacArthur left
Bataan for Australia.
   In 1954, the U.S. Army charged that Wisconsin Sen. Joseph R.
McCarthy and his subcommittee's chief counsel, Roy Cohn, had used
pressure to obtain favored treatment for Private G. David Schine, a
former consultant to the subcommittee.
   In 1965, a white Boston minister, the Rev. James J. Reeb, died
after being beaten by whites during civil rights disturbances in
Selma, Ala.
   In 1977, more than 130 hostages held in Washington D.C., by
Hanafi Moslems were freed after ambassadors from three Islamic
nations joined the negotiations.
   In 1978, 34 Israelis were killed as Palestinian guerrillas went
on a bloody rampage on the Tel Aviv-Haifa highway.
   In 1982, protesting his innocence, Sen. Harrison A. Williams Jr.,
D-N.J., resigned after 23 years in the Senate, rather than face
expulsion in the wake of his ``ABSCAM'' conviction.
   In 1985, the Soviet Union announced the death of its leader,
Konstantin U. Chernenko, and said that Politburo member Mikhail S.
Gorbachev had been chosen to succeed him as Communist Party General
Secretary.
   Ten years ago: Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin hosted a
state banquet for President Jimmy Carter, who appeared grim as Begin
warned in his toast that ``serious problems'' still stood in the way
of a peace treaty with Egypt.
   Five years ago: Gary Hart found himself the target of criticism
during a debate of Democratic presidential candidates, particularly
from Walter F. Mondale, who ridiculed Hart's ``new ideas'' theme.
   One year ago: Saying, ``I got a fair hearing, and the people have
decided,'' Gary Hart withdrew a second time from the race for the
1988 Democratic presidential nomination.
   Today's birthdays: Bandleader Lawrence Welk is 86. Former British
Prime Minister Harold Wilson is 73. Civil rights leader Ralph D.
Abernathy is 63. Newspaper publisher Rupert Murdoch is 58. ABC
correspondent Sam Donaldson is 55. Supreme Court Justice Antonin
Scalia is 53.
   Thought for today: ``For a fiction writer, to believe nothing is
to see nothing.'' _ Flannery O'Connor, American author, 1925-1964.
