<FIRST>s i BC-APN--YeatsAnniversary Adv12-2Takes   02-27 1116</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Yeats Anniversary, Adv 12-2 Takes,1137</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 graphic.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ Nobel laureate William Butler Yeats died in the
South of France in l939, but World War II delayed the return of his
remains to Ireland for almost a decade. Now on the 50th anniversary
of his death, a great mystery hovers over his grave in Ireland. Did
the French undertakers dig up the wrong body or just send any old
body? If so, where is the Irish bard? And what does that epitaph on
his tombstone mean?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</NOTE>
<NOTE>AP Special Correspondent</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DRUMCLIFF, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty years after his death, tourists
by the busload and in a procession of rental cars pay scant heed to
the epitaph William Butler Yeats had carved on his tombstone in the
little churchyard here:
   ``Cast a cold eye
   ``On life, on death.
   ``Horseman, pass by!''
   Last year, 50,000 visitors from as far away as Japan and
Australia trooped into the Church of Ireland graveyard ``under bare
Ben Bulben's head,'' the flattopped mountain that like a huge grand
piano with the lid down echoes the winds and waves of the wild
Atlantic. Some carried well-thumbed volumes by the Nobel laureate
regarded by many as the sublimest poet of the English language since
Milton.
   ``Even on the foulest, wettest day, if I leave the church open,
someone is sure to come by and sign the guest book,'' says the Rev.
Robert Hayman, an American from San Francisco by way of Seattle who
is rector of St. Columba's, the rural Protestant parish where Yeats'
great-grandfather had served.
   Record numbers are expected for this year's semicentennial
observance of the poet's death. In August, scholars and lecturers
from around the world will gather for the 30th session of the Yeats
International Summer School.
   For something to write postcards home about besides ``the most
wild and beautiful scenery under a sky ever loaded and fantastic
with flying clouds,'' as Yeats described it, there is renewed
controversy over whether the poet actually lies beneath the epitaph
he composed four months before his death in 1939. For certain, his
wife is buried there, memorialized by a smaller stone engraved
``George,'' which also mystifies visitors.
   ``Like a plague of locusts, that question of the wrong body in
the grave comes up every seven years,'' scoffed Aengus Cantwell,
president-elect of the Council of the Yeats Society, which
administers his library and memorial in the old Royal Bank building
in Sligo. ``Willie probably would have enjoyed this morbid joke on
himself, but it's very distasteful for his son, Michael, and
daughter, Anne, to have to go through it all over again.''
   Yeats in declining health sought the warmth of the French
Riviera, where he died on Jan. 28, 1939. The outbreak of World War
II delayed compliance with his wish to be buried at Drumcliff, so
his casket was taken to the little cemetery at Roquebrune on the
heights overlooking Menton and Monaco in the shadow of the Alps.
   Rumors of what happened there resurfaced last fall when British
biographer Diana Souhami was researching the life of Dutch painter
Hannah Gluck, a close friend of Yeats. She reported finding
``letters from the priest in Roquebrune and the undertakers''
casting doubt on who was buried where. Her version has Georgie
Yeats, the poet's widow, consigning his remains to a temporary
grave, which she thought would remain untouched for at least 10
years. Instead, claimed the writer, he was buried in a paupers'
grave ``with four or five others,'' which was cleared in 1946 and
``all the bones placed in a common ossuary.''
   Biographer Souhami said artist Gluck and journalist Edith Heald
visited Roquebrune a year later and ``were shocked to find no trace
of Yeats' grave.'' Gluck had friends write to the priest, who
replied that it would be possible to identify the poet's remains
``if we empty the entire contents of the ossuary and if we have
details of distinctive characteristics which will enable us to
reconstruct the skeleton after painstaking research carried out
under the direction of a medical expert.''
   But, according to Souhami, ``Yeats' purported remains were
exhumed and shipped to Ireland just one month later _ much too soon
to enable the bones to be indentified'' with scientific precision.
   In a letter to the Irish Times, Michael Yeats, a member of the
Irish Senate like his father, denounced her claims as ``the greatest
nonsense.'' He insisted his mother had overlooked the whole
operation and the remains were measured. ``It is absolutely certain
that my father is buried in County Sligo,'' he wrote. ``I have the
documentation to prove it.''
   All of which keeps alive a bizarre and macabre tale of the sort
William Butler Yeats would have relished hearing from the farmers
and fishermen around Sligo Bay and retelling in glorious, ghoulish
detail in his folk collection titled ``Mythologies.'' Even the
reburial of Yeats at a grand state funeral is an enduring chapter in
the oral history of Ireland's wild west.
   The American critic Hugh Kenner found this out when he
interviewed the locals more than three decades after that September
morning in 1948 when the Irish gunboat Macha brought the remains to
Galway harbor ``whence they bumped to Sligo, past knots of
schoolchildren standing mute with their teachers, along roads never
built for a poet's gliding.''
   He was told ``for a fact'' how ``the coffin was a substitute
filled with stones, how drunken sailors let the original slide into
the unplumbed Mediterranean; also how the Macha ran aground in Sligo
harbor before being diverted to Galway, and how her load, whether
stones or lead-encased bones, instantly broke the hearse's springs.''
   It's almost a tale told by ``Silly Willie himself,'' as Cantwell
said Sligo people still characterize the poet from his habit of
walking solitary and often barefoot along the strand at Rosses
Point, through the woods of Lissadell, on the lake isle of
Innisfree, up tortuous trails to the barren heights of Ben Bulben
and Knocknarea and the other childhood haunts that echo in his
lovely lines.
   Yeats was born in Dublin, lived much of his life in London and
died in France. Yet he always regarded Sligo, where he spent every
boyhoood summer, as his home. His barrister father gave up law to
become a painter. His brother, Jack, was Ireland's leading artist.
   His mother's side of the family, the seafaring Middletons and
Pollexfens, were steamboat captains, smugglers and eventually
prosperous ship owner's on whom a poor poet could always depend for
a free passage home from Liverpool.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890227-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1419EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-APN--YeatsAnniversary Adv12-1stAdd   02-27 1032</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Yeats Anniversary, Adv 12-1st Add,1058</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 12</HEAD>
<HEAD>DRUMCLIFF, Ireland: from Liverpool.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Young Willie spent many summers with Uncle Henry Middleton at
Elsinore House, which had a secret tunnel for the delivery of
contraband from the beach and the ghost of that smuggling ancestor
strolling the veranda or tapping at the window pane.
   Nearby lived bachelor uncle George Pollexfen, a spirit-raising
medium who imbued Yeats with a lifelong infatuation with horoscopes,
seances, crystal balls, tarot cards, telepathy and remembering
bizarre dreams like the apparition of ``Bernard Shaw as a smiling
sewing machine.''
   Young Yeats sat with old people by their turf fires to hear myths
and legends he later retold in ``The Celtic Twilight'': tales about
Queen Maeve buried in the massive cairn near the top of Knocknarea,
the warrior Cuchulain who fought the horses of the sea in Sligo Bay,
and the O'Cuirnin family of Gaelic bards with whom he felt a mythic
kinship when rowing out to their island in Lough Gill.
   Yeats set for himself the poetic goal of bringing together
Ireland's heroic legends and rural folklore after listening to tales
told by the likes of ``one Paddy Flynn, a little bright-eyed old man
who lived in a leaky one-room cabin'' on the Sligo road and often
was found ``under a hedge smiling in his sleep'' after dancing the
night away with troops of leprechauns.
   The ghost-mad lad known hereabouts as ``old parson Yeats
great-grandson'' went off to Stockholm in 1923 to receive the Nobel
Prize for literature from the King of Sweden.
   Going down the eight fairway at Rosses Point, the cultured golfer
can see the gray stone walls of Lissadell, the Georgian country
house of Sir Henry Gore-ooth, also haunted and now open to tourists.
Here Yeats wrote a tragic poem to the two daughters that begins:
   ``The lights of evening, Lissadell,
   ``Great windows open to the south,
   ``Two girls in silk kimonos, both
   ``Beautiful, one a gazelle.''
   Constance, the older of two, not the gazelle, whose name was Eve,
was an impassioned Irish revolutionary who was sentenced to a firing
squad for commanding the forces that held St. Stephen's Green during
the Easter Rising of 1916. Her sentence was commuted to life in
prison, and Yeats wrote several poems to her before her eventual
release.
   Britain hurriedly executed 16 leaders of the rising, including
the severly wounded James Connolly, who was carried in a wheel chair
out to the firing squad, and Yeats helped canonize them as martyrs
in a magnificent canto.
   Farther south along the coast in neighboring County Galway is
Coole Park, where for two decades Yeats was the frequent house guest
of the playwright Lady Augusta Gregory.
   The great house in Dublin where they launched the Irish National
Theater, which soon became the Abbey Theater, has been torn down,
but in the walled garden amid the ruins is a huge copper bench
carved with the initials of Yeats, Shaw, Sean O'Casey, John
Masefield, the painter Augustus John and the abbey's resident
genius, John Millington Synge.
   A few miles away is Thoor Ballylee, the 14th century Norman tower
that Yeats renovated as a summer cottage for Georgie Hyde-Lees, the
22-year-old bride he took after years of pining away in impassioned
poetry for actress Maud Gonne.
   George, as she was called in life as well as on her tiny
tombstone, was also a psychic medium who introduced Yeats to
``automatic writing.''
   The tower, which figured in the title of two collections of
Yeats' verse, is now a Yeats museum. Tourists can climb the winding
stairs to the secret room on the top floor where the couple sought
contact with the beyond.
   George continues to intrigue the pilgrims who ignore Yeats'
injunction to pass by the grave.
   ``It's the name of his dog,'' pastor Hayman has heard many a
visitor comment.
   ``Actually,'' said Cantwell, ``Yeats had a dog named Daniel
O'Connell.''
   The poet was never comfortable with the laboring class that
worshiped The Liberator but a generation later deserted Charles
Parnell. Although a shrewd businessman himself, who cast a warm eye
on the abbey's box office, Yeats also professed haughty disdain for
the merchants who ``fumble in a greasy till.''
   The poet, said Cantwell, ``regarded the peasants as the font of
Irish poetic lore and greatly admired the occupants of the stately
houses, but he didn't care much for those in between.''
   A sense of ``romance and adventure'' propelled the Rev. Hayman
from St. Luke's in downtown San Francisco to St. Columba's in rural
Sligo. Several summers before, while based in Seattle, he had
swapped pulpits with a Limerick clergyman and ``fell in love with
Ireland. When Drumcliff became available last March, my wife Sally
and I were ready.''
   Going though the parish archives he discovered that the Rev. John
Yeats, the poet's ancestor, ``had run up a bill of some 400 pounds
with the wine merchant in Sligo, which was a goodly amount in 1846.''
   So far pastor Hayman has had neither the occasion nor the
collection receipts to match that standard of hospitality. His noon
service on Sunday draws a congregation of 55, ``mostly farming
people.''
   But with the advent of summer and the return of the chartered
buses, the parish operates a little tea shop in a shed near the
rectory and provides toilet facilities.
   ``It's really amazing,'' Hayman says. They come from all over.
France. Holland. Germany. Many from Japan and Korea. If you noticed,
we just had new doors put on the church. Those lovely brass handles
were the gift of the Yeats Society of Western Australia.''
   The pilgrims arrive full of awe and sometimes wonder. ``This past
summer,'' Hayman recalls, ``a busload arrived led by a Roman
Catholic priest who was totally dumbfounded to find that Yeats was
buried in a Protestant churchyard.''
   The American pastor at Drumcliff is called upon time and again to
explain that enigmatic epitaph. ``I always have to admit I don't
know what it means. Some scholars say the poet may be addressing his
own ghost. All I know is you could write a Ph.D. thesis on those few
words.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 12</NOTE>
