<DOCNO> AP890227-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-RebuildingBasra Adv05   02-27 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rebuilding Basra, Adv 05,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iraqi Port of Basra Rising from Ruins of War</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BASRA, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sandbags are gone in Basra, Iraq's second
largest city, after years of battering by the Iranians in the
Persian Gulf war. A new city is rising from the rubble.
   ``It's going to be the best city in Iraq,'' said a bank manager,
who identified himself only as Simon. ``Everything's going to be
new.''
   The scars of ferocious Iranian missile attacks and artillery
bombardments are still everywhere: shrapnel-scarred buildings,
groves of decapitated palm trees, abandoned tanks, sunken ships in
the Shatt-al-Arab waterway that meanders through the city to the
Persian Gulf.
   But the souk, or market, is booming. The Sheraton Hotel on the
bank of the muddy Shatt-Al-Arab, peppered by direct shell hits and
deserted for the last two years, opened for business again in
February.
   It was a dispute over territorial claims to the Statt-al-Arab
that led to the war in 1980.
   The two daily flights from Baghdad, Iraq's capital, to Basra's
newly reopened airport are packed with businessmen, including
construction engineers who have come to lobby officials for
contracts.
   On a recent visit, President Saddam Hussein criticized the slow
pace of rebuilding in a city that symbolized Iraq's defense against
six years of Iranian offensives.
   ``The people of Basra deserve their city to be beautiful and more
organized,'' he said.
   His government has pledged $5 billion to repair the damage and
make Basra the centerpiece of a new international industrial zone.
   Founded 1,400 years ago and known as the Venice of the East
because of its network of canals, Basra was Iraq's main port with a
prewar population of 1.5 million. It is just 15 miles from Iran.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's Iranian forces battled to within
six miles of Basra's eastern outskirts in early 1987, putting it
within easy artillery range.
   In the bombardments, 90 percent of Basra's buildings were
destroyed or damaged. Thousands of civilians were killed or wounded
and thousands more fled.
   The port is still blocked because the Shatt Al-Arab is an issue
in the Iran-Iraq peace talks.
   The first major construction project nearby is 23 new piers for
what were minor ports at Um Qasr and Khour el-Zubiar before the war.
   The main work in Basra since the Aug. 20 cease-fire has been
clearing the wreckage.
   Arfan, one of the engineers looking for contracts in Basra,
noted: ``Right now they're just cleaning up, but by the end of the
year there will be lots of work in Basra.''
   Heavy trucks, graders and cranes _ many of them from the military
_ growl through downtown. Hundreds of new apartment buildings,
ringed by fields of mud, have gone up.
   Many were occupied even before they were completed, with
residents using corrugated iron sheets to cover the still-empty
windows.
   In the souk, merchants say they can't keep up with consumer
demand, even though prices have gone up by as much as 25 percent.
   ``We're selling more and more,'' said Mohammed Aslan Mohsen, who
runs an appliances store.
   At the Sheraton Hotel, manager William Meuree, a Belgian, said it
took two days of cleaning the rugs before the colors started to
emerge from the dust.
   The sign above the entrance hangs askew and the acne of artillery
hits across the front of the building is still visible under
concrete patches.
   Meuree said 99 percent of the damage from several direct hits has
been repaired, and 130 out of the 210 rooms reopened.
   Visitors from Baghdad and Kuwait come for the weekend. Many want
rooms looking out over three sunken freighters in the Shatt-al-Arab,
the estuary of the Tigris and Euphrates rivers that runs into the
Persian Gulf. At least 70 ships are stranded there.
   ``Unfortunately there aren't enough rooms on the river to satisfy
everyone,'' said Meuree.
   Basra had a prewar reputation for serendipity as Kuwaits escaping
their nation's alcohol ban made it their weekend watering hole.
   ``They're coming back slowly, it's not like before,'' said
Khamis, the Sheraton's bartender, who estimated that he serves 50
people every weekend night. ``They come to drink, to enjoy
themselves.''
   Down the road from the Sheraton a new nightclub has opened,
surrounded by a wall of plants and black statues of naked women.
   In the neighborhood behind it, residents said everyone who fled
the shelling is back.
   Dawla, a 49-year-old mother of seven, fled in 1986 after bombs
shattered every window in the house and killed a man praying in the
neighborhood mosque.
   The house was missing walls and was partially looted when she
came back after the cease-fire, but it's been rebuilt.
   ``If there's a war again I'll never leave my house,'' she said.
  
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 5</NOTE>
