<FIRST>s a BC-Small-TownDrugs Adv05-1stAdd   02-27 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Small-Town Drugs, Adv 05-1st Add,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the mail.'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _ In Yakima, Wash., the DEA office covering 11 largely rural
counties made 143 arrests last year. ``The only thing that keeps it
from being greater is manpower and money,'' Dreisbach said.
   _ In Georgia, three Americans and six Panamians last year were
convicted of or pleaded guilty to importing about 161 kilos of
cocaine from Panama, via U.S. Army planes, commercial flights or
mail packages sent to Moultrie, Ga. The drugs were then sent to New
York, officials said. Three of the nine had Army ties.
   ``This case is about as hometown as you can get,'' said Bill
Malarney, agent-in-charge of the DEA office in Columbus, Ga. ``You'd
expect a big city to have these problems. But this is a small
southern town and here, you were having cocaine delivered in the
mail!''
   Despite the large number of arrests, most rural drug cases are
smaller, but still take considerable manpower. In Dodge County,
Minn., for instance, undercover officers spent three months
arranging the purchase of 25 pounds of marijuana from two men, who
were charged in December.
   Prosecutors acknowledge many of these cases wouldn't make it into
urban drug-clogged courts.
   ``A lot of what we do here wouldn't be prosecuted in Miami,''
said Murphy, the Iowa prosecutor. ``A kilo of cocaine is of no
special significance for Miami, Los Angeles or a border state.''
   There are other differences. Rural authorities don't have to
contend with heavily armed big-city gangs and may benefit from
small-town residents less tolerant of drug dens in their towns.
   Ironically, though, the everybody-knows-everybody network makes
it harder for undercover agents to operate. Even on rural roads
they're quickly noticed.
   ``It's harder to sneak up on the guy,'' Malarney said. ``You're
talking about a quarter of a mile between houses and there's one
road.''
   But small-town dealers also know how to be inconspicuous.
   ``They don't drive a Cadillac,'' Stevens said. ``They'll drive a
pickup truck. You don't see diamonds and gold ... Everybody knows
them for 20 miles. How can they show up with a $20,000 car and build
a $100,000 house? They're just socking it away.''
   ``If people think they can move to rural areas to get away from
drugs, they're wrong,'' he added. ``There's no place else to go
anymore.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sharon Cohen is the AP Midwest regional reporter,
based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 5</NOTE>
