<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReviews Adv00   02-27 1039</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Reviews, Adv 00,1077</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At The Movies: ``Cousins,'' ``Tap''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Cousins''
   
   It is indeed a sad indictment of the Hollywood movie machine to
see its growing reliance on foreign films as a source for new
American movies. The adaptation market seems frenzied these days
with such remakes as ``Three Men and a Baby'' and ``Three
Fugitives.'' It seems the creative and innovative spark of the
world's greatest movie institution has died.
   The latest redo is ``Cousins,'' Joel Schumacher's graceless
treatment of Jean-Charles Tacchella's charming 1976 comedy,
``Cousin, Cousine.''
   Schumacher makes the mistake of trying to closely follow the
original. Both open with a rousing family wedding scene in which the
husband and wife of two different couples meet, run off for a little
sexual fling and leave their respective mates waiting at the
catering hall for their returns. The cuckholded spouses start up a
harmless flirtation and friendship and eventually have an affair of
their own.
   But where the original danced lightly with the passions and
eccentricities of French culture, the new version applies the thin,
moralistic veneer of an American TV sitcom with idiot level dialogue
and conviction. Simply put, the French have a different way of
viewing adultery.
   Ted Danson, as compelling in this role as a bottle of warm, flat
champagne, plays Larry Kozinski who is married to Tish, played with
airhead finesse by Sean Young. Isabella Rossellini, perhaps cast in
this movie to give it some sort of continental class and a little
sunshine, is Maria Hardy, an understanding wife and mother married
to a brutish bore named Tom (William Petersen) who sells Suburus but
who likes to say he sells BMWs.
   The truly comic moments (which were many in ``Cousin, Cousine'')
are diluted in ``Cousins'' by weighty and blunt situations: When Tom
realizes Maria and Larry are also having an affair, he confronts
Larry in typical Hollywood macho style with, ``If you go near my
wife again, I'll kill you.'' Petersen is more Fred Flintstone than
Valentino.
   What saves ``Cousins'' from utter and total oblivion is the
wonderful patter between Larry's father (Lloyd Bridges) and his son,
Mitch (Keith Coogan). Grandpa and grandson have a bucolic moment
over some girlie magazines, and the scene in which Mitch helps
grandpa Vince prepare for a date with Maria's mother (Norma
Aleandro) is worth the ticket price and popcorn.
   A totally unnecessary addition to ``Cousins'' is the subplot
involving the boy-girl problems Tom and Maria's daughter is having
in pre-school. Who cares?
   Perhaps Hollywood will one day realize that some things get lost
in translation. One would think the lesson would have been learned
in 1983 when Jim McBride remade Jean-Luc Godard's classic 1960 film
``Breathless'' into a pathethic and misguided movie. It starred
Richard Gere, who was embarrassing as he attempted to take on the
role Jean-Paul Belmondo had created in the original.
   Something gets lost in the translation as Hollywood puts its neon
wand to French confections.
   If it ain't broke, then don't fix it....
   ``Cousins,'' a Paramount Pictures release produced by William
Allyn, is rated PG-13.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Tap''
   
   Movie audiences have yearned for those splashy, joyous, romantic
musicals of the 1930s, '40s and '50s when boy met girl, boy lost
girl, boy got girl back and everybody lived happily everafter,
dancing all the way to the altar.
   Nick Castle, whose father choreographed many of those wonderful
Fred Astaire-Ginger Rogers vehicles, attempts to bring back those
golden dance movies with ``Tap,'' a love letter to hoofers great and
small.
   Starring Gregory Hines and some of the greatest tap kings living,
``Tap'' features excellent dancing and a splendid exuberance.
Unfortunately, the movie holds back; the dance sequences never seem
to totally reach their potential.
   One production number, in which Hines takes a club full of tap
fans out to Times Square to feel and hear the beat and rhythms of
the city (such as cars going over metal plates in the road or
construction crews thumping the pavement) and marks out a dance. The
number starts out well, luring the viewer to the rhythms and moves.
Then it fizzles.
   Another disappointment is the wistful roof-top soft shoe
performed by Hines and the lovely Suzzanne Douglas to ``Cheek to
Cheek.'' It's a romantic Fred and Ginger take-off that never really
gets off. How sad.
   The biggest problem with ``Tap'' is Castle's script and story
line. Max (Hines) is a genius dancer who unfortunately finds
second-story work more to his liking than hoofing. After a stint in
jail, he returns to New York where he hooks up with the hoods again.
At the same time, his mentor, Little Mo (Sammy Davis Jr.) encourages
him to resume his dancing and even tries to turn him on to a new tap
innovation _ amplified shoes.
   The plot, though, gets in the way of the dancing. It's not
compelling, poignant or interesting enough. The tap dancing,
however, is.
   Hines, perhaps the greatest contemporary tap stylist around these
days, is marvelous. His supporting cast includes Savion Glover, a
14-year-old hoofer who one day will make the same claim.
   There are also Sandman Sims, Bunny Briggs, Harold Nicholas, Jimmy
Slyde and Steve Condos _ some of the dancers who helped define and
perfect the art and craft of tap during the 20th century.
   And Douglas, who learned how to tap for the movie, is quite good
for a newcomer.
   Forget about the story. See ``Tap'' as a tribute to the great
ones and to appreciate what tap dancing was all about before
Broadway and Hollywood took away its snap and crackle.
   Produced by Gary Adelson and Richard Vane, the Tri-Star Pictures
release is rated PG-13.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
