<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   02-27 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Married to the Mob'' (Orion Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.98, Rated
R)
   
   This delightful comedy should not be missed on the little screen
if you didn't see it in theatrical release.
   Angela, the anguished, beauty school-dropout wife of Mafia
soldier Frankie the Pickle, surveys the crated TV sets in her
too-plush, Long Island living room and wails, ``Everything we own
fell off a truck!''
   So there's trouble in Paradise.
   Frankie is fooling around, her son is scamming the neighborhood
kids at three-card monte, and all her creep friends are gangsters'
wives. ``I want a divorce,'' sobs Angela (Michelle Pfeiffer).
   Frankie laughs. You don't divorce the Mob.
   Next thing you know, Angela's a widow and Frankie's ex-boss, capo
Tony the Tiger (Dean Stockwell) is sniffing around her weeds. This
is not lost on Tony's insanely jealous wife, Connie (Mercedes
Ruehl), or the handsome, young, clean-cut FBI agent (Matthew Modine)
who's out to nail Tony the Tiger.
   This is when things start to get complicated.
   ``Married to the Mob,'' directed by Jonathaan Demme, screenplay
by Barry Strugatz and Mark R. Burns, is a genuinely hilarious movie
that is full of bravura performances by actors at the height of
their powers.
   Pfeiffer, who played the icy blond bimbo in ``Scarface'' and the
love interest in ``Tequila Sunrise,'' is more luminously beautiful
than ever. Her character conveys a tough, smart, innocent
vulnerability that is magic.
   Stockwell's portrayal of clever, weasely Tony deserved his
Academy Award nomination (as did his lunatic cameo as Howard Hughes
in ``Tucker''). So did Mercedes Ruehl, whose crazed Connie adds a
joyously funny intensity to the action.
   Ever since ``Citzens' Band'' (as well as ``Melvin and Howard'' or
``Stop Making Sense'' or ``Swimming to Cambodia''), Demme has been
making important American movies. In ``Married to the Mob'' he makes
one that is pure fun.
   Aces.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Bellman and True'' (Cannon Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated R)
   
   Run out and borrow, rent or buy this one. It was my favorite
video of 1988.
   It's an unrelentingly tense caper movie that inexorably notches
up the tension, yet has at its center a beautiful and moving story
of a father and son.
   Bernard Hill plays a burned-out alcoholic, a computer systems
engineer who takes a bribe to deliver a mysterious computer file to
a cheeky, new-breed London ``villain'' (Derek Newark) and his
henchmen.
   The engineer and his stepson (Kieran O'Brien) are held prisoner
until the file is interpreted, and it turns out to be the cash flow
reports and electronic schematic to the ultra-secure branch bank
serving Heathrow Airport.
   Suddenly it is too late to back out. The gang needs a ``bellman''
to handle the bank's electronics. And there is a share of $25
million.
   ``Your life's a bit gray, these days, isn't it, darling?'' says
the cheeky thug.
   Considered only for its ingenious caper, ``Bellman and True''
would be a worthwhile movie, but the relationship of the father and
son is equally important, heightening the sense of value, risk and
loss.
   Novelist Desmond Lowden wrote the tight, fast-paced screenplay
from his book with director Richard Loncraine with Michael Wearing.
Loncraine's headlong direction utterly crisp, atmospheric and
breathless enough to get you on the edge of your seat. The cast is
superlative, every one.
   Highest recommendation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
