<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RancherArtist Adv10-12   02-27 1079</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Rancher Artist, Adv 10-12,1105</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 10-12 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Designing By the Seat of Your Pants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ask Ned Livingston what he does and even he has
a hard time deciding what it is, exactly.
   There's what he calls ``this stuff'': the chairs and other
furniture he whittles in fluid designs, which sell for big money in
fashionable art galleries in New York and Los Angeles.
   Then there's what he calls ``the land'': the old Gerber Ranch,
which he and his wife inherited with its pastures to irrigate, and
timber to manage.
   And there are the fish in the pond in front of the house, which
need a handful of chopped liver now and then; the red-legged
partridges, which he released into Miller Creek Canyon; and the
Klamath County Planning Commission, on which he serves as a member.
   ``You are talking to a guy who is not particularly sure what
woman he is married to, the furniture or the land,'' Livingston said
one winter's day at his home, which he built in a meadow surrounded
by ponderosa pine and juniper at the foot of Horsefly Mountain.
``And I'm not particularly worried about it.''
   Livingston and his wife, Marilyn, were both born and raised in
this high desert country east of the Cascade Range: Ned in Klamath
Falls and Marilyn on the old Gerber Ranch, which is a good 1{-hour
drive from the city.
   ``We came back here (in the 1950s) after college for a year or
two,'' he said. ``Then we went to the big city looking for a big
architecture job.
   ``If I had proceeded professionally, I would have stayed in San
Francisco. But we kept coming back and coming back. Finally, I said,
`Let's quit looking for ourselves and do what we really want to
do.'''
   So they moved back to the ranch. Livingston started gluing up
pieces of oak and walnut and using a horseshoe rasp to shape
free-flowing chairs, cradles, music stands, benches, coat racks,
library ladders and bar stools. The ones he didn't sell stayed home.
It has taken some years to get six chairs around the dining table.
   ``In the '60s I was really hot,'' Livingston recalled. ``I was
going to burn up the art world with these things. I had a piece in
the Renwick Gallery at the Smithsonian. The point is I had stuff
around the country. Maybe I would sell a piece here, a piece there.
   ``It hasn't built into the kind of thing where I didn't need to
worry about a monthly income. Then comes the estate breaking up. I
had been involved in the operation of this ranch. So the last four
or five years I've let this stuff slide. I've worked on irrigating
the south 40 or thinning timber.
   ``The land is definitely a conflict with this other stuff,'' he
said. ``Most people aren't so fortunate to have that problem. It
would be stupid of me to neglect it.''
   Livingston proudly recites the history of his land, which was
assembled by cattlemen _ first Horsefly Wilson and later the Gerber
brothers _ in the late 1800s out of small homesteads too poor to
support a family. Marilyn Livingston drives about 15 miles on a
cinder road to get to the little logging community of Bly, where she
teaches school. They lease the pastureland for grazing and Ned is
working on expanding the irrigation network to produce more summer
grass.
   He recently cruised several hundred acres of timber. Where the
logging outfit wanted to cut all the mature timber, Livingston left
enough of the big trees to generate new ones and maintain the
diversity of the forest.
   With 20 inches of snow on the ground, he's been able to get back
to what he calls the wood whittling.
   ``My furniture tries to conform to the shape of the human body.
It ends up kind of sculptural.
   ``One of the hardest things to make is a chair. Vitruvius (a
Roman architect from the first century, B.C.) said a building should
accomplish three things: firmness, commodity and delight. What is a
chair but the same three things?''
   Livingston has been working on improving his dining chair, which
he considers his signature work and abstractly calls to mind the
sandhill cranes that breed nearby. ``The bad thing is the scoop seat
makes it hard to get in and out of,'' he says.
   The sketch of his latest idea is in the middle of his notes from
a meeting where a state planning official explained some new
regulations aimed at stopping the fragmentation of Oregon's farm and
forest lands.
   In his shop, an early chair, a prototype for a collasible
cathouse, jigs, horse collars, bicycles and a small hydroplane one
of his two sons built hang from the ceiling. On a work bench, a
portable radio propped on a milk can plays classical music.
   At another bench, Livingston is free-forming a curved lamination
that will form the splayed legs and support the seat of the new
dining chair.
   ``This is the fun part about designing by the seat of your
pants,'' he said. ``You think you know where you're going, but you
don't.
   ``If you look at it, you're looking at the bone and sinew and all
the rest of the mass is subtracted. I get more of a feel for what
makes that baby work.''
   Livingston was intrigued by a suggestion some time back to make
the chairs out of injection-molded plastic.
   ``The way I work with the material, I tend to make the wood into
a plastic material,'' he said. ``You look at a tree limb sticking
out from the trunk, and if that isn't a plastic process, I don't
know what is. Wood is basically a bunch of bendable fibers.
   ``It would be easier to pour the stuff into an injection mold and
spit out one of these chairs every two hours in any color you want
and walk laughing to the bank.''
   Though it takes 40 hours to whittle one of his dining chairs out
of wood, Livingston finds it more friendly than plastic.
   ``It has an inherent warmth about it that's hard to duplicate in
plastic,'' he said. ``Even a warm color in plastic is cold. Whereas
wood, you want to touch wood, feel it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 10-12</NOTE>
