<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--CowboyJunkies Adv10-12   02-27 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Cowboy Junkies, Adv 10-12,0962</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 10-12 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Music Makers: Country-Blues Band Jives on Melancholy ^By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The words like ethereal, despairing, melancholy
and dolorous that mark reviews of the Cowboy Junkies tip off right
away that this is not your average pop group.
   So, learning that vocalist Margo Timmins' apartment on one of
Toronto's trendiest streets is unmarked and hidden away behind some
offices should not come as a surprise.
   ``That's the way I like it,'' she says with a bit of a grimace
when told the address for the scheduled interview was hard to find.
   The publicity machine of the pop music industry is gearing up to
promote one of its unlikeliest recent hits, the Cowboy Junkies'
``The Trinity Session'' recorded in one day in November 1987 at the
Church of the Holy Trinity in Toronto.
   The album, whose production cost was $250, includes eerily
stretched out, sparse versions of Hank Williams' ``I'm So Lonesome I
Could Cry,'' Lou Reed's ``Sweet Jane'' and Patsy Cline's ``Walking
After Midnight.''
   Some haunting originals are included as well, such as ``Misguided
Angel'' and ``200 More Miles.''
   ``In the last two months I've done more interviews than most
people do in a lifetime,'' the 28-year-old Timmins said, taking a
break from packing for a long tour that includes a New York stop to
perform on ``Saturday Night Live.''
   ``It's just a matter of getting used to it,'' she said, with a
laugh. ``It's like everything ... everything's happened so quickly.''
   Her 29-year-old brother, Michael, and his childhood friend Alan
Anton came back to Toronto after stints performing to little acclaim
for a few years in New York and England. They started rehearsing in
the garage of Timmins' younger brother, Pete, then brought him into
the band to play drums. Margo joined to do vocals.
   But not only didn't she see herself as a singer, she also was
concerned that a band with too many family relationships could cause
strains. ``It's worked out really well. Mike and I really work well
together,'' she said.
   Settled in for a conversation with EmmyLou Harris' new record
playing in the background, she said, ``It's an honor for me to sing
his songs.''
   The band has been together since 1985 but publicity swelled last
year after RCA released ``The Trinity Session'' in the United States
and enthusiastic reviews started appearing.
   The music generally is pegged as country-blues with a touch of
the Velvet Underground.
   The Los Angeles Times' critics poll found it the best pop album
of 1988, beating out U2, Tracy Chapman and Prince. Times' critic
Robert Hilburn called them ``mesmerizing.''
   Michael Timmins phones to check if the interview is running
smoothly or if an explanation of how the Cowboy Junkies picked their
name is needed, but Margo tells him it's already been discussed.
   She said the name was chosen because an independent band,
especially in Canada with its smaller market, needs anything it can
get to attract attention. ``I think it did us well at that level,''
she said. ``It's still generating a lot of interest.''
   With the addition of three sidemen, the band has swelled to seven.
   There's been some local sniping about the Cowboy Junkies' success
outside of Canada, where record companies generally have limited
slots that go to bands aimed squarely at the mainstream.
   ``Yes, I think that's really unfortunate that you have to go
across the border to get recognized, but you have to be realistic,''
said Timmins, her shock of light hair pulled back. ``I am in the
American market. It's the facts of life _ but no one's going to get
me to say that I'm an American band.
   ``Whatever makes us Canadian is in our music. I don't think we're
flag raisers. We're much more laid back.''
   She also has limited patience for those who criticize their music.
   ``If you like it, fine. If you don't _ don't listen,'' she said.
``I can't really put my finger on what we're doing. It surprises us;
a lot of it is spontaneous.''
   The slow pacing of the music and the band's quiet demeanor during
performances can take some getting used to.
   ``It's definitely on some weird edge and there's the danger of
falling off at some point,'' Michael said in an interview with the
Canadian Press news agency. ``We've never attempted to be a country
band or a rock band. We just play and this melancholy sound comes
out.''
   ``We've just found when we slow a song down it starts to make
more sense,'' Margo said. ``It leaves us much more room for
interpretation.''
   ``It's a big challenge to play slow. You're asking a lot of the
audience,'' she said. ``There's also the risk that when it doesn't
work, it's dull. And I'm not ashamed to admit it.''
   The decision to record in a church was made for the sound, and
Timmins noted that the ``The Trinity Session'' was centered
consciously around the vocals.
   ``We knew that the church would bring out the best of my voice,''
she said, laughing. ``Singing in a church does a lot for your
vocals.''
   The next album will also be recorded live over a period of time
in different locations.
   ``When you record live, the room is an acoustical instrument,''
she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 10-12</NOTE>
