<FIRST>r f PM-BoeingImage     02-27 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing Image,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aircraft Accident Another Reflection On Boeing's Name</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Plane Emergency, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another air disaster involving a Boeing Co. plane
has officials of the Seattle-based manufacturer shaking their heads
over what appears to be a lengthy bout with bad luck.
   On Friday, a huge hole ripped open in the fuselage of a United
Airlines Boeing 747 shortly after it took off from Hawaii, and nine
people died when they were sucked from the aircraft. The pilot was
able to land the crippled plane at Honolulu.
   Federal investigators believe failed cargo door locks may be
responsible, but National Transportation Safety Board officials have
not come to any conclusions.
   Although Boeing's business is booming, it's not been a good year
for the aerospace giant, which has seen a number of mishaps and
accidents involving its jets.
   It also is dealing with an embarrassing delay in shipping its
newest airplane, the long-range 747-400, and reports of miswiring in
some newer Boeing models.
   ``What you have here is a series of events, and the only
correlation is that they're happening in the same time frame, but if
you dissect each one you will find that they're totally unrelated,''
said David Jimenez of Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
   With news reports of problems in rapid succession, however, ``it
does become one large blur to the public,'' Jimenez said.
   ``The planes carry the Boeing name and it reflects on the Boeing
image any time there's an accident no matter what the cause,'' said
Boeing spokesman John Wheeler. ``We're concerned about what happens
to every airplane throughout its life.''
   Friday's tragedy was chillingly reminiscent of an April 28, 1988,
accident in which a flight attendant was killed and 61 people hurt
when the top of an Aloha Airlines Boeing 737 built in the late 1960s
peeled off at 24,000 feet during a flight over Hawaii. That accident
focused attention on the question of how long aging aircraft can fly.
   More recent events that have focused attention on Boeing planes
include the Dec. 21 terrorist bombing of a Pan American 747 over
Lockerbie, Scotland, in which 259 people on the plane and 11 on the
ground were killed; the January crash of a British Midland Airways
737 in England, killing 44 people; and the Feb. 8 crash of a
chartered 707 in the Azores, which left 144 dead.
   Whatever the public perception of Boeing's name, the people who
buy the planes are voting with their checkbooks.
   Last year, Boeing broke industry records for new aircraft orders
at 636 commercial jets worth nearly $30 billion. About 65 percent of
all commercial jets in the air are Boeings.
   Production lines are backed up two years or more at Boeing and
its two competitors, McDonnell Douglass Corp. and Airbus Industrie,
and industry analysts say the boom should continue into the
mid-1990s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
