<FIRST>r f PM-FoundryRevival     02-27 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foundry Revival,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Worker: Closure of Foundry Nightmare; Reopening Brings Tears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRANITE CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven years ago, Milton Wright entered
a living nightmare.
   The American Steel Foundries plant where he had worked for 19
years closed. Bills mounted as he struggled to find work, and
unemployment put a strain on his marriage, which ended in divorce.
He sought professional help to calm his nerves.
   ``When we shut down, most of us said we're gonna' get a two,
three month's rest,'' Wright, 51, recalled. ``Six months later when
your unemployment runs out, you say, `Hey, what's gonna happen to
me?'
   ``Then, a year later, it's a nightmare.''
   Wright finally found work as a supervisor in another
steel-related plant in this Southern Illinois community, where he
now makes between $30,000 and $40,000 annually. But this week, he
was overjoyed to learn ASF plans to resume production at its
foundry, once the nation's largest producer of railroad
undercarriages, and that he is eligible for recall.
   The foundry's revival is a godsend for more than 200 workers who
expect to be rehired. An estimated 650 employees were laid off when
the plant shut down in late 1982.
   ``I can't think of anything else that would make me happier than
to see this plant open up,'' Wright said. ``I have tears in my eyes
right now.''
   At its peak in 1979, when U.S. manufacturers produced about
94,000 railroad cars, the foundry employed about 1,700 people, said
ASF president Norman A. Berg.
   But then the railroad parts industry collapsed, spurred by
deregulation and an oversupply of cars. In the early 1980s, the
industry faced a surplus of nearly 300,000 railroad cars, said Elwyn
Ahnquist, president of the Chicago-based American Railway Car
Institute.
   Wright, a father of two who lives in nearby Venice across the
Mississippi River from St. Louis, said he was devastated when the
foundry shut down, and had to scramble to feed his children.
   ``You can tell them you ain't got a job, but how do you tell them
you ain't got no food?''
   But the dark days are ending now. The surplus is over, Berg said,
and many of the 1.2 million cars in use now are obsolete or near
that stage.
   In May, he said, the foundry will resume producing cast steel
side frames and bolsters, which form the undercarriages, or trucks,
of railroad cars.
   Already, the plant has 35 employees getting it ready for
reopening, and in the next couple of weeks, another 30 will be added
to complete preparations, plant manager William Donovan said.
   By early summer, the company expects to recall 200 more workers
at roughly a $10 hourly wage.
   The American Railway Car Institute, an association of railroad
car makers, projects the manufacture of about 25,000 cars for 1989,
Ahnquist said.
   Since the early 1980s, Berg said, ASF pumped more than $14
million into the foundry for improvements. In 1988, it spent about
$1 million to ready the plant for possible production.
   ``We're really tickled,'' Berg said. ``We're really excited about
this thing.''
   So is Wright, who calls ASF ``the best company to work for.
   ``Whether I go back or not, I am concerned about my co-workers,''
Wright said. ``Hopefully, they'll be able to go to work at American
Steel and say, `Hey! Once again I'm a working man. I have my pride
back.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
