   The Federal Reserve Board dramatically
escalated its fight against inflation by raising its key bank
lending rate to the highest level in three years to dampen upward
pressure on prices.
   The Fed's action Friday repudiated recent Bush administration
claims that price increases haven't been serious enough to warrant
higher interest rates. Private analysts said the move was long
overdue and should have been stronger.
   The central bank raised the discount rate, the fee it charges for
short-term loans to member banks, 7 percent from 6.5 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a week of tough questions over what
critics see as big gaps in President Bush's 1990 spending plan,
Budget Director Richard Darman expressed optimism that serious
negotiations will soon begin with Congress over a compromise budget.
   Darman predicted Friday that in the next two weeks the
administration and congressional leaders will begin crafting a
compromise budget for fiscal 1990, which begins next Oct. 1.
   Democrats in Congress have insisted they want the White House to
put more details about Bush's budget on the record before they enter
into negotiations.
