<FIRST>r f PM-SEC-Prime     02-27 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-Prime,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Reportedly Investigating Prime Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission reportedly
is investigating whether MAI Basic Four Inc. violated federal stock
margin rules in its hostile bid for Prime Computer Inc.
   An MAI spokesman confirmed that SEC investigators questioned
executives about the value of collateral MAI pledged to finance the
takeover offer, according to a published report today.
   MAI Basic, based in Tustin, Calif., is offering $20 a share for
Prime in a deal that values the Natick minicomputer maker at $970
million.
   The Boston Globe said congressional sources told it about the SEC
investigation into the takeover bid. SEC spokeswoman Mary McCue
today declined to comment on the report.
   The Federal Reserve sets margin rules to limit the amount of
unsecured debt used to back the purchase of stock. Stock has been
pledged to back loans of nearly $1.5 billion that MAI would use to
buy Prime.
   ``We've had informal, cordial and cooperative discussions with
SEC staff,'' an MAI spokesman said. ``We've answered all of the
questions they've asked of us. And as we previously stated in our
offering documents, we believe our offer complies with all margin
rules.''
   U.S. District Judge A. David Mazzone blocked MAI's bid last
month. A hearing is scheduled Thursday before the 1st U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Boston.
   MAI is challenging Prime's defenses against the takeover in
Delaware Chancery Court.
   Mazzone in late December said the highly leveraged nature of
MAI's bid raised questions about compliance with margin requirements.
   U.S. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and Massachusetts
Democratic Congressmen Edward J. Markey and Barney Frank had
questioned the SEC's enforcement of federal margin rules in
takeovers.
   SEC Chairman David S. Ruder said the commission is examining
``factual and legal questions relating to possible margin violations
in...pending tender offers.''
</TEXT>
