<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-TimesSquare     02-27 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Times Square,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Challenge to Time Square Redevelopment Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected a challenge to
a proposed $2 billion Times Square redevelopment project in New York
City opponents say will mean more traffic congestion and air
pollution.
   The court, without comment, refused to hear arguments that the
redevelopment will lead to violations of federal clean air standards.
   Challengers to the project include Brendan Gill, a well-known
author and critic; Stephen F. Wilder, head of the Metropolitan
Transit Authority's citizens advisory committee; and others who live
and work in the midtown Manhattan area.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last August that the
challengers are not entitled to renew their attack on the project.
The appeals court said the opponents already ``have had their day in
court,'' losing a state court challenge to the redevelopment.
   There is no need to relitigate the issues in federal court, the
appeals court said as it upheld a federal judge's dismissal of the
lawsuit.
   There have been more than two dozen legal challenges to the
project by environmentalists, local residents, business owners and
others who say it will destroy historic landmarks.
   The plans include redevelopment of 13 acres centered on 42nd
Street between Seventh and Eighth Avenues. The project would include
construction of four large office towers, a 2.4-million-square-foot
wholesale mart and a hotel. It also would include the renovation of
nine movie houses into theaters and retail space.
   The case is Wilder vs. Thomas, 88-1103.
</TEXT>
