<FIRST>u f BC-Ford-Retirement     02-27 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ford-Retirement,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Mum On Early Retirement Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Clay Ford, the last member of Ford Motor
Co.'s founding family in a top-level executive post, may announce
his retirement within the next two weeks, according to a published
report Monday.
   The retirement of the last living grandson of founder Henry Ford
as vice chairman would leave the company without a family member in
a high-ranking executive position for the first time in history, The
Wall Street Journal reported.
   ``It's a speculative story, and we have nothing to say about
it,'' Ford Motor Co. spokesman Tom Foote said Monday.
   Announcement of the retirement may come at the company's March 9
board meeting, the newspaper said.
   William Clay Ford will be 64 years old March 14. The newspaper
said he likely will retire for personal and health reasons.
   Ford talked about retiring while recuperating last April from
heart surgery. ``Next February is 40 years (with Ford), and I think
that's a pretty good round number to quit on,'' Ford, owner of the
National Football League Detroit Lions, told sportswriters during
the NFL's player draft.
   The Wall Street Journal said Ford will remain as a director and
as chairman of the board's finance committee. Family members control
40 percent of the company's voting stock, and William Clay Ford is
the largest individual shareholder.
   His son, William Clay Ford Jr., 31, and nephew Edsel B. Ford II,
40, are middle managers at Ford. While Chairman Donald Petersen has
said promotions should be based solely on merit, the Ford family
would like one of its own in a high post.
   ``I don't think CEO is necessary, but I do think there ought to
be a Ford in some clearly visible management spot,'' William Clay
Ford recently told Fortune magazine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
