<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RigCount     02-27 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rig Count,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rig Count Slips by 9 to Total 757</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of working oil and gas rigs fell by
nine to 757 this week, after turning in a good performance last
week, Baker Hughes Inc. reported.
   Last week, the count rose by 20 to total 766. A year ago, the
count was 983, Baker Hughes said in its weekly report Monday.
   Baker Hughes economist Ike Kerridge said the count usually drops
off during late December through late March or early April.
   The rig count is a widely watched industry index of drilling
activity and it reflects the number of rigs actively exploring for
oil as of last Friday, not the number of rigs actively producing oil.
   Houston-based Hughes Tool Co., an oil toolmaker company that
merged with Baker International Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept
track of the rig count since 1940.
   In December 1981 at the height of the oil boom, the rig count
reached a peak of 4,500. But oil prices plunged to less than $10 per
42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, prompting a collapse in the
rig count that bottomed out at 663 _ the lowest since Hughes began
compiling figures.
   Among major oil producing states, Texas saw the biggest decline
with 14; followed by Louisiana and New Mexico, five each; Ohio and
Pennsylvania, three each; Kansas, two; and California, Colorado,
Michigan and Oklahoma, one each.
   Wyoming and North Dakota saw the only increases with rises of
four and three, respectively.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890227-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1224EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Scotus-Jurisdiction     02-27 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Jurisdiction,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court to Rule on Illinois Firm's Right to Challenge Texas Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether an Illinois insurance company may sue in federal court to
challenge a Texas man's worker compensation award.
   The justices said they will use the case to decide whether worker
compensation insurers can get into federal court with such
challenges when the employer they insure is based in the same state
as the allegedly injured employee.
   Northbrook National Insurance Co., based in Illinois, is the
insurer for Whitmore Line Clearance Inc. in Texas.
   In 1987, Northbrook sued in federal court in Texas over an award
made to Larry W. Brewer for injuries allegedly suffered while
working for Whitmore.
   Legal papers submitted to the high court did not describe
Brewer's work or his injuries, or the size of the award he won. The
legal documents also did not state in what Texas city Whitmore is
based.
   U.S. District Judge Paul Brown in Paris, Texas, dismissed the
case after ruling that he lacked the jurisdiction to hear it.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld Brown's ruling last
Sept. 13. The appeals court said Northbrook could get into federal
court, under a doctrine called ``diversity jurisdiction,'' only if
Whitmore were based in a state other than that where Brewer resided.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the insurance company
said other federal appeals courts have not restricted federal court
access in that way.
   The case is Northbrook National Insurance vs. Brewer, 88-995.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
