<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-GrandMet     02-27 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Grand Met,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pillsbury's New Owner Reorganizes Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC said Monday it is
reorganizing operations following the $5.7 billion acquisition of
Pillsbury Inc. last year.
   A new unit called Grand Metropolitan Foods Group Europe, with
annual sales expected to be about $2.5 billion, will hold
Pillsbury's European food interests as well as the non-dairy
operations of Grand Met's Express Foods, the company said.
   The businesses are spread throughout Britain, France, Spain, West
Germany and the Netherlands.
   Grand Met will manage its remaining food operations outside the
United States, which are mainly dairy interests, under the Express
Foods Group (International) umbrella.
   A new unit called Pillsbury International, based in the United
States, will run the food interests of Pillsbury in Canada, Latin
America and the Far East. Pillsbury International is expected to
have annual sales of about $500 million.
   Ian Martin, head of Grand Met's food sector, said Monday that the
company believes Pillsbury brands such as Green Giant and Burger
King have strong international potential.
   ``This reorganization is an indication of the importance we place
on the development of these brands as part of our strategy to
strengthen our position as a major world food company,'' Martin said.
</TEXT>
