<FIRST>r f BC-Venezuela-IMF     02-27 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Venezuela-IMF,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuelan Team Travels to Washington to Sign Letter of Intent with
IMF</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of Venezuelan negotiators
traveled to Washington to sign a letter of intent with the
International Monetary Fund for a $1.5 billion bridge loan to
bolster the country's troubled economy.
   The loan is intended to back up economic reforms begun by the
government of President Carlos Andres Perez, who inherited a largely
bankrupt state-subsidized economy crippled by falling oil prices and
a $33 billion dollar foreign debt _ the fourth largest in Latin
America.
   Central Bank President Pedro Tinoco, among the negotiators who
left Caracas late Sunday, told the El Nacional newspaper that he
could sign the letter with IMF by Tuesday.
   Venezuela also is seeking short-term loans from the U.S. Federal
Reserve and the Central Bank of Spain worth $1.1 billion, contingent
on the signing of the letter of intent with the IMF, according to
banking sources.
   The World Bank also is prepared to provide money to back up the
reforms, according to representatives in Caracas last week. They
refused to discuss a specific sum.
</TEXT>
