<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against most major currencies
Monday in busy European trading marked by strong interest in the
West German currency.
   Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the Deutsche mark firmed amid
continued speculation that the Bundesbank, the West German central
bank, would raise interest rates. The bank has a council meeting
scheduled for Thursday.
   Interest in the mark, coupled with worries over the British
economy, combined to hurt the pound despite repeated intervention by
the Bank of England.
   On the whole, interest in the dollar was dampened by active
trading in the mark and sterling.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7440 dollars, less expensive
for buyers than $1.7520 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates, compared with late Friday: 1.8150 West
German marks, down from 1.8270; 1.5495 Swiss francs, down from
1.5602; 6.1775 French francs, down from 6.2265; 2.0490 Dutch
guilderslire, down from
1,350.00; and 1.2025 Canadian dollars, up from 1.9990.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 126.00 yen, down 0.29 yen from Thursday's
close. Japanese financial markets were closed Friday because of the
state funeral of Emperor Hirohito. Later, in London, it was quoted
at 126.35 yen.
   Bullion dealers said the dollar's softness nudged gold prices
higher, but that each time gold moves up to the $391-an ounce level
profit-taking brings it back down.
   Gold traded late in London at a bid price of $389.00 a troy
ounce, down from $390.20 bid late Friday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $390.25, up from $389.00 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.61 to close at a bid $392.94
an ounce.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.93 a troy ounce,
down from Friday's $6.04.
</TEXT>
