<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1600EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HousingConstruction     02-27 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housing Construction,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Declines 1 Percent In Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release after 6:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction starts declined 1 percent in
the fourth quarter compared with the same period of 1987 and the
apartment market remained especially weak, according to a private
report Monday.
   For all of 1988, construction was begun on 9 percent fewer
dwelling units than in 1987, F.W. Dodge Group of McGraw-Hill
Information Services Co. said. Housing starts declined 14 percent in
1987 from 1986.
   ``The stability of single-family home building over the past few
years stands in sharp contrast to the virtual collapse of apartment
construction,'' George A. Christie, chief economist of F.W. Dodge,
said in a written statement.
   Single-family home construction fell 7 percent over the two years
from 1986 to 1988, to 1.01 million units, while multi-family
dwelling construction plummeted 41 percent to 448,000 units over the
same period, Christie said.
   Housing starts reached their peak of the decade at 1.85 million
units in 1986 before falling to 1.59 million in 1987 and 1.46
million in 1988.
   Apartment construction was stimulated beyond demand by tax
incentives in the mid-1980s and vacancies remain high, Christie said.
   Construction of one-family houses has remained stable at 1
million to 1.1 million a year for the past three years, he said.
   This year, higher interest rates should hurt the single-family
housing market more than the apartment market, he said.
   The California housing market was stimulated in 1988 by
developers' rushing to beat no-growth initiatives on the state
ballot, Christie said. The initiatives were defeated.
   Leading the nation in housing starts in the fourth quarter was
the Los Angeles-Long Beach are, at 10,473 units, up 2 percent over
the 1987 fourth quarter.
   Rounding out the top 10 were Riverside-San Bernardino, Calif.,
9,449, up 15 percent; Atlanta, 9,316 units, down 3 percent;
Washington, 9,306, down 27 percent; Philadelphia, 6,072, down 1
percent; Chicago, 6,058, up 7 percent; Las Vegas, 5,469, up 115
percent; Seattle, 5,467, down 19 percent; West Palm Beach-Boca
Raton-Delray Beach, Fla., 5,442, up 19 percent; and Detroit, 5,134,
down 2 percent.
   For 1988 as a whole, the top 10 were: Riverside-San Bernardino,
51,795, up 22 percent; Washington, 49,300, down 10 percent; Los
Angeles-Long Beach, 45,177, down 11 percent; Atlanta, 42,386, down 8
percent; Philadelphia, 25,048, up 4 percent; Chicago, 24,830, down
17 percent; Detroit, 24,147, down 5 percent; Seattle, 22,823, up 7
percent; San Diego, 21,609, down 20 percent; and Phoenix, 21,412,
down 21 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
