<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   02-27 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0258</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices declined Monday
at the Chicago Board of Trade, but analysts said supportive
fundamentals helped temper losses.
   Farmer selling of corn and soybeans picked up steam over the
weekend and helped pressure prices, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Traders were further discouraged from buying by the notion that a
selloff is due after the markets' strong gains last week, he said.
   In the wheat pit, traders sold after a rumored sale of export
bonus wheat to the Chinese on Friday failed to materialize.
   But anticipation that a deal with China still may be in the
works, and expectations that the Soviet Union may make a bid on
corn, helped curb the decline in those pits, Lespinasse said.
   Weather is playing a supporting role, and the slightest hint of
another dry spring could send prices soaring, he said.
   ``All we need is a weather scare for the market to respond''
because of a lack of commodity reserves following last year's
drought, Lespinasse said.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 3 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in March at $4.32{ a bushel; corn was 1} cents lower to
{ cent higher, with March at $2.69} a bushel; oats were 3\ cents to
6} cents lower, with March at $1.99{ a bushel; and soybeans were 4{
cents lower to 1{ cents higher, with March at $7.56{ a bushel.
