substantially on Monday as dealers awaited January trade figures.
   Fears of higher interest rates contributed to the negative
feeling, heightened by further steep declines in the British
currency.
   Nervousness before Wednesday's trade report for January kept many
institutional investors on the sidelines during Monday's session,
dealers said.
   At the close the FT-SE 100-share index was down 22.8 points, or
1.12 percent at 1996.7. The late afternoon rally came as Wall Street
moved slightly into positive territory after a weak start.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index was down 19.2 points
at 1644.2. The Financial Times 500 share index fell 11.9 points to
1,138.05.
   Trading activity was light. According to stock exchange figures,
413.8 million shares changed hands. But dealers said the figure was
not representative, as new reporting rules that took effect Monday
allowed market makers to report trades of more than 100,000 pounds
on the following day.
