<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened against all major
currencies in moderate trading Monday after ending weaker overseas.
   Gold prices declined. Republic National Bank of New York said
gold was bid at $386.50 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EST, down $2.50 from
Friday's late bid.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's turnaround domestically
to firmer short-term U.S. interest rates, particularly the federal
funds rates, the interest on overnight loans between banks. The fed
funds rate was trading at 9~ percent, up from 913-16 percent Friday.
   Short-term rates rose sharply on Friday as the Federal Reserve
raised its discount rate by a half percentage point to 7 percent due
to concerns about inflation.
   Higher interest rates tend to support a currency.
   Also lending support to the dollar Monday was belief that the
West German Bundesbank won't be raising its short-term interest
rates when it meets on Thursday, explained James T. McGroarty, a
vice president at Discount Corp. in New York.
   Speculation of such a hike had pushed the West German mark higher
overseas at the expense of the British pound, traders said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 126.00 yen, down 0.29 yen from Thursday's
close. Japanese financial markets were closed Friday because of the
state funeral of Emperor Hirohito.
   The dollar was quoted at 126.35 yen in London, and 126.78 yen in
New York, up from 126.125 yen late Friday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7440, less expensive for
buyers than $1.7520 late Friday. Sterling fetched $1.7380 in New
York, down from $1.7530 Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday's
levels, included: 1.82435 West German marks, up from 1.81875; 1.5530
Swiss francs, up from 1.55245; 1.20325 Canadian dollars, up from
1.19825; 6.2070 French francs, up from 6.1940; and 1,343.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,342.50 Italian.
   Late dollar rates in Europe included: 1.8150 West German marks,
down from 1.8270; 1.5495 Swiss francs, down from 1.5602; 6.1775
French francs, down from 6.2265; 2.0490 Dutch guilders, down from
2.0630; 1.2025 Canadian dollars, up from 1.9990; and 1,339.62
Italian lire, down from 1,350.00.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $387.30 a troy ounce, down $3.80 from Friday's
settlement price.
   Gold traded late in London at a bid price of $389.00 an ounce,
down from $390.20 bid late Friday. In Zurich, the bid price was
$390.25, up from $389.00 bid late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.61 to close at a bid $392.94
an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices declined. On New York's Comex, silver for
current deliver fell to $5.845 a troy ounce from $5.923 late Friday.
In London, silver fell to $5.93 an ounce from Friday's $6.04.
