<FIRST>r f AM-Coastal-TexasEastern     02-27 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coastal-Texas Eastern,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coastal Leaves $2.6 Billion Offer for Texas Eastern on Table</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coastal Corp. said Monday its $2.6 billion cash
offer for Texas Eastern Corp. will remain on the table pending the
completion of a competing $3.2 billion tender offer for the company
by Panhandle Eastern Corp.
   Coastal, however, said it does not intend to increase its
$42-per-share offer to a level that would be competitive with
Panhandle Eastern's $53-per-share bid for 80 percent of the
Houston-based natural gas company.
   Coastal currently owns about 2.5 million of Texas Eastern's 60.8
million common shares and said it may sell some or all of these
holdings in the open market or in private transactions.
   Coastal's offer, which began Jan. 17, was extended last week and
is scheduled to expire at midnight March 10. Panhandle Eastern's
offer expires at midnight March 20. Both are natural gas companies
headquartered in Houston.
   Coastal said in a statement that its intentions are based on
information currently available to it and could change if it
receives additional relevant information or as a result of its
ongoing review of the situation.
   Texas Eastern's board of directors rejected Coastal's bid calling
the offer inadequate.
   Panhandle Eastern's deal, which the Texas Eastern board approved,
called for the company to buy 80 percent of the company. Shares not
purchased under the cash offer would be exchanged for Panhandle
Eastern stock at the same $53 a share.
   The combination of Texas Eastern and Panhandle Eastern would
create a 27,000-mile pipeline system, while Texas Eastern-Coastal
merger would create a 30,000-mile network. Both would be the
second-largest in total miles behind Enron Corp., also of Houston,
that has 38,000 miles of pipe.
</TEXT>
