<HEAD>Malaysian Investor Launches Tender Offer for SSMC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by Malaysian investor Vincent Tan on
Monday announced a $33-a-share tender offer for SSMC Inc., the
Shelton Conn.-based maker of Singer sewing machines.
   The group, Berjaya Corp. (Malaysia) Berhad, already owns slightly
less than 10 percent of SSMC's 7.1 million outstanding shares,
giving its tender offer for the remaining stock a value of about
$211 million.
   The offer expires at midnight EST on March 24, according to an
advertisement published Monday.
   The tender offer is conditioned on Berjaya acquiring a majority
of the shares and on SSMC rescinding its so-called poison-pill
anti-takeover measure.
   The offer from Berjaya comes after SSMC already has definitively
agreed to be acquired by Semi-Tech Microelectronics (Far East) Ltd.
for about $23 a share plus $7 of preferred stock, totaling $220
million.
   Semi-Tech is a sewing-machine distributing unit of International
Semi-Tech Microelectronics Inc. of Toronto.
   The offer from Berjaya expires at midnight EST on March 24,
according to an advertisement published Monday.
   The tender offer is conditioned on Berjaya acquiring a majority
of the shares and on SSMC rescinding its so-called poison-pill
anti-takeover measure.
   According to the SEC filing, Stamford, Conn.-based Singer Co.,
controlled by Paul Bilzerian, has agreed to buy Singer Furniture
Co., a SSMC subsidiary, for $40 million in cash.
   Under the agreement, Singer would sell to Berjaya its ``Singer''
trademark for an undisclosed sum. Also, Berjaya would sell SSMC's 49
percent interest in Regnis (Malaysia) Sdn. Bhd. for $50 million.
</TEXT>
