<HEAD>Energy Price Advance Moderates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices finished higher Monday but
below the day's best levels as the recent rally began losing
momentum.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, unleaded gasoline for March
delivery rose 0.56 cent to end the day at 50.67 cents a gallon.
March heating oil gained 0.92 cent to settle at 52.65 cents a gallon.
   ``The products did perform pretty well today,'' said John
Rowland, a trader at E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc. But he
added, ``The markets are slowing down a little bit.''
   He said the performance Monday largely reflected brokers buying
before the March contracts expire on Tuesday.
   Crude oil prices also strengthened. The April contract for the
benchmark U.S. crude, West Texas Intermediate, gained 7 cents to
finish at $18.14 a barrel.
   The temporary shutdown of a pumping station on the trans-Alaska
oil pipeline, which halted the flow of oil in the line for several
hours during the weekend, had little, if any, effect on crude
prices, dealers said.
   One of three pumps at Pump Station One failed Saturday when snow
got into its ventilation system, melted and caused an electrical
short, said Tom Brennan, spokesman for the Alyeska Pipeline Service
Co.
   The station's other two pumps failed that night when air intakes
froze shut on their booster pumps, he said.
</TEXT>
