<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     02-27 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cotton Prices Surge As Pakistan Curbs Exports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cotton futures prices surged Monday at the New York Cotton
Exchange, fueled by reports that Pakistan is halting all new export
sales and by rumors of purchases by China.
   On other markets, declines were posted in grains, soybeans,
precious metals and cattle prices, while hog prices were mostly
lower and pork bellies were mostly higher. Oil prices were mixed.
   News out of Pakistan, a leading cotton producer and exporter
behind China, the United States, Soviet Union and India, was the
major factor in the cotton pit, said Ed Whitten, an analyst with New
York-based Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   ``Pakistan has issued an edict to not allow any more exports,''
he said, adding that it is unclear if the move is temporary or
permanent.
   The measure affects new sales, and ``is indicative of a fact that
the world is running out of extra cotton for export,'' Whitten said.
``If there are any buyers ... they will have to come to the United
States. If they come to us, they'll have to pay our price.''
   Rumors of Chinese purchases of U.S. cotton also supported prices,
he said.
   Cotton prices settled .67 cent to 1.60 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at 59.19 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures prices dipped at the Chicago Board of
Trade, but analysts said supportive fundamentals helped temper
losses.
   Farmer selling of corn and soybeans increased slightly over the
weekend and helped pressure prices, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader
for Dean Witter Reynolds, Inc. in Chicago.
   Buying was further discouraged by the notion that a selloff is
due after the markets' strong gains last week, he said.
   In the wheat pit, traders sold after a rumored sale of export
bonus wheat to the Chinese on Friday failed to materialize.
   But anticipation that a deal with China still may be on tap, and
expectations that the Soviet Union may make a bid on corn helped
curb the decline in those pits, Lespinasse said.
   Wheat prices settled { cent to 2{ cents lower, with the contract
for delivery in March at $4.32{ a bushel; corn settled 1{ cents
lower to { cent higher, with the March contract at $2.70 a bushel;
oats were 3\ cents to 7 cents lower, with March at $1.99\ a bushel;
and soybeans were 3} cents lower to 1} cents higher, with March at
$7.57\ a bushel.
   Credit-tightening by the Federal Reserve late last week,
indicative of its ``commitment to an anti-inflationary stance,''
continued to pressure gold and silver prices at the New York
Commodity Exchange, said George Anagnos, a New York analyst with
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc.
   The Federal Reserve on Friday raised its discount rate, the loan
fee it charges to member banks, from 6.5 percent to 7 percent, in a
move designed to curb inflation by slowing down the economy.
   ``It's not an environment where investors are actively seeking to
add to their portfolio of precious metals,'' Anagnos said.
   Gold prices settled $2.80 to $3 lower, with the contract for
delivery in March at $387.30 a troy ounce; silver prices were 4.7
cents to 8 cents lower, with March at $5.85 a troy ounce.
   Cattle prices dipped, hog prices were mostly lower and pork
bellies were mostly higher in lackluster trading at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Pork belly prices remained firm despite the Agriculture
Department's monthly cold storage report, released after the close
of trading Friday, indicating frozen pork belly supplies were
slightly greater than had been expected.
   Anticipation of the report sparked a selloff Friday, which in
turn encouraged short-covering Monday, analysts said.
   Live cattle settled unchanged to .40 cent lower, with the
contract for delivery in April at 78.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle
were .27 cent to .70 cent lower, with the March contract at 82.92
cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to .05 cent higher,
with April at 43.47 cents a pound; and pork bellies settled .18 cent
lower to 1.12 cents higher, with March at 37.82 cents a pound.
   Crude oil prices were mixed in trading at the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   Crude oil settled 13 cents lower to 7 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in April at $18.14 a barrel; heating oil was
.22 cent lower to .92 cent higher, with March at 52.65 cents a
gallon; unleaded gas was .20 cent lower to .56 cent higher, with
March at 50.67 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
