<FIRST>r f AM-SteelRestraints     02-27 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Restraints,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Foreign Steel Dumping without Restraints, Executive Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign companies are ready to resume large-scale
steel dumping on the United States if voluntary restraints on the
amount of imported steel are not continued this fall, the president
of the USS Division of USX Corp. said Monday.
   Thomas Graham said a 5-year renewal of the limits, wich expire
Sept. 30, is essential for the U.S. steel industry to continue its
2-year financial comeback.
   ``We can't afford to become giddy,'' he said. ``Two years of
profitability doesn't offset five years of losses.''
   Graham said the U.S. steel industry earned more than $2 billion
in 1988 and about $900 million the year before. But between 1982 and
1986, the industry lost $12 billion, an average of $2.4 billion
annually.
   The voluntary restraint agreement, which began in 1984, limits
the amount of imported finished steel to 18.5 percent of the U.S.
market, among other things. The American Institute for Imported
Steel said steel made overseas and shipped to the United States
accounts for about 17.7 percent of the market, below the current VRA
limit.
   Despite that, Graham said, the U.S. government must hold the line
on the amount of steel coming into the country.
   ``There's no doubt that foreign producers will revert to
large-scale dumping of heavily subsidized steel'' without a VRA
renewal, he said. ``We certainly can't tolerate a return to past
practices.''
   In the third quarter of 1984, shortly before the VRA began,
imported steel made up just more than 30 percent of the U.S. market.
   Graham's comments came during the opening day of the week-long
annual congress of the Society of Automotive Engineers.
   The imported steel association, which supports an elimination of
the VRA or a 2-year extension instead of five years, has claimed
that the limits reduce supply thereby increasing prices for U.S.
steel, something the domestic steelmakers like.
   But Graham dismissed that contention.
   ``It's not an issue of protectionism,'' he said. ``It's an issue
of legal trading practices.''
   Graham also said Pittsburgh-based USS is prepared to file legal
papers if the Bush administration rejects a VRA extension.
   ``We need enabling legislation from Congress before the Bush
administration has the ability to act,'' he said. ``We see ourselves
as prudent businessmen.''
   He declined to say when any legal moves may be taken, adding that
an earlier agreement barred the industry from filing trade
litigation while a VRA was in effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
