<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1814EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-National-Hitachi     02-27 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-National-Hitachi,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Sells Unit to Hitachi-GM For $398 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Semiconductor Corp. said
Monday it is selling its mainframe computer business to Hitachi Ltd.
and a unit of General Motors Corp. for $398 million, a deal one
analyst called ``a great move'' for National.
   In announcing the sale, the chip maker said it broke off a
tentative agreement with a Dutch company, Memorex Telex NV, for half
of National Advanced Systems.
   Hitachi, which will own 80 percent of the joint venture that is
buying National Advanced Systems, will gain a greater presence in
the U.S. mainframe market dominated by International Business
Machines Corp., analysts said.
   National Advanced Systems sells Hitachi's mainframe computers and
data-storage systems. The deal will tighten that relationship and
allow Hitachi greater flexibility in building the $900
million-a-year business.
   The GM unit, Dallas-based Electronic Data Systems Corp., also is
expected to become a stronger competitor to IBM and Digital
Equipment Corp. in helping companies assemble computer systems.
   ``From National's standpoint, it's a very positive move,'' said
John McManus of Thomas McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York. ``They
get all the money up front. I think it's a great move.''
   Jim Hammons, a computer industry analyst with the Sierra Group in
Tempe, Ariz., also said the deal was good for National Semiconductor
but wondered what it would do with all the money.
   ``National couldn't do anything with NAS,'' Hammons said. ``So
now that they've gotten rid of it, the question is what are they
going to do with the cash that they couldn't do with the company?''
   National Semiconductor spokeswoman Mary Coady said the money
would go toward the retirement of debt and working capital.
   National Semiconductor announced on Jan. 9 that it had signed a
letter of intent to sell a half-interest in National Advanced
Systems to Memorex Telex NV of Amsterdam, the Netherlands, for $250
million and 4 million shares of Memorex Telex stock. National
Semiconductor would have continued to own the rest.
   Complications in financing the deal arose and the letter of
intent expired earlier this month, freeing National Semiconductor to
consider other offers, said George Bragg, a spokesman for Memorex
Telex's U.S. subsidiary in Tulsa, Okla.
   Under the new deal, which is also subject to a definitive
agreement, National Advanced Systems is to be bought by a
joint-venture company created by Hitachi and GM's EDS unit.
   Hitachi will own 80 percent of the company and EDS will own 20
percent, Hitachi spokesman Osamu Naito said. He said the partners
will in turn sell the European portion of the business, which
accounts for less than half its revenue, to Comparex Information
Systems GmbH for an undisclosed price.
   Comparex, based in Mannheim, West Germany, is Hitachi's other
sales outlet for mainframe computers in Europe, Naito said.
   National Semiconductor has been selling off businesses to raise
cash to build up its core business of computer chips, which has been
losing money.
   The financing problem that spoiled the deal with the Dutch
company came when there was more difficulty than expected in having
National Advanced Systems raise $250 million in cash, which would
have been paid to National Semiconductor, Bragg said.
   He said Memorex Telex proposed other deals but could not match
the all-cash offer from Hitachi and EDS.
   National Advanced Systems is Hitachi's largest distributor of
mainframe computers that run the same programs as IBM's big
mainframes. It has 2,200 employees worldwide, including 1,200 in the
United States.
   ``We think it's a good situation for us,'' said Coady. ``I just
want to make it clear that we did not accept the Hitachi deal
because we thought it was a better deal, in a vaccuum. We continued
to negotiate with Memorex Telex well after the letter of intent had
expired.''
   A definitive agreement is expected by the end of March and the
deal should be closed by the end of April, Coady said. National
Semiconductor then would be pared down to about 35,000 employees
worldwide. The company announced 2,000 layoffs earlier this year.
</TEXT>
