<DOCNO> AP890227-0328 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 1900EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Empire     02-27 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Empire,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Empire Seeks Nearly $1 Billion From FSLIC In Recapitalization Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators would contribute $905
million to Empire of America's recapitalization under a proposal
made by the troubled thrift Monday.
   The application to the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp.
is a first of its kind, but industry observers said others will
follow.
   ``We've been predicting this would happen for some time,'' said
Douglas Faucette, an attorney for a coalition of banking interests.
``Unless executives are totally asleep at the helm, they'll all be
doing this.''
   If the request was approved by the FSLIC, the bank said it would
be able to raise an additional $670 million through private
investors and could return immediately to profitability.
   The recapitalization plan ``demonstrates a means whereby the cost
to taxpayers of the resolution of the entire thrift crisis could be
significantly reduced,'' Empire Chairman Paul Willax said.
   Empire, the nation's 12th-largest thrift with $11.3 billion in
assets, is asking the FSLIC for the cash as a replacement for
non-cash assistance the FSLIC gave Empire when it took over 13
failing savings and loans from 1981 to 1986.
   Although the bank is currently solvent, officials are afraid that
federal proposals to save the thrift industry will reduce the value
of its non-cash assistance. If that happened Empire would have
difficulty raising money to meet new capital requirements.
   ``This is not at all an act of desperation but rather an act of
anticipation,'' Willax said.
   The proposal shows the investment community still has confidence
in Empire, he said.
   Willax said the $670 million commitment of Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., a New York investment firm, is the largest amount of private
money involved in the recapitalization of any thrift.
   In a statement issued by Drexel Burnam, senior vice president
Stephen Joseph called the Empire proposal ``an exciting, innovative
effort that will result in a strengthened institution.''
   Faucette, an attorney for Financial Assistance Inequity Coalition
in Washington, said Drexel Burnam's involvement was an indication
that the financial community has doubts about government proposals
to help the thrift industry.
   ``The feeling is that the government has gone and changed the
rules for insititutions like Empire and that this sort of thing (the
Empire plan) may be the only way out,'' he said.
   Faucette said, however, he doubted the federal officials would
approve of the idea.
   ``You can imagine the type of reception you'd get when you ask
for nearly a billion dollars,'' he said.
</TEXT>
