<FIRST>r f AM-SEC-Prime     02-27 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Prime,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Probing Prime Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal securities regulators have questioned MAI
Basic Four Inc. about possible violations of stock margin
requirements in its hostile bid for Prime Computer Inc., MAI Basic
confirmed Monday.
   The inquest comes after several Massachusetts congressmen pressed
the Securities and Exchange Commission to step up enforcement of
margin requirements, passed after the 1929 stock market crash to
limit borrowing for speculative purposes.
   ``We've had informal, cordial and cooperative discussions with
SEC staff,'' MAI Basic spokesman Peter Rosenthal said in a
statement. ``We've answered all of the questions they've asked of
us. And as we previously stated in our offering documents, we
believe our offer complies with all margin rules.''
   The SEC declined to comment on whether it was conducting a
preliminary inquiry or a full-scale investigation.
   David A. Smith, an aide to Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said
the SEC began interviewing MAI officials last week.
   ``What I know is that there is an inquiry going on,'' he said.
``How intensive, I couldn't tell you.''
   MAI Basic, a Tustin, Calif.-based computer firm controlled by New
York investor Bennett S. LeBow, has offered $20 per share for Prime,
a much larger computer maker headquartered in Natick.
   In court documents, MAI said it would finance the takeover with
an $875 million corporate borrowing and $650 million in secured
loans. Under the margin rules, at least 50 percent of the $650
million must be secured by collateral, such as cash, tangible assets
or stock.
   ``They have put up stock, but the question is, what is the actual
value of the stock, and is it really secured by assets of MAI,''
said Howard Homonoff, an aide to Rep. Joseph Markey, D-Mass.
   U.S. District Judge A. David Mazzone temporarily enjoined MAI's
bid last month, ruling that the firm had not adequately disclosed
its financial arrangements with the investment firm Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   A hearing in the case is scheduled Thursday at the 1st U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Boston.
   Mazzone late last year said MAI's bid raised serious questions
about compliance with margin requirements. Following the judge's
comments, Frank, Markey and Kennedy wrote letters to the SEC and the
Federal Reserve Board urging stiffer application of the margin rules
in takeover battles.
   Aides to the Massachusetts congressmen said that despite the boom
in highly leveraged corporate takeovers, the SEC has not brought an
enforcement action on margin rules recently.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
