<FIRST>r f AM-Cold-Vegetables 1stLd-Writethru f0131 02-27 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cold-Vegetables, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0131,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmers Survey Damage; But Plenty of Produce Available</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd graf to include Georgia losses; INSERTS
1 graf after 4th graf, `Florida's $1.3 billion ...,' to add comment from
citrus officials; picks up 5th graf pvs, `But the ...'. Also moved on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's vegetable farmers surveyed heavy
losses in tomato, cucumber and potato crops Monday after a
record-setting cold snap, but an industry official predicted
shoppers will not face shortages.
   Wayne Crain, marketing-production manager for the Florida Fruit
and Vegetable Association, predicted that supermarket consumers
would see little loss of volume in popular vegetables such as
lettuce and tomatoes despite damage to winter and early spring crops.
   ``We still have plenty of product. We're still in the market,''
Crain said.
   Just north of the Florida border, Georgia peach growers reported
more than $9 million in losses from the cold. However, Tommy Irvin,
commissioner of the Georgia Department of Agriculture, said, ``It
seems right now we didn't come out hardly as bad as we first
appeared.''
   Florida's $1.3 billion citrus crop reportedly came through the
frosty weather Thursday, Friday and Saturday nearly unscathed. The
temperatures did not stay low enough long enough to affect fruit on
the trees.
   Citrus industry officials said it would be about two weeks before
they determine how the damage to early blooms and new growth would
affect next year's crop.
   But the state's $1.1 billion vegetable industry did not fare as
well.
   With vegetable losses undetermined, most industry leaders said it
was too early to tell what effect the freezing temperatures Thursday
through Saturday might have on consumer prices.
   ``There would have to be vast losses in all sectors before any
real impact is made at the retail level,'' Agriculture Commissioner
Doyle Conner said.
   Officials estimated the tomato crops were the hardest hit, with
half of the crop wiped out in the Ruskin-Palmetto area around St.
Petersburg, 25 percent to 35 percent of the crop lost in southwest
Florida around Naples and Immokalee and 10 percent of the crop
damaged in south Florida around Homestead.
   Tomatoes are the state's largest produce crop, valued at almost
$490 million in 1987, the latest figures available from the U.S.
Department of Agriculture.
   About 70 percent of the cucumbers were reported damaged, and
production was set back until May for most of the crop, which is
grown primarily in the southern part of the state at this time of
year.
   Spring potatoes in the Palatka-St. Augustine area in
north-central Florida were heavily damaged.
   There was lesser damage to corn, peppers, squash, watermelons and
leafy vegetables, mainly in north and central Florida.
   Crops along the East Coast were not badly affected.
   ``I just see a crazy, mixed-up spring marketing,'' Crain said.
``With replanting, everything (production) is being pushed back. And
with the weather moderating in the spring, we're going to see a lot
of crops overlapping.''
   Some of Florida's traditional late-winter crops also will be
overlapping with the same varieties from southeastern states, Texas
and the Southwest in April, May and June, he said.
   Mexico, which is a major competitor in tomatoes, peppers,
cucumbers, squash and eggplant, was hit hard by freezing
temperatures in January and its production is also way down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
