<HEAD>Infotechnology Agrees To Buy Remaining Shares Of Company Controlling
UPI</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Infotechnology Inc. said Monday it had agreed to
buy the shares it does not already own in WNW Group Inc., which
controls the management of the news agency United Press
International.
   Infotech agreed to buy the WNW Group stake in exchange for nearly
2 million shares of restricted Infotech common stock.
   Completion of the deal is subject to completing necessary
documentation.
   ``We are pleased with the progress at UPI in its first year of
operation under WNW Group,'' Earl Brian, chairman of Infotech, said
in a statement.
   He said UPI will continue to operate independently, but that both
Infotechnology and UPI ``will benefit greatly from UPI's direct
interaction among Infotech companies.''
   The statement was released late Monday afternoon, and several
calls placed to Infotechnology for elaboration on the announcement
went unanswered.
   Paul Steinle, president of WNW Group, was quoted in the statement
as calling the deal a ``further vote of confidence in the future of
United Press International.''
   WNW Group, based in Washington, D.C., has managed UPI since
February 1988 under terms of an irrevocable proxy from controlling
UPI shareholder Mario Vazquez-Rana, a Mexican publisher.
   Infotechnology, based in New York, has interests in information
technology and invests in medical and scientific ventures. It also
owns the Financial News Network.
   UPI said it lost about $16 million in 1988 compared with a $25
million loss in 1987. Steinle has said he expects the 81-year-old
news agency to begin turning a profit by the end of 1989.
