<FILEID>AP-NR-02-27-89 2336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-PatentFight     02-27 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Patent Fight,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules for Genentech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has overturned a Scripps
Clinic patent on an anti-bleeding substance for hemophiliacs,
allowing rival firms to continue work on their own versions of the
potentially lucrative product.
   The ruling by U.S. District Judge William Schwarzer, made public
Monday, was a victory for the biotechnology company Genentech Inc.
and the license-holder of its patent, Miles Laboratories Inc., which
otherwise could have been forbidden from further work and possibly
required to pay damages.
   ``This does a great deal to lift the clouds of uncertainty in an
area that's previously been uncertain,'' said Bud Modersbach, a
lawyer for Cutter Biological, a division of Miles. Cutter has begun
human clinical trials of a version of the substance produced through
gene-splicing but has not obtained federal approval to market it.
   Eugene Moroz, a lawyer for Scripps Clinic and Research
Foundation, said the company disagreed with the ruling and was
hopeful of a reversal by the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal
Circuit.
   The ruling does not prevent the Rorer Group Inc., which is
licensed to use the Scripps patent, from continuing to sell a
blood-clotting product called Monoclate. But if the decision is
upheld, it will prevent Rorer from dominating ``a very large
market,'' said Stephen Raines, Genentech's vice president for
patents.
   The substance is an artificial form of a clotting protein called
Human Factor VIII, found in healthy people but missing in
hemophiliacs.
   Scripps' version of the purified protein, made from human and pig
blood plasma, received a patent in 1982 and an updated patent in
1984. Genentech, using different technology, produced a similar
protein in 1984.
   Schwarzer ruled in 1987 that Genentech had violated Scripps'
patent, but he refused to halt work by Genentech. The judge said
hemophiliacs could suffer if development of the product was
hampered, and also noted Genentech's challenge to the validity of
Scripps' patent.
   In his latest ruling, Schwarzer found:
   _Scripps' patent did not describe, or adequately identify, the
particular substance or antibody that would make the substance work.
   _The updating of the patent by the U.S. Patent Office in 1985 was
based on Scripps' claim that its 1982 patent application contained
inadvertent errors. Schwarzer said the claim of error, which is
required for expansion of a patent, were ``incredible'' coming from
experienced patent lawyers.
   _Scripps was guilty of ``inequitable conduct'' for submitting
patent claims based on a purified product when one of its samples
contained 50 percent contamination.
   _A 1979 doctoral thesis by a student researcher had publicly
revealed the process of producing a clotting product with the same
potency as the Scripps patent. That finding would invalidate several
aspects of the patent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
